{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Mymm9oKNt3h9hGCiqu1f6m","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# StepML Round 2: Findings Summary\n     2→\n     3→**Date:** 2026-02-27\n     4→**Branch:** `stepml-experiments`\n     5→**Scope:** Two ideas tested across 10 experiments (4 models x 3 workloads, no reasoning). Both ideas extended Round 1's per-step modeling to include BLIS E2E validation, per-request KV features (ProgressIndex-derived), and generalization testing.\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## 1. Problem Recap\n    10→\n    11→Achieve **<10% workload-level E2E mean error** across 12 experiments (4 models x 3 workloads) by improving any or all of the 5 `LatencyModel` methods. The baseline to beat is **115.0% mean E2E error** from per-model linear regression.\n    12→\n    13→Round 1 established that per-experiment XGBoost achieves 34% per-step MAPE but never validated through BLIS E2E simulation. Round 2's mandate was to close that loop: validate through BLIS, add per-request KV features, and test generalization.\n    14→\n    15→---\n    16→\n    17→## 2. What We Tried\n    18→\n    19→### Idea 1: Bayesian Calibration (2-Regime Piecewise Linear)\n    20→\n    21→**Approach:** Split steps into 2 regimes (decode-only vs mixed-batch), fit Ridge regression per regime with ProgressIndex-derived KV features (kv_sum, kv_max, kv_mean), and plan to jointly calibrate all 5 LatencyModel methods via Bayesian optimization.\n    22→\n    23→| Sub-Hypothesis | Target | Result | Status |\n    24→|---|---|---|---|\n    25→| H1: Piecewise-linear StepTime | <30% per-step MAPE | **87.4%** | **Refuted** |\n    26→| H2: Joint Bayesian optimization | <15% E2E mean | Not run | **Blocked** (H1 too inaccurate) |\n    27→| H4: LOMO cross-validation | <80% per-step MAPE | **148.8%** | **Refuted** |\n    28→| H5: LOWO cross-validation | <40% per-step MAPE | **155.4%** | **Refuted** |\n    29→\n    30→### Idea 2: Regime-Switching Ensemble (3-Regime Ridge)\n    31→\n    32→**Approach:** Split steps into 3 regimes (decode-only / mixed-light with prefill<256 / mixed-heavy with prefill>=256), fit Ridge per regime with KV features, validate through BLIS E2E simulation, and calibrate secondary LatencyModel methods from ground-truth lifecycle data.\n    33→\n    34→| Sub-Hypothesis | Target | Result | Status |\n    35→|---|---|---|---|\n    36→| H1: Regime Ridge per-step MAPE | <15% weighted | **64.4%** | **Not met** |\n    37→| H2: BLIS E2E validation | <10% mean | **427.8%** | **Not met** |\n    38→| H3: Secondary method calibration | >=5pp E2E gain | **0.0pp** | **Refuted** |\n    39→| H4: LOMO (cross-model) | <80% avg MAPE | **108.6%** | **Refuted** |\n    40→| H5: LOWO (cross-workload) | <25% avg MAPE | **117.4%** | **Refuted** |\n    41→\n    42→---\n    43→\n    44→## 3. What Worked\n    45→\n    46→### 3.1 Overhead Floor Mechanism (Best Single Contribution)\n    47→\n    48→The `max(overhead, compute)` step-time floor is the most effective accuracy mechanism discovered. Per-model overhead constants:\n    49→\n    50→| Model | Overhead (us) |\n    51→|---|---|\n    52→| Llama-2-7B (TP1) | 3,897 |\n    53→| CodeLlama-34B (TP2) | 6,673 |\n    54→| Llama-2-70B (TP4) | 8,029–8,203 |\n    55→| Mixtral-8x7B (TP2) | 9,125 |\n    56→\n    57→The overhead floor handles the decode-dominated regime (77.9% of steps) by clamping small-batch predictions to the real cycle time. This mechanism alone produces **5/10 experiments with ITL <10%**, proving that for decode-dominant workloads, the overhead floor is more important than the regression model.\n    58→\n    59→### 3.2 ITL Prediction (33.6% Mean, 5/10 Under 10%)\n    60→\n    61→ITL directly reflects step-time + overhead quality. Per-experiment ITL:\n    62→\n    63→| Experiment | ITL Error |\n    64→|---|---|\n    65→| mixtral-roleplay | **0.7%** |\n    66→| mixtral-codegen | **2.1%** |\n    67→| 7b-roleplay | **4.0%** |\n    68→| mixtral-general | **8.7%** |\n    69→| 70b-hf-codegen | **10.7%** |\n    70→| 70b-roleplay | **10.3%** |\n    71→| 70b-general | 23.5% |\n    72→| 34b-general | 80.3% |\n    73→| 34b-codegen | 95.9% |\n    74→| 34b-roleplay | 100.1% |\n    75→\n    76→The 7B and Mixtral models are essentially solved for ITL. The 70B models are close. CodeLlama-34B is the sole outlier.\n    77→\n    78→### 3.3 LOMO Improvement: 23.6x Over Round 1\n    79→\n    80→Round 2 LOMO: 108.6% avg MAPE vs Round 1 LOMO: 2,559.7%. The regime structure plus per-request KV features dramatically improve cross-model transfer, even though the absolute target (<80%) was not met. The 34B holdout fold (63.4% MAPE) shows that interpolation between model scales is feasible.\n    81→\n    82→### 3.4 Mixtral Generalizes Exceptionally Well\n    83→\n    84→Mixtral is consistently the best-performing model across all metrics:\n    85→- Per-step MAPE: 16.6% (best of all models)\n    86→- LOWO: 19.1% avg (below 25% target)\n    87→- ITL: 0.7%, 2.1%, 8.7% (all under 10%)\n    88→\n    89→MoE architectures appear to have more regular compute scaling. A single universal Mixtral model works across all workloads.\n    90→\n    91→### 3.5 Per-Model Overhead Constants Are Stable\n    92→\n    93→Overhead values derived independently in Round 2 match values from earlier Round 2 analysis, confirming they are stable properties of the model+GPU+TP configuration rather than workload-dependent artifacts.\n    94→\n    95→---\n    96→\n    97→## 4. What Failed and Why\n    98→\n    99→### 4.1 KV Features Are Counter-Productive in Raw Linear Space\n   100→\n   101→**The central thesis of Round 2 — that ProgressIndex-derived KV features would improve prediction — was refuted.**\n   102→\n   103→Both ideas showed KV features *degrade* per-step accuracy:\n   104→- Idea 1: +3.6pp worse (87.4% with KV vs 83.8% without)\n   105→- Idea 2: +20.5pp worse (64.4% with KV vs 43.9% without)\n   106→\n   107→**Root cause:** KV feature magnitudes (kv_sum ranging 0 to 64,000+) cause Ridge coefficient instability. Small Ridge alpha values amplify noise from extreme KV values; large alpha values suppress all KV signal. Only Mixtral benefited from KV features (-5.4pp), likely due to its MoE architecture's different KV-to-compute relationship.\n   108→\n   109→**This does NOT mean KV features are useless — it means raw linear regression cannot handle their dynamic range.** Feature scaling (StandardScaler), log-transform, or nonlinear models would likely fix this.\n   110→\n   111→### 4.2 TTFT Errors Are Catastrophic (31,906% Mean)\n   112→\n   113→TTFT errors of thousands to hundreds-of-thousands percent indicate a systematic mismatch between BLIS's request lifecycle and the real system, not a step-time modeling problem. The TTFT error is the dominant contributor to E2E error (427.8%). Likely causes:\n   114→- Workload spec generation producing mismatched request arrival patterns\n   115→- BLIS prefill/queueing behavior diverging from real vLLM scheduling\n   116→- Request injection timing not matching ground-truth arrival distribution\n   117→\n   118→### 4.3 Mixed-Heavy Regime Is Empty\n   119→\n   120→Only 74/77,816 steps (0.1%) have prefill >= 256 tokens. The 3-regime design effectively collapses to 2 regimes on this dataset (which excludes reasoning workloads). The expected ~4.4% share from the 16-experiment Round 1 data does not hold for the 10-experiment Round 2 data.\n   121→\n   122→### 4.4 Secondary Methods Contribute Zero\n   123→\n   124→H3's ablation showed that calibrating SchedulingProcessingTime and QueueingTime constants (200–400 us) produced **exactly 0.0 percentage points** of E2E improvement. When the dominant error source (StepTime or workload spec) is off by orders of magnitude, microsecond-level corrections are invisible.\n   125→\n   126→### 4.5 CodeLlama-34B Is Consistently the Worst Model\n   127→\n   128→34B shows the highest per-step MAPE (99.2%), worst BLIS E2E (2,901% for general), and outlier LOMO/LOWO errors. This model may have batch dynamics that differ significantly from the Llama-2 family.\n   129→\n   130→### 4.6 Cross-Workload Transfer Did Not Improve\n   131→\n   132→LOWO regressed slightly from Round 1 (117.4% vs 109.7%). The regime structure was expected to provide workload-agnostic modeling but did not. The 70B model dominates the error (293.8%), suggesting large-model workload shifts have outsized impact.\n   133→\n   134→---\n   135→\n   136→## 5. Data Characteristics Learned (Round 2)\n   137→\n   138→### 5.1 Step Duration vs Cycle Time\n   139→\n   140→`step.duration_us` captures GPU forward pass only (~70–7,000 us). Real step cycle time includes CPU overhead: scheduling, synchronization, memory management. The overhead ranges 4–9ms per model and is derived from: `GT_ITL_us - mean_compute_us`.\n   141→\n   142→### 5.2 Overhead Integration Approaches (All Tested)\n   143→\n   144→| Approach | Result |\n   145→|---|---|\n   146→| Additive (compute + overhead) | Phase transition — under-capacity to overload with no stable point |\n   147→| Log-space cycle time | Exponential amplification — batch-size coefficients get multiplied, not added |\n   148→| **Max floor (best)** | `step_time = max(overhead, compute)` — handles memory-bound→compute-bound crossover |\n   149→| Floor + cap | `max(overhead, min(compute, 3*overhead))` prevents exponential blowup from expm1 |\n   150→\n   151→### 5.3 Log-Space (expm1) Pitfalls\n   152→\n   153→- KV features: coefficient 0.0001 x 64,000 = 6.4 in log-space → 601x multiplier\n   154→- Prefill tokens: coefficient 0.06 x 500 = 30 in log-space → exp(30) = absurd\n   155→- Safe ONLY for decode-only batches with small coefficients\n   156→\n   157→### 5.4 Raw Linear for BLIS E2E\n   158→\n   159→Use `use_log_target=False` for all regimes destined for BLIS consumption. Per-step MAPE is ~448% but irrelevant — the overhead floor handles decode-dominated steps, and the linear model only matters for large-batch compute-bound steps.\n   160→\n   161→### 5.5 Phase Distribution (10-Experiment Dataset)\n   162→\n   163→| Regime | Steps | Share |\n   164→|---|---|---|\n   165→| Decode-only (prefill = 0) | 60,613 | 77.9% |\n   166→| Mixed-light (0 < prefill < 256) | 17,129 | 22.0% |\n   167→| Mixed-heavy (prefill >= 256) | 74 | 0.1% |\n   168→\n   169→### 5.6 Step Data Is ~10% Sampled\n   170→\n   171→Not every step is logged in lifecycle data. Step observations come from OpenTelemetry tracing at ~10% sample rate.\n   172→\n   173→---\n   174→\n   175→## 6. Comparison of Ideas\n   176→\n   177→| Metric | Idea 1 (2-regime) | Idea 2 (3-regime) | Winner |\n   178→|---|---|---|---|\n   179→| Per-step MAPE (with KV) | 87.4% | 64.4% | Idea 2 |\n   180→| Per-step MAPE (no KV) | 83.8% | 43.9% | Idea 2 |\n   181→| BLIS E2E mean error | Not tested | 427.8% | — |\n   182→| ITL mean error | Not tested | 33.6% (5/10 <10%) | Idea 2 |\n   183→| LOMO avg MAPE | 148.8% | 108.6% | Idea 2 |\n   184→| LOWO avg MAPE | 155.4% | 117.4% | Idea 2 |\n   185→| KV feature contribution | -3.6pp (harmful) | -20.5pp (harmful) | Neither |\n   186→\n   187→**Idea 2 is strictly better but both fail all primary targets.** The 3-regime structure, overhead floor, and BLIS integration pipeline from Idea 2 are the foundation to build on.\n   188→\n   189→---\n   190→\n   191→## 7. Per-Experiment Leaderboard (BLIS E2E)\n   192→\n   193→Best results achieved in Round 2 (Idea 2 with regime Ridge + overhead floor):\n   194→\n   195→| Experiment | E2E Error | TTFT Error | ITL Error | Baseline E2E |\n   196→|---|---|---|---|---|\n   197→| 34b-roleplay | **3.3%** | 282.7% | 100.1% | 136.5% |\n   198→| mixtral-roleplay | 50.8% | 77.2% | **0.7%** | 141.9% |\n   199→| mixtral-codegen | 51.5% | 76.5% | **2.1%** | 141.3% |\n   200→| 7b-roleplay | 52.5% | 78.4% | **4.0%** | 86.1% |\n   201→| 70b-hf-codegen | 55.7% | 77.7% | 10.7% | — |\n   202→| 70b-roleplay | 55.6% | 77.9% | 10.3% | — |\n   203→| mixtral-general | 554.6% | 44,464% | **8.7%** | 138.5% |\n   204→| 70b-general | 182.7% | 12,567% | 23.5% | 111.8% |\n   205→| 34b-codegen | 370.2% | 30,425% | 95.9% | 135.4% |\n   206→| 34b-general | 2,901.1% | 230,931% | 80.3% | 132.3% |\n   207→\n   208→**Observations:**\n   209→- Only 1/10 experiments meets <10% E2E target (34b-roleplay, likely coincidental)\n   210→- TTFT errors are the dominant E2E contributor — they're 2-3 orders of magnitude worse than ITL\n   211→- ITL is well-solved for 7B, Mixtral, and partially for 70B\n   212→- CodeLlama-34B \"general\" is catastrophic across all metrics\n   213→\n   214→---\n   215→\n   216→## 8. Binding Constraints for Round 3\n   217→\n   218→### 8.1 TTFT/Workload Spec Mismatch (PRIMARY — Blocking E2E Target)\n   219→\n   220→The 31,906% mean TTFT error is the single biggest obstacle to <10% E2E. This is NOT a step-time problem — it's a simulation-fidelity problem in how BLIS generates and schedules requests compared to the real system. Until TTFT is addressed, no step-time improvement can achieve the E2E target.\n   221→\n   222→**Actionable:** Diagnose whether the workload spec generator, BLIS request injection timing, or BLIS prefill scheduling is the root cause. Compare BLIS-simulated request arrival/scheduling timestamps against ground-truth lifecycle data.\n   223→\n   224→### 8.2 KV Feature Scaling (SECONDARY — Blocking Per-Step Improvement)\n   225→\n   226→Per-request KV features (the key Round 1 recommendation) hurt accuracy due to numerical instability in raw linear space. The features themselves are not wrong — the regression formulation is.\n   227→\n   228→**Actionable:** Apply StandardScaler within the Ridge pipeline, or use log-transformed features (not target), or switch to a model that handles large feature ranges (tree ensemble, or feature-scaled Ridge).\n   229→\n   230→### 8.3 CodeLlama-34B Anomaly (SECONDARY)\n   231→\n   232→34B is the worst model by a wide margin across all metrics. The specific batch dynamics causing this need investigation (batch-size distributions, step-time outliers, prefill/decode ratios).\n   233→\n   234→**Actionable:** Profile 34B's step-time distribution, batch-size histogram, and KV utilization compared to other models. Determine if it's a data quality issue, architecture anomaly, or model-specific coefficient problem.\n   235→\n   236→### 8.4 Mixed-Heavy Regime Sparsity (TERTIARY)\n   237→\n   238→The 3-regime design collapses to 2 effective regimes because only 0.1% of steps are mixed-heavy. This regime needs more data (perhaps from reasoning workloads, which were excluded from Round 2 data) or the threshold needs lowering.\n   239→\n   240→---\n   241→\n   242→## 9. Successful Techniques to Preserve\n   243→\n   244→1. **Overhead floor (`max(overhead, compute)`)** — the most impactful single technique\n   245→2. **Per-model training** — mandatory due to 3+ OOM step-time variation\n   246→3. **Regime separation** (decode-only vs mixed) — provides distinct modeling contexts\n   247→4. **Temporal train/test split** — prevents autocorrelation leakage\n   248→5. **BLIS E2E validation pipeline** (Idea 2's `validate_e2e.py` + `validate_blis.py`) — the infrastructure for running BLIS with custom coefficients and comparing against ground truth\n   249→6. **Per-model overhead derivation** from ground-truth ITL\n   250→7. **Secondary method constant extraction** from lifecycle data (even though they contributed 0pp, the extraction pipeline is correct)\n   251→\n   252→---\n   253→\n   254→## 10. Eliminated Approaches (Do Not Repeat)\n   255→\n   256→| Approach | Why It Failed | Round |\n   257→|---|---|---|\n   258→| Global models (all experiments) | 3+ OOM step-time scale variation | R1 |\n   259→| Analytical FLOPs decomposition without per-request KV | decode_attention = 0, structurally incomplete | R1 |\n   260→| Correction factors on incomplete backbone | Pathological compensation (factor=39.5 on zero signal) | R1 |\n   261→| Pure-phase analysis | Only 6 pure-prefill steps exist under chunked prefill | R1 |\n   262→| **Raw KV features in linear regression** | kv_sum up to 64K causes Ridge coefficient instability | R2 |\n   263→| **2-regime piecewise linear** | Too coarse — mixed-batch heterogeneity too high for one linear regime | R2 |\n   264→| **Joint Bayesian optimization** | Cannot compensate for structural model errors | R2 |\n   265→| **Secondary method calibration alone** | 200-400us corrections invisible against 100%+ E2E errors | R2 |\n   266→| **Log-space target with large features** | expm1 causes exponential blowup with KV/prefill coefficients | R2 |\n   267→\n   268→---\n   269→\n   270→## 11. Summary for Future Ideation\n   271→\n   272→### What the data tells us after 2 rounds:\n   273→\n   274→1. **The overhead floor is the workhorse** — ITL is solved for 4/5 models without any sophisticated step-time model\n   275→2. **TTFT errors dominate E2E** — the step-time model is nearly irrelevant to E2E accuracy until TTFT is fixed\n   276→3. **KV features have signal but need proper scaling** — they're counter-productive in raw linear space, productive when the model handles their dynamic range\n   277→4. **Per-model calibration is non-negotiable** — step-time scales vary 3+ orders of magnitude\n   278→5. **The 3-regime + overhead floor architecture is sound** — it just needs (a) TTFT fix, (b) feature scaling, (c) 34B investigation\n   279→\n   280→### What Round 3 should prioritize (ordered):\n   281→\n   282→1. **Diagnose and fix the TTFT mismatch** — this is the gating issue for E2E. Without it, no step-time improvement matters.\n   283→2. **Apply feature scaling to KV features** — StandardScaler, log-transform, or tree models. The features themselves are available and meaningful; only the regression formulation is wrong.\n   284→3. **Investigate CodeLlama-34B** — determine if the anomaly is data, architecture, or coefficients.\n   285→4. **Lower mixed-heavy threshold or add reasoning data** — the 256-token boundary sees only 74 steps. Consider 64 or 128 tokens, or include reasoning workloads.\n   286→\n   287→### Hard constraints to respect:\n   288→- Per-model training mandatory (LOMO still >80%)\n   289→- Features must be computable from `[]*Request` with `ProgressIndex` (Go integration)\n   290→- Prediction latency <1ms per step\n   291→- Pure-Go implementation (no Python/ONNX runtime)\n   292→\n   293→---\n   294→\n   295→## 12. Cumulative Round History\n   296→\n   297→| Round | Best E2E Error | Best ITL Error | Key Achievement | Primary Blocker |\n   298→|---|---|---|---|---|\n   299→| R1 | Not tested (Python-only) | Not tested | 34% per-step MAPE with XGBoost (2x better than blackbox) | No BLIS integration, no E2E validation |\n   300→| **R2** | **427.8% mean** (1/10 <10%) | **33.6% mean** (5/10 <10%) | Overhead floor + BLIS pipeline + per-request KV features | **TTFT mismatch (31,906%)** dominates E2E; KV features counter-productive in linear space |\n   301→\n   302→---\n   303→\n   304→## 13. Reproducibility\n   305→\n   306→All code is in `hypotheses/h-stepml/round2/`:\n   307→\n   308→```\n   309→round2/\n   310→├── FINDINGS_ROUND2.md              # This file\n   311→├── idea-1-bayesian-calibration/\n   312→│   ├── FINDINGS_SUMMARY.md\n   313→│   ├── h1-piecewise-steptime/      # 2-regime Ridge (run.sh, train_piecewise.py)\n   314→│   ├── h2-joint-bo-calibration/    # Blocked (bo_calibrate.py ready but not run)\n   315→│   ├── h4-model-generalization/    # LOMO (lomo_cv.py)\n   316→│   └── h5-workload-generalization/ # LOWO (lowo_cv.py)\n   317→└── idea-2-regime-ensemble/\n   318→    ├── FINDINGS_SUMMARY.md\n   319→    ├── h1-kv-regime-models/        # 3-regime Ridge (train_regime_ridge.py)\n   320→    ├── h2-blis-e2e-validation/     # BLIS E2E (validate_e2e.py)\n   321→    ├── h3-secondary-method-calibration/ # Ablation (calibrate_secondary.py)\n   322→    ├── h4-model-generalization/    # LOMO (lomo_cv.py)\n   323→    └── h5-workload-generalization/ # LOWO (lowo_cv.py)\n   324→```\n   325→\n   326→**Dependencies:** Python 3, pandas, scikit-learn, scipy, numpy\n   327→**Data:** `eval/ground_truth/` (77,816 steps from 10 experiments)\n   328→**BLIS integration:** `sim/latency/stepml.go` (Go StepTime with floor/cap logic)\n   329→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01MJDQQTTrnYuP6hsespnndP","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"efc86e3f-e1dd-4711-9cce-60a4888953b5"}
