{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01FMy5fRN8Y2HQyRGMAxMJaf","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Idea 1: Bayesian Calibration — Findings Summary\n     2→\n     3→**Date:** 2026-02-27\n     4→**Overall Verdict:** All hypotheses refuted. The 2-regime piecewise-linear approach is structurally weaker than Idea 2's 3-regime ensemble.\n     5→\n     6→---\n     7→\n     8→## Executive Summary\n     9→\n    10→Idea 1 proposed a piecewise-linear StepTime model with two regimes (decode-only vs mixed-batch), ProgressIndex-derived KV features, and joint Bayesian optimization of all 5 LatencyModel methods against BLIS E2E error. Four hypotheses were designed; three were executed (H1, H4, H5) and one was blocked (H2).\n    11→\n    12→**Every executed hypothesis was refuted.** The core structural limitation is the 2-regime split: lumping all mixed-batch steps (1 prefill token through 2000+) into a single linear regime creates too much heterogeneity for a linear model. Additionally, KV features provided zero-to-negative contribution in this formulation, and the approach was worse than Round 1 for workload generalization.\n    13→\n    14→---\n    15→\n    16→## Hypothesis Scorecard\n    17→\n    18→| # | Hypothesis | Target | Result | Status |\n    19→|---|-----------|--------|--------|--------|\n    20→| H1 | Piecewise-linear StepTime (<30% MAPE) | <30% per-step MAPE | **87.4%** | **Refuted** |\n    21→| H2 | Joint BO of all 5 methods (<15% E2E) | <15% E2E mean error | Not run | **Blocked** |\n    22→| H4 | LOMO cross-validation (<80% MAPE) | <80% per-step MAPE | **148.8%** | **Refuted** |\n    23→| H5 | LOWO cross-validation (<40% MAPE) | <40% per-step MAPE | **155.4%** | **Refuted** |\n    24→\n    25→---\n    26→\n    27→## Key Results\n    28→\n    29→### H1: Piecewise-Linear StepTime — Per-Model Quality\n    30→\n    31→The base model achieves 87.4% weighted MAPE across 5 model+TP configurations, barely improving over the 2-feature blackbox baseline (89.7%). Performance varies dramatically by model:\n    32→\n    33→| Model | Piecewise MAPE | Blackbox MAPE | Improvement |\n    34→|-------|---------------|--------------|-------------|\n    35→| Mixtral-8x7B (TP2) | 18.6% | 20.7% | +2.1 pp |\n    36→| Llama-2-7B (TP1) | 38.2% | 40.2% | +2.0 pp |\n    37→| Llama-2-70B-HF (TP4) | 88.4% | 90.6% | +2.2 pp |\n    38→| Llama-2-70B (TP4) | 94.7% | 86.8% | -7.9 pp |\n    39→| CodeLlama-34B (TP2) | 168.5% | 176.9% | +8.4 pp |\n    40→\n    41→**KV features hurt overall** (-3.6 pp) — the model without KV features achieved 83.8% MAPE vs 87.4% with KV. For 2/5 models (7B, Mixtral), Ridge assigned zero weight to KV features. For the 70B models, KV features increased error.\n    42→\n    43→### H4: Cross-Model Transfer (LOMO) — 17x Better than Round 1\n    44→\n    45→| Held-Out Model | MAPE | MSPE | Key Observation |\n    46→|---------------|------|------|----------------|\n    47→| CodeLlama-34B | 53.9% | Mixed | Best fold — 34B interpolates between 7B and 70B |\n    48→| Llama-2-70B | 146.5% | +105%/+177% | Heavily overpredicted |\n    49→| Llama-2-7B | 187.0% | -185%/-205% | **Negative predictions** — catastrophic scale mismatch |\n    50→| Mixtral-8x7B (MoE) | 207.8% | +152%/+312% | Dense-to-MoE transfer fails completely |\n    51→\n    52→Average 148.8% MAPE (target: <80%), but still 17.2x better than Round 1's LOMO baseline (2559.7%). The improvement comes from regime separation, but the model lacks scale normalization needed for cross-architecture transfer.\n    53→\n    54→### H5: Cross-Workload Transfer (LOWO) — Worse than Round 1\n    55→\n    56→| Model | general | codegen | roleplay | Avg |\n    57→|-------|---------|---------|----------|-----|\n    58→| Mixtral | 15.8% | 21.4% | 26.6% | **21.3%** |\n    59→| 34B | 43.4% | 292.4% | 107.2% | 147.7% |\n    60→| 70B | 145.9% | 265.2% | 480.6% | 297.3% |\n    61→| 7B | — | — | — | (no data) |\n    62→\n    63→Grand average 155.4% MAPE (target: <40%), which is 0.7x of Round 1's LOWO (109.7%) — a **regression**. Mixtral is the sole success (21.3%), proving MoE architectures generalize across workloads. Dense models fail because workload-specific batch-composition distributions shift between training and test.\n    64→\n    65→### H2: Bayesian Optimization — Not Run\n    66→\n    67→Blocked because H1's base model (87.4% MAPE) is too inaccurate for BO to compensate. BO can tune overhead and secondary constants but cannot fix batch-composition-dependent prediction errors. The ~66-133 hours of compute is unjustified. Idea 2's comparable test (H3) already showed secondary methods contribute minimally to E2E error.\n    68→\n    69→---\n    70→\n    71→## Root Causes of Failure\n    72→\n    73→### 1. The 2-regime split is structurally insufficient\n    74→\n    75→The decode-only / mixed-batch boundary is too coarse. The mixed-batch regime (22.1% of steps) spans steps with 1 prefill token to 2000+ prefill tokens. This range includes both memory-bound micro-prefills and compute-bound large prefills — fundamentally different operations that a single linear model cannot represent.\n    76→\n    77→**Evidence:** Idea 2's 3-regime split (decode-only / mixed-light / mixed-heavy at 256-token boundary) achieves substantially different MAPE for mixed-light vs mixed-heavy, confirming the heterogeneity.\n    78→\n    79→### 2. KV features require finer regime segmentation to be useful\n    80→\n    81→KV features (kv_sum, kv_max, kv_mean) have extremely high variance (0 to 64,000+) relative to step-time range (70-7,000 us). In the 2-regime formulation:\n    82→- Ridge assigns zero weight to KV features for Mixtral and 7B (features are noise)\n    83→- For 70B models, the tiny KV coefficients amplify noise at extreme KV values\n    84→- The blackbox's `decode_tokens` is a better proxy because it correlates with batch size and has lower variance\n    85→\n    86→With Idea 2's mixed-light/mixed-heavy split, KV features become informative because the regime boundary constrains the feature space.\n    87→\n    88→### 3. Raw linear regression has inherent per-step MAPE limitations\n    89→\n    90→`step.duration_us` captures GPU forward pass only (median ~200-3000 us). The batch-feature-to-time relationship is approximately log-linear, not linear. Raw linear regression:\n    91→- Overpredicts small-batch steps (can produce negative predictions)\n    92→- Underpredicts large-batch steps\n    93→- Achieves high per-step MAPE even when the overhead floor makes E2E accuracy acceptable\n    94→\n    95→This is consistent with Round 2's earlier finding that raw linear per-step MAPE is ~448% but irrelevant for BLIS E2E.\n    96→\n    97→### 4. Cross-model transfer requires scale normalization\n    98→\n    99→LOMO fails because step-time scales differ by 5-10x across models (7B: ~150us, 70B: ~1000us). The linear model learns coefficients scaled for the training models. Without normalizing features by model-specific constants (parameter count, FLOPS per token), the predictions are catastrophically wrong for held-out models at different scales.\n   100→\n   101→### 5. Cross-workload transfer requires feature diversity or nonlinearity\n   102→\n   103→LOWO fails because different workloads create different batch-composition distributions. A linear model on 4 features cannot capture these distributional shifts. Round 1's 30-feature XGBoost performed better (109.7% vs 155.4%) because it had more features and nonlinear capacity to absorb distribution shifts.\n   104→\n   105→---\n   106→\n   107→## Comparison with Idea 2 (3-Regime Ensemble)\n   108→\n   109→| Metric | Idea 1 (2-regime) | Idea 2 (3-regime) | Winner |\n   110→|--------|-------------------|-------------------|--------|\n   111→| H1 per-step MAPE | 87.4% | Comparable (per-model) | Idea 2 |\n   112→| KV feature contribution | -3.6 pp (harmful) | Positive (mixed-heavy KV helps) | Idea 2 |\n   113→| LOMO avg MAPE | 148.8% | (refuted at similar level) | Comparable |\n   114→| LOWO avg MAPE | 155.4% | (refuted at ~similar level) | Comparable |\n   115→| Feature count per regime | 4 | 7-8 | Idea 2 |\n   116→| Regime boundary | Binary (prefill=0 vs >0) | Ternary (0 / <256 / >=256) | Idea 2 |\n   117→\n   118→**Verdict:** Idea 2's 3-regime approach is strictly better. The additional regime boundary and richer feature set provide meaningful improvements, especially for mixed-batch prediction and KV feature utilization.\n   119→\n   120→---\n   121→\n   122→## Surprises and Positive Findings\n   123→\n   124→Despite overall refutation, several valuable insights emerged:\n   125→\n   126→1. **Mixtral generalizes exceptionally well.** Both LOMO (Fold 4 aside) and LOWO (21.3% avg) show that MoE architectures have more regular step-time scaling that transfers across contexts. A single Mixtral StepML model can serve any workload type.\n   127→\n   128→2. **LOMO interpolation works for 34B.** Holding out CodeLlama-34B (which falls between 7B and 70B in scale) yields 53.9% MAPE — suggesting that cross-model transfer via interpolation is feasible with proper scale normalization.\n   129→\n   130→3. **Per-model overhead is consistent with Round 2 findings.** The overhead values (3.9ms for 7B, 6.7ms for 34B, 8.0-8.2ms for 70B, 9.1ms for Mixtral) match prior observations, providing independent validation.\n   131→\n   132→4. **\"General\" workload is the easiest holdout.** In LOWO, holding out the \"general\" workload yields the lowest average MAPE (68.4%), likely because \"general\" has the most diverse batch compositions (averaging effect), making it the most representative of a mixture of training workloads.\n   133→\n   134→---\n   135→\n   136→## Recommendations\n   137→\n   138→### For StepML Research\n   139→\n   140→1. **Abandon the 2-regime piecewise-linear approach.** The 3-regime split (Idea 2) is strictly better and should be the foundation for further work.\n   141→2. **Investigate feature normalization for LOMO.** The 34B interpolation result (53.9%) suggests that dividing features by model-specific constants (parameter count, FLOPS per token) could make cross-model transfer viable.\n   142→3. **Explore MoE-specific models.** Mixtral's consistent success across all experiments suggests that MoE architecture warrants a dedicated StepML model family.\n   143→4. **Do not invest in BO until per-step quality improves.** Joint BO cannot compensate for structural model errors. Focus on improving the base StepTime model first.\n   144→\n   145→### For BLIS Deployment\n   146→\n   147→1. **Use per-model StepML coefficients** — cross-model and cross-workload transfer are not production-ready.\n   148→2. **The overhead floor (`max(overhead, compute)`) remains the primary accuracy mechanism.** Per-step MAPE is poor, but the overhead floor makes E2E accuracy acceptable for standard workloads.\n   149→3. **Ship Mixtral with a single universal model.** Its LOWO results (21.3%) justify deploying one model for all Mixtral workloads.\n   150→\n   151→---\n   152→\n   153→## Data and Artifacts\n   154→\n   155→| Hypothesis | Output Directory | Key Files |\n   156→|-----------|-----------------|-----------|\n   157→| H1 | `h1-piecewise-steptime/output/` | `piecewise_results.csv`, `piecewise_summary.json`, `artifacts/*.json` |\n   158→| H2 | `h2-joint-bo-calibration/output/` | (not run — script ready at `bo_calibrate.py`) |\n   159→| H4 | `h4-model-generalization/output/` | `lomo_per_step_results.csv`, `lomo_summary.json`, `lomo_artifacts/*.json` |\n   160→| H5 | `h5-workload-generalization/output/` | `lowo_per_step_results.csv`, `lowo_summary.json`, `lowo_artifacts/*.json` |\n   161→\n   162→## Reproducing All Experiments\n   163→\n   164→```bash\n   165→# H1: Base model training (~5 min)\n   166→cd hypotheses/h-stepml/round2/idea-1-bayesian-calibration/h1-piecewise-steptime && ./run.sh\n   167→\n   168→# H4: LOMO cross-validation (~15 min)\n   169→cd hypotheses/h-stepml/round2/idea-1-bayesian-calibration/h4-model-generalization && ./run.sh\n   170→\n   171→# H5: LOWO cross-validation (~15 min)\n   172→cd hypotheses/h-stepml/round2/idea-1-bayesian-calibration/h5-workload-generalization && ./run.sh\n   173→\n   174→# H2: BO calibration (~66-133 hours, not recommended)\n   175→cd hypotheses/h-stepml/round2/idea-1-bayesian-calibration/h2-joint-bo-calibration && ./run.sh\n   176→```\n   177→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01MJDQQTTrnYuP6hsespnndP","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"a9f9f378-4e8b-4bab-889f-b46897ae1293"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_019Ep4wPcTTZt59iJHrAddom","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Idea 2: Regime-Switching Ensemble — Findings Summary\n     2→\n     3→**Date:** 2026-02-27\n     4→**Data:** 77,816 steps from 10 experiments (4 models x 3 workloads; no reasoning workloads in this dataset)\n     5→**Models:** Llama-2-7B (TP1), Llama-2-70B (TP4), CodeLlama-34B (TP2), Mixtral-8x7B (TP2)\n     6→**Workloads:** general, codegen, roleplay\n     7→\n     8→---\n     9→\n    10→## Executive Summary\n    11→\n    12→Idea 2's regime-switching Ridge ensemble was designed to exploit the insight that batch computation falls into distinct regimes (decode-only, mixed-light, mixed-heavy) with different feature-performance relationships. The approach uses ProgressIndex-derived KV features to capture per-request memory footprint — a key missing signal identified in Round 1.\n    13→\n    14→**Bottom line:** On the current ground-truth data (10 experiments, 77K steps), Idea 2 fails to meet its primary targets. Per-step MAPE is 64.4% (target was <15%), BLIS E2E error is 427.8% (target was <10%), and generalization tests both fail. However, ITL prediction remains reasonable at 33.6%, and LOMO shows a 23.6x improvement over Round 1's catastrophic baseline. The results point to specific fixable problems (KV feature instability, workload spec generation for TTFT) rather than a fundamental flaw in the approach.\n    15→\n    16→---\n    17→\n    18→## Hypothesis Results\n    19→\n    20→| # | Hypothesis | Status | Key Metric | Target | Actual |\n    21→|---|-----------|--------|-----------|--------|--------|\n    22→| H1 | Regime Ridge per-step MAPE | **Not met** | Weighted MAPE | <15% | 64.4% |\n    23→| H2 | BLIS E2E validation | **Not met** | Mean E2E error | <10% | 427.8% |\n    24→| H3 | Secondary method calibration | **Refuted** | E2E improvement | >=5pp | 0.0pp |\n    25→| H4 | LOMO (cross-model) | **Refuted** | Avg MAPE | <80% | 108.6% |\n    26→| H5 | LOWO (cross-workload) | **Refuted** | Avg MAPE | <25% | 117.4% |\n    27→\n    28→---\n    29→\n    30→## H1: Regime-Specific Ridge Training\n    31→\n    32→### Per-Model Step Overhead\n    33→\n    34→Step duration in training data captures GPU forward pass only. The real step cycle time includes CPU overhead (scheduling, sync, memory management). Overhead is derived from ground-truth ITL:\n    35→\n    36→| Model | Overhead (us) |\n    37→|-------|--------------|\n    38→| Llama-2-7B (TP1) | 3,897 |\n    39→| CodeLlama-34B (TP2) | 6,673 |\n    40→| Llama-2-70B (TP4) | 8,029-8,203 |\n    41→| Mixtral-8x7B (TP2) | 9,125 |\n    42→\n    43→### Regime Distribution\n    44→\n    45→| Regime | Steps | Share |\n    46→|--------|-------|-------|\n    47→| decode_only (prefill == 0) | 60,613 | 77.9% |\n    48→| mixed_light (0 < prefill < 256) | 17,129 | 22.0% |\n    49→| mixed_heavy (prefill >= 256) | 74 | 0.1% |\n    50→\n    51→Mixed-heavy has only 74 steps — effectively untestable. This is a key difference from the HYPOTHESIS.md expectation of ~4.4% (~5,400 steps), indicating the new ground-truth data has fundamentally different prefill characteristics.\n    52→\n    53→### Per-Model Regime MAPE (Test Set)\n    54→\n    55→| Model | Weighted MAPE | decode_only | mixed_light | Best alpha |\n    56→|-------|--------------|-------------|-------------|------------|\n    57→| Llama-2-7B (TP1) | **36.2%** | 36.6% (r=0.530) | 32.4% (r=0.590) | 1000/0.01 |\n    58→| Mixtral-8x7B (TP2) | **16.6%** | 18.3% (r=0.610) | 13.4% (r=0.872) | 0.01/0.01 |\n    59→| CodeLlama-34B (TP2) | **99.2%** | 65.8% (r=0.785) | 179.9% (r=0.714) | 1000/0.01 |\n    60→| Llama-2-70B-HF (TP4) | **84.4%** | 91.7% (r=0.702) | 67.9% (r=0.697) | 0.01/1000 |\n    61→| Llama-2-70B (TP4) | **93.3%** | 112.2% (r=0.854) | 59.3% (r=0.758) | 1000/1000 |\n    62→\n    63→### Model Comparison\n    64→\n    65→| Model Type | Weighted MAPE |\n    66→|-----------|--------------|\n    67→| Regime-specific Ridge (with KV) | **64.4%** |\n    68→| Single global Ridge (all features) | 93.5% |\n    69→| Blackbox baseline (2 features) | **46.9%** |\n    70→| Regime Ridge (no KV features) | **43.9%** |\n    71→\n    72→### KV Feature Ablation: Negative Contribution\n    73→\n    74→KV features **hurt** per-step MAPE by 20.5 percentage points (64.4% with KV vs. 43.9% without). Per-model breakdown:\n    75→\n    76→| Model | With KV | Without KV | Delta |\n    77→|-------|---------|-----------|-------|\n    78→| Llama-2-7B | 36.2% | 30.1% | +6.1pp worse |\n    79→| Mixtral-8x7B | 16.6% | 22.0% | -5.4pp better |\n    80→| CodeLlama-34B | 99.2% | 55.5% | +43.7pp worse |\n    81→| Llama-2-70B-HF | 84.4% | 48.2% | +36.2pp worse |\n    82→| Llama-2-70B | 93.3% | 68.3% | +25.0pp worse |\n    83→\n    84→KV features only help Mixtral. For all dense models, KV features degrade performance. The numerical overflow warnings during Ridge training (divide-by-zero, overflow in matmul) confirm that KV feature magnitudes (kv_sum up to 64,000+) cause coefficient instability in raw linear space.\n    85→\n    86→### Diagnosis\n    87→\n    88→1. **Mixed-heavy regime is empty** (74 steps vs. expected ~5,400). The 256-token prefill threshold sees almost no steps. This means the 3-regime split collapses to 2 effective regimes.\n    89→2. **KV features cause numerical instability.** Large kv_sum values produce overflow during Ridge CV grid search. Alpha=1000 often wins for large models, indicating severe regularization is needed to tame unstable coefficients.\n    90→3. **The blackbox 2-feature baseline outperforms all KV-augmented models.** This suggests the KV features as implemented add noise rather than signal — possibly because ProgressIndex KV proxies are poorly correlated with actual batch-level compute cost in this dataset.\n    91→\n    92→---\n    93→\n    94→## H2: BLIS E2E Validation\n    95→\n    96→### Per-Experiment Results\n    97→\n    98→| Experiment | E2E Error | TTFT Error | ITL Error |\n    99→|-----------|-----------|------------|-----------|\n   100→| 7b-roleplay | 52.5% | 78.4% | **4.0%** |\n   101→| 70b-general | 182.7% | 12,567% | 23.5% |\n   102→| 70b-hf-codegen | 55.7% | 77.7% | **10.7%** |\n   103→| 70b-roleplay | 55.6% | 77.9% | **10.3%** |\n   104→| mixtral-codegen | 51.5% | 76.5% | **2.1%** |\n   105→| mixtral-general | 554.6% | 44,464% | **8.7%** |\n   106→| mixtral-roleplay | 50.8% | 77.2% | **0.7%** |\n   107→| 34b-general | 2,901.1% | 230,931% | 80.3% |\n   108→| 34b-codegen | 370.2% | 30,425% | 95.9% |\n   109→| 34b-roleplay | **3.3%** | 282.7% | 100.1% |\n   110→\n   111→### Aggregate Metrics\n   112→\n   113→| Metric | Mean | Experiments <10% |\n   114→|--------|------|-----------------|\n   115→| E2E error | 427.8% | 1/10 (34b-roleplay) |\n   116→| TTFT error | 31,906% | 0/10 |\n   117→| ITL error | 33.6% | 5/10 |\n   118→\n   119→### Pattern Analysis\n   120→\n   121→- **ITL is the best metric** (33.6% mean, 5/10 under 10%). ITL directly reflects step-time prediction quality + overhead floor, confirming the core modeling approach works for decode-dominant workloads.\n   122→- **TTFT errors are catastrophic** (thousands to hundreds-of-thousands percent). This indicates the BLIS simulation's prefill + queueing timing is fundamentally mismatched with the ground truth. The workload spec generation or request injection timing may be wrong.\n   123→- **\"general\" workloads consistently worst** (70b-general 182.7%, mixtral-general 554.6%, 34b-general 2901.1%). The \"general\" workload likely has longer prefill sequences and more variable batch dynamics.\n   124→- **CodeLlama-34B is the worst model** across all metrics. Per-step MAPE for 34b was already 99.2% (worst in H1).\n   125→\n   126→---\n   127→\n   128→## H3: Secondary Method Calibration\n   129→\n   130→### Extracted Constants\n   131→\n   132→| Model | Queue-to-Schedule (us) | Schedule-to-First-Token (us) |\n   133→|-------|----------------------|---------------------------|\n   134→| Llama-2-7B (TP1) | 202 (p25=187, p75=219) | 15,884 |\n   135→| Llama-2-70B (TP4) | 415 (p25=265, p75=550) | 40,869 |\n   136→| Llama-2-70B-HF (TP4) | 281 (p25=220, p75=316) | 37,372 |\n   137→| CodeLlama-34B (TP2) | 291 (p25=246, p75=510) | 30,100 |\n   138→| Mixtral-8x7B (TP2) | 353 (p25=275, p75=577) | 37,952 |\n   139→\n   140→### Ablation Result\n   141→\n   142→| Config | Mean E2E | Mean TTFT | Mean ITL |\n   143→|--------|----------|-----------|----------|\n   144→| A: StepTime-only | 427.8% | 31,905.8% | 33.6% |\n   145→| B: + Secondary methods | 427.8% | 31,905.7% | 33.6% |\n   146→| **Delta** | **+0.0pp** | **+0.0pp** | **+0.0pp** |\n   147→\n   148→**Verdict: REFUTED.** The secondary method constants (200-400 us) are negligible compared to E2E errors of hundreds to thousands of percent. When the dominant error source (StepTime or workload spec) is off by orders of magnitude, microsecond-level corrections cannot matter.\n   149→\n   150→---\n   151→\n   152→## H4: LOMO (Leave-One-Model-Out)\n   153→\n   154→### Per-Fold Results\n   155→\n   156→| Fold | Held-Out Model | Per-Step MAPE | BLIS E2E Mean |\n   157→|------|---------------|---------------|---------------|\n   158→| 1 | CodeLlama-34B | 63.4% | 657.0% |\n   159→| 2 | Llama-2-70B | 197.6% | 797.6% |\n   160→| 3 | Llama-2-7B | 41.2% | BLIS failed |\n   161→| 4 | Mixtral-8x7B | 132.3% | 253.7% |\n   162→\n   163→**Average LOMO MAPE: 108.6%** (target: <80%) — **REFUTED**\n   164→\n   165→### Per-Regime MAPE (Across Folds)\n   166→\n   167→| Regime | Average MAPE | Range |\n   168→|--------|-------------|-------|\n   169→| decode_only | 88.9% | 27.8-200.4% |\n   170→| mixed_light | 185.7% | 55.0-320.6% |\n   171→| mixed_heavy | 243.1% | 67.5-473.9% |\n   172→\n   173→### Comparison to Round 1\n   174→\n   175→- Round 1 LOMO: 2,559.7% average MAPE\n   176→- Round 2 LOMO: 108.6% average MAPE\n   177→- **Improvement: 23.6x** (significant, but still above 80% threshold)\n   178→\n   179→### Diagnosis\n   180→\n   181→The 70B fold is the worst (197.6%) because 70B is the largest model with highest absolute step times. Cross-model transfer fails because step-time scale is model-dependent (determined by parameter count and TP degree). The Mixtral fold (132.3%) confirms that dense-to-MoE transfer remains challenging due to fundamentally different compute scaling.\n   182→\n   183→---\n   184→\n   185→## H5: LOWO (Leave-One-Workload-Out)\n   186→\n   187→### Per-Model LOWO MAPE\n   188→\n   189→| Model | Avg MAPE | Worst Fold |\n   190→|-------|----------|-----------|\n   191→| 7b | 25.6% | roleplay (31.1%) |\n   192→| 34b | 131.0% | roleplay (183.5%) |\n   193→| 70b | 293.8% | roleplay (420.0%) |\n   194→| Mixtral | 19.1% | roleplay (23.9%) |\n   195→\n   196→**Grand average LOWO MAPE: 117.4%** (target: <25%) — **REFUTED**\n   197→\n   198→### Per-Workload MAPE (Across Models)\n   199→\n   200→| Held-Out Workload | Avg MAPE | Range |\n   201→|-------------------|----------|-------|\n   202→| codegen | 123.1% | 18.7-265.1% |\n   203→| general | 67.4% | 14.8-145.4% |\n   204→| roleplay | 161.7% | 23.9-420.0% |\n   205→\n   206→### BLIS E2E on Held-Out Workloads\n   207→\n   208→| Held-Out Workload | Mean E2E Error | Mean ITL Error |\n   209→|-------------------|---------------|----------------|\n   210→| codegen | 163.5% | 36.8% |\n   211→| general | 273.0% | 16.4% |\n   212→| roleplay | 36.4% | 36.7% |\n   213→\n   214→### Comparison to Round 1\n   215→\n   216→- Round 1 LOWO: 109.7% average MAPE\n   217→- Round 2 LOWO: 117.4% average MAPE\n   218→- **Improvement: 0.9x** (no improvement — slightly worse)\n   219→\n   220→### Diagnosis\n   221→\n   222→Workload generalization is comparable to Round 1. The regime structure was expected to provide workload-agnostic computation modeling, but LOWO MAPE actually regressed slightly. The 70B model dominates the error average (293.8%), suggesting that for large models with complex batch dynamics, workload distribution shifts have outsized impact on predictions.\n   223→\n   224→---\n   225→\n   226→## Cross-Cutting Findings\n   227→\n   228→### 1. KV Features Are Counter-Productive in Raw Linear Space\n   229→\n   230→The central thesis of Idea 2 was that ProgressIndex-derived KV features would improve per-step prediction. On this ground-truth data, the opposite is true: KV features degrade per-step MAPE from 43.9% to 64.4%. The root cause is numerical instability — kv_sum values reaching 64,000+ cause Ridge coefficient overflow when alpha is small. Only Mixtral benefits from KV features (-5.4pp), possibly because its MoE architecture has a different KV-to-compute relationship.\n   231→\n   232→**Implication:** KV features need either (a) normalization/scaling before regression, (b) log-transform of features (not target), or (c) a non-linear model that handles large feature ranges gracefully.\n   233→\n   234→### 2. Mixed-Heavy Regime Is Empty\n   235→\n   236→Only 74 of 77,816 steps (0.1%) fall in the mixed-heavy regime (prefill >= 256). The original hypothesis expected ~4.4% based on 16 experiments with 4 workloads. The current 10-experiment dataset (3 workloads, no reasoning) has very few long-prefill batches. The 3-regime design is effectively a 2-regime design on this data.\n   237→\n   238→### 3. TTFT Errors Indicate Systematic Workload Spec or Simulation Mismatch\n   239→\n   240→TTFT errors of 31,906% cannot be explained by per-step model inaccuracy. These errors point to a mismatch in how the BLIS simulation generates/schedules requests vs. how the real system operates. Likely causes include:\n   241→- Workload spec generation (`build_workload_spec`) producing request arrival patterns that don't match the ground truth\n   242→- BLIS request queueing behavior differing from real vLLM queueing\n   243→- Prefill scheduling in BLIS (chunked prefill, request admission) not matching the real system's behavior\n   244→\n   245→### 4. ITL Remains the Most Accurate Metric\n   246→\n   247→Despite the per-step model limitations, ITL error is 33.6% mean with 5/10 experiments under 10%. This confirms that the overhead floor mechanism (`max(overhead, compute)`) effectively handles the decode-dominated continuous batching regime. The step-time model's accuracy matters less when the overhead floor dominates — which it does for small-to-medium batch sizes.\n   248→\n   249→### 5. CodeLlama-34B Is Consistently the Worst Model\n   250→\n   251→34B shows the highest per-step MAPE (99.2%), worst BLIS E2E (2,901% for general), and high generalization errors. This model may have batch dynamics that differ significantly from the Llama-2 family. Investigation into 34B-specific step-time distributions and batch size patterns is warranted.\n   252→\n   253→### 6. \"General\" Workloads Are Consistently Hard\n   254→\n   255→Across H2, the \"general\" workload produces the worst E2E errors for every model (182.7%, 554.6%, 2,901.1%). The \"general\" workload likely has more diverse batch compositions and longer prefill sequences, pushing the model into poorly-covered regions of the feature space.\n   256→\n   257→---\n   258→\n   259→## Recommendations for Next Steps\n   260→\n   261→1. **Fix KV feature scaling.** Normalize KV features (e.g., kv_sum / max_kv_blocks, kv_mean / max_seq_len) before regression, or use StandardScaler within the Ridge pipeline.\n   262→\n   263→2. **Investigate TTFT errors.** The 31,906% mean TTFT error is the dominant contributor to E2E error. Diagnose whether the workload spec, BLIS request injection, or prefill scheduling is the root cause.\n   264→\n   265→3. **Lower the mixed-heavy threshold or drop it.** With only 74 steps in mixed-heavy, consider a 2-regime model (decode-only vs. any-mixed) or lower the threshold to 64 or 128 tokens.\n   266→\n   267→4. **Investigate 34B-specific dynamics.** CodeLlama-34B accounts for disproportionate error. Check if its batch size distribution, step-time distribution, or KV utilization patterns differ qualitatively from other models.\n   268→\n   269→5. **Consider feature scaling for large models.** The 70B and 34B models show much higher MAPE than 7B and Mixtral. This may be because absolute feature values (kv_sum, decode_tokens) scale with model capacity, and raw linear regression cannot handle the scale differences without normalization.\n   270→\n   271→---\n   272→\n   273→## Output Artifacts\n   274→\n   275→| Hypothesis | Output Directory | Key Files |\n   276→|-----------|-----------------|-----------|\n   277→| H1 | `h1-kv-regime-models/output/` | `regime_ridge_results.csv`, `artifacts/*.json` |\n   278→| H2 | `h2-blis-e2e-validation/output/` | `e2e_validation_regime.csv`, `e2e_summary_regime.json` |\n   279→| H3 | `h3-secondary-method-calibration/output/` | `ablation_comparison.csv`, `ablation_summary.json`, `secondary_constants.json` |\n   280→| H4 | `h4-model-generalization/output/` | `lomo_per_step_results.csv`, `lomo_blis_e2e_results.csv`, `lomo_summary.json` |\n   281→| H5 | `h5-workload-generalization/output/` | `lowo_per_step_results.csv`, `lowo_blis_e2e_results.csv`, `lowo_summary.json` |\n   282→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01MJDQQTTrnYuP6hsespnndP","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"38a65392-d0ca-41c9-8dc8-845fdcfcfa96"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01BQHavMi7gpWQyxrDYQ82mR","type":"tool_result","content":"/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/BLIS-research/hypotheses/h-stepml/round1/idea-1-tree-ensemble/h1-features/FINDINGS.md\n/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/BLIS-research/hypotheses/h-stepml/round1/idea-1-tree-ensemble/h2-model/FINDINGS.md\n/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/BLIS-research/hypotheses/h-stepml/round1/idea-1-tree-ensemble/h3-generalization/FINDINGS.md\n/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/BLIS-research/hypotheses/h-stepml/round1/idea-2-analytical-decomposition/h1-features/FINDINGS.md\n/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/BLIS-research/hypotheses/h-stepml/round1/idea-2-analytical-decomposition/h2-model/FINDINGS.md\n/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/BLIS-research/hypotheses/h-stepml/round1/FINDINGS_ROUND1.md"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01MJDQQTTrnYuP6hsespnndP","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"8df3fd57-b30a-4cd3-bb0a-e6363dd89f0f"}
