{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01QKwbLQscxFZU1vyji6wNo1","type":"tool_result","content":"# DistServe Latency Model Analysis\n\nBased on the provided content, Appendix A details DistServe's latency modeling approach, though the complete formulas aren't fully included in this excerpt. Here's what I can extract:\n\n## Prefill Latency Modeling\n\nDistServe analyzes prefill computation by examining \"FLOPs and the number of memory accesses for prefill and decoding phases respectively\" to build execution time approximations. The prefill phase is characterized as typically compute-intensive, with execution time depending on input sequence length and batch composition.\n\n## Decode Latency Modeling\n\nFor decoding, the system recognizes it as \"heavily bandwidth-bound,\" making batching essential for GPU utilization. The latency model incorporates batch size effects, as larger batches improve throughput but affect per-token latency.\n\n## Queuing Theory Integration\n\nThe paper leverages M/D/1 queuing models to predict latency. For prefill, they use:\n\n\"Avg_TTFT = D + RD²/2(1-RD)\"\n\nwhere D represents execution time and R is arrival rate. This separates execution time (first term) from queuing delay (second term).\n\n## Handling Sequence Length and Batch Effects\n\nThe system profiles a critical threshold \"Lₘ\" representing the input length needed to saturate GPU compute. Beyond this, adding requests increases processing time proportionally rather than improving efficiency, directly impacting TTFT predictions.\n\nThe simulator validates against real profiling, achieving <2% error in SLO attainment predictions."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"152b6f02-f905-4bf3-be7d-59a3695ca47c"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01RusPZHzGGW8nxGEgRKQLt5","type":"tool_result","content":"# Revati's Technical Approach: Key Mechanisms\n\n## Step/Iteration Time Modeling\n\nRevati employs a **runtime prediction layer** accepting batch composition (prefill count, decode count, sequence lengths) and hardware specifications to estimate kernel durations. The system extends analytical models from prior work with support for modern features like Mixture-of-Experts routing and optimized collectives.\n\n## Time-Warp Technique\n\nThe core innovation exploits a fundamental property of inference systems: \"GPU computation accounts for 90-95% of total execution time, with CPU overhead remaining minimal.\" Rather than executing GPU kernels, Revati performs virtual time jumps—fast-forwarding by predicted durations while preserving causal semantics.\n\nThe system uses a **barrier-based coordination protocol** where:\n- Actors (request dispatchers, GPU workers) request time jumps to a central Timekeeper\n- The Timekeeper advances virtual time to the minimum requested target across all actors\n- This minimum-advancement rule preserves causality—no actor jumps past intended time\n- Multiple barrier rounds handle staggered completion times\n\n## Addressing Per-Step to End-to-End Gap\n\nRevati bridges this gap through **transparent device virtualization**. It intercepts CUDA API calls via LD_PRELOAD, presenting virtual devices to unmodified serving frameworks. This allows direct execution of real control-plane logic—scheduling, batching, memory management—capturing complex system behaviors without manual reimplementation.\n\n## Calibration Approach\n\nThe system bifurcates GPU memory allocations:\n- **Metadata buffers** (<4MB) receive real backing for control decisions\n- **Compute buffers** receive virtual pointers; operations become no-ops with predicted durations\n\nThis preserves temporal semantics while avoiding unnecessary data transfers.\n\n## Accuracy Results\n\nRevati achieves \"<5% prediction error across multiple models and parallelism configurations\" for both TTFT and TPOT metrics, while delivering \"5-17× faster than real GPU execution.\""}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"af9e6923-e294-468c-9d76-a45597779f75"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_019hEy7QqBxehzSMRG5RvPCF","type":"tool_result","content":"# Vidur's Execution Time Prediction Approach\n\n## Step/Iteration Time Modeling\n\nVidur models execution time by profiling individual computational steps. The system captures performance characteristics for different operation types, allowing it to predict how long each step will take during inference.\n\n## CDF-Based Profiling\n\nThe approach uses cumulative distribution functions (CDFs) to characterize step execution times. Rather than assuming deterministic durations, this probabilistic method captures the \"distribution of step latencies across different hardware configurations and input sizes,\" enabling more realistic predictions that account for variability.\n\n## Prefill vs. Decode Handling\n\nVidur distinguishes between two inference phases:\n- **Prefill phase**: Processing the initial prompt tokens\n- **Decode phase**: Generating subsequent tokens sequentially\n\nThe system profiles these phases separately since they have fundamentally different computational characteristics and bottlenecks.\n\n## Calibration Methodology\n\nThe calibration process involves running profiling experiments on target hardware to establish baseline performance curves. These curves are then used to extrapolate predictions for untested configurations, creating a transferable model of system behavior.\n\n## Accuracy for Key Metrics\n\nVidur achieves strong predictive accuracy for end-to-end latency metrics:\n- **Time to First Token (TTFT)**: Captures initial response delay\n- **Inter-Token Latency (ITL)**: Models token generation speed\n\n## Key Error Rates\n\nWhile specific error percentages weren't detailed in the provided excerpt, the system demonstrates reliable prediction across diverse model sizes and hardware configurations, with errors typically remaining within acceptable tolerances for serving optimization decisions."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"72afc17d-cdf7-4c7f-b2a7-acfd531f144b"}
