{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01FZ6iVNxv7jCgtTkwyqhJXG","type":"tool_result","content":"# Vidur's Step Time Prediction Methodology\n\nI apologize, but I cannot extract the specific technical details you've requested from the provided content. The document appears to be a PDF file containing binary-encoded streams and compressed objects that don't render as readable text in this format.\n\nTo accurately answer your questions about:\n- Vidur's profiling and prediction methodology\n- CDF-based interpolation approaches\n- Prefill vs. decode handling\n- TTFT and ITL accuracy metrics\n- Mixed batch processing\n- Calibration techniques\n\nI would need access to the actual readable research paper or technical documentation rather than the PDF's internal structure data.\n\n**Recommendation**: Please provide either:\n1. The plain text version of the Vidur paper\n2. A direct link to the published research\n3. Extracted sections focusing on the prediction methodology\n\nThis will allow me to give you precise, properly-quoted information about their specific error metrics and technical approaches."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"31390c23-a36b-499d-9eac-b9030804a072"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_014TLxEm6s8QW5eV89B31W1h","type":"tool_result","content":"I appreciate your request, but I need to be transparent: the content provided appears to be a PDF file encoded in binary/compressed format rather than readable text. The document shows PDF stream objects with FlateDecode compression, which I cannot meaningfully extract or analyze directly.\n\nTo properly address your questions about queueing theory frameworks for LLM inference, proposed models, batch serving approaches, and latency prediction challenges, I would need:\n\n1. **Plain text or properly decoded content** from the source document\n2. **A clearly readable version** of the paper you're referencing\n\n**What I can tell you generally about LLM serving and queueing theory:**\n\nResearchers have increasingly applied classical queueing models (particularly M/G/1 queues) to understand LLM inference systems because:\n- Requests arrive stochastically (Poisson-like patterns)\n- Service times vary significantly based on prompt/completion lengths\n- Batch processing creates complex scheduling dynamics\n\nKey challenges in this domain typically include:\n- **Time-to-first-token (TTFT) prediction** varies with batching strategies\n- **Step time variability** depends on sequence length and GPU utilization\n- **Coupling between request characteristics** and system state\n\nIf you can provide the paper in a readable format (plain text, markdown, or a proper PDF link), I'd be happy to extract the specific frameworks, models, and open problems they discuss while maintaining the citation standards you've requested."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"14244e36-4c09-47b0-873a-abc01cbae029"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_017xjYQ1JWcmD5Gf5q2bnacH","type":"tool_result","content":"# Sarathi-Serve's Iteration Time Modeling Approach\n\n## Step Time Prediction for Chunked Prefill\n\nSarathi-Serve predicts step times by modeling the computational characteristics of chunked prefill operations. The system accounts for how prefill work is divided into chunks and estimates the time each chunk requires based on sequence lengths and batch configurations.\n\n## Throughput-Latency Tradeoff Modeling\n\nThe system models the inherent tension between serving many requests simultaneously (throughput) versus responding quickly to individual requests (latency). By predicting iteration times across different batch sizes and prefill chunk sizes, Sarathi-Serve quantifies this tradeoff, enabling informed scheduling decisions that balance system objectives.\n\n## Stall-Free Batching Approach\n\nThe stall-free batching mechanism ensures continuous GPU utilization by carefully orchestrating when prefill and decode work are scheduled together. The approach prevents idle GPU cycles that would occur if the scheduler waited for one phase to complete before beginning another.\n\n## Prefill-Decode Interference Handling\n\nSarathi-Serve models how prefill operations compete with decode operations for shared GPU resources, particularly memory bandwidth and compute capacity. The prediction model captures performance degradation when these workloads execute concurrently, allowing the scheduler to make interference-aware batching decisions.\n\n## Latency Prediction Accuracy\n\nWhile specific accuracy metrics aren't detailed in the available content, Sarathi-Serve's iteration time modeling enables significantly improved scheduling efficiency by providing reliable predictions that guide batch composition and prefill chunking decisions."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"9013dec6-8f19-42f9-9d80-5db95fde8d99"}
