{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_018YCdr9gPGnSDBSKW4rJy23","type":"tool_result","content":"# Revati Accuracy Results: Key Findings\n\n## Specific Error Metrics\n\nRevati achieves \"<<5% prediction error\" across TTFT (Time-to-First-Token) and TPOT (Time-Per-Output-Token) metrics. Figure 6 demonstrates that predictions \"closely match\" actual execution distributions for both vLLM and SGLang across three model configurations (Llama-3.1-8B, Llama-3.1-70B, Qwen3-30B-A3B).\n\n## Comparison to Vidur\n\nThe paper doesn't directly compare end-to-end accuracy against Vidur. However, it notes that Vidur required only \"~150 lines of code\" for the original vLLM scheduler, highlighting how simulator maintenance became untenable as systems evolved—a problem Revati solves through direct execution rather than reimplementation.\n\n## CPU vs. GPU Execution Time\n\nA critical finding reveals the asymmetry enabling Revati's acceleration: \"GPU computation accounts for 90-95% of total execution time, with CPU overhead remaining minimal.\" This 5-10% CPU work creates the opportunity for time-acceleration without sacrificing fidelity, since \"the control plane's logic does not depend on the values computed by the GPU.\"\n\n## Key Lesson for Simulator Calibration\n\nThe fundamental insight is that serving systems are \"engineered to maximize GPU utilization while keeping CPU overhead minimal.\" Simulators attempting to capture performance must accurately model this temporal separation—CPU control logic happens rapidly, while GPU waits dominate actual execution time. Direct execution (Revati's approach) naturally captures these dynamics automatically, whereas reimplemented simulators risk subtle timing divergences."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"45ad1df0-786b-45dc-9497-74963deee84b"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01XAVSXSKXXfsg6Cb5FHxUEG","type":"tool_result","content":"# DistServe's Latency Modeling Approach\n\n## Prefill Execution Time\n\nDistServe models prefill execution using FLOPs and memory access counts. The system analyzes \"the FLOPs and the number of memory accesses for prefill and decoding phases respectively, and use a latency model to approximate the inference execution time.\" The prefill phase is characterized as typically compute-intensive when processing longer sequences.\n\n## Decoding Execution Time\n\nFor decoding, the model recognizes it as \"constrained by the GPU's memory bandwidth\" despite processing only one token per step. The execution time remains relatively constant per step since each decoding iteration generates a single token.\n\n## M/D/1 Queuing Formula for TTFT\n\nDistServe employs M/D/1 queue theory for single-device prefill analysis. Their foundational formula is:\n\n**Avg_TTFT = D + (RD²)/(2(1-RD))**\n\nwhere D represents constant execution time per request and R is the Poisson arrival rate. The first term captures execution time; the second represents queuing delay.\n\n## Profiling Step Times\n\nThe system uses \"prior knowledge of the workload's arrival process and input and output length distributions.\" DistServe \"fits a distribution from the history request traces and resamples new traces from the distribution as the input workload to the simulator.\"\n\n## Achieved Accuracy\n\nThe simulator demonstrates high accuracy: \"The error is less than 2% in all cases\" when comparing simulated versus actual SLO attainment across different request rates.\n\n## Per-Step to SLO Relationship\n\nDistServe handles this through discrete-event simulation incorporating queuing delays alongside execution times, ensuring step-level accuracy translates to end-to-end SLO predictions."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"48a6c7d8-465a-445a-821f-72b53cd4afee"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01MJDQQTTrnYuP6hsespnndP","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have all the key documents. Here is the comprehensive summary.\n\n---\n\n## StepML Research: Comprehensive Summary of Rounds 1 and 2\n\n### Goal\n\nReplace BLIS's 3-coefficient blackbox latency model (`step_time = beta0 + beta1*prefill_tokens + beta2*decode_tokens`) with a data-driven predictor achieving **<10% workload-level E2E mean error** across experiments (4 models x 4 workloads on H100 GPUs). The model must integrate into BLIS as a pure-Go `LatencyModel` implementation.\n\n**Training data:** 122,752 step-level observations (Round 1, 16 experiments) / 77,816 steps (Round 2, 10 experiments) from instrumented vLLM v0.15.1 with OpenTelemetry tracing at ~10% sample rate.\n\n---\n\n### Round 1 (2026-02-26): Python-Only Per-Step Modeling\n\n**Three ideas tested; two executed, one deferred.**\n\n#### Idea 1: Physics-Informed Tree Ensemble\n\n- **h1 (30 features + Ridge):** 92.1% avg per-step MAPE per-experiment; 301.7% global. Weakly supported for per-experiment only.\n- **h2 (XGBoost per-experiment):** **Best Round 1 result: 34.0% avg MAPE** -- 2x improvement over blackbox (70.4%). 5/16 experiments under 15% MAPE, zero regressions vs. blackbox.\n- **h3 (Cross-config generalization):** Catastrophic failure. LOMO (leave-one-model-out) = 2,559.7%, LOWO (leave-one-workload-out) = 109.7%.\n\n#### Idea 2: Analytical Decomposition + Learned Corrections\n\n- **h1 (4-component FLOPs decomposition):** 0/4 components exceeded 0.8 Pearson r with step duration. Structurally incomplete because `decode_attention_flops = 0` for all steps (per-request KV lengths unavailable).\n- **h2 (Multiplicative correction factors):** 78.7% MAPE -- *worse* than the 3-parameter blackbox (70.4%). Optimizer set `decode_attn_factor = 39.5` trying to amplify a zero signal.\n\n#### Idea 3: Evolutionary Synthesis (OpenEvolve)\n\nDeferred -- dependent on Idea 2's analytical components and required infrastructure not available.\n\n#### Round 1 Key Quantitative Results\n\n| Approach | Avg Per-Step MAPE | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Blackbox baseline | 70.4% | Per-experiment fit |\n| Ridge 30 features (per-exp) | 92.1% | Worse than blackbox |\n| XGBoost 30 features (per-exp) | **34.0%** | Best result (2x improvement) |\n| Analytical decomposition | 78.7% | Worse than blackbox |\n| Global Ridge | 301.7% | Catastrophic |\n| LOMO XGBoost | 2,559.7% | Catastrophic |\n\n#### Round 1: What Worked\n1. **Per-experiment XGBoost** with 30 physics-informed features provided a genuine 2x improvement.\n2. **Feature engineering insights:** Top features were KV cache state proxies (`kv_blocks_used`, `running_depth`, `kv_blocks_free`), indicating the model is bottlenecked by KV information quality.\n3. **Temporal train/test split** (60/20/20) prevents autocorrelation leakage.\n4. **Physics-informed interaction terms** (`prefill_x_decode`, `batch_size_x_kv_pressure`) added unique signal.\n\n#### Round 1: What Failed\n1. **Global models** -- step times span 3+ orders of magnitude across model configs (7B: 12-500us, 70B: 500-250,000us).\n2. **Cross-model generalization** -- features encode absolute values, not scale-normalized.\n3. **Analytical decomposition** -- structurally incomplete without per-request KV lengths; decode attention (the dominant cost for 80.6% of steps) is literally uncomputable.\n4. **Pure-phase analysis** -- only 6 pure-prefill steps exist under vLLM's chunked prefill.\n\n#### Round 1 Binding Constraints\n1. **PRIMARY: Missing per-request KV cache lengths** in training data. BLIS has `ProgressIndex` at prediction time but training data only has aggregate batch features.\n2. **SECONDARY: Step time scale variation** (3+ OOM) forces per-model training.\n3. **TERTIARY: Hyperparameter underfitting** -- XGBoost selected shallow trees (max_depth=4), suggesting the feature set, not model capacity, is the bottleneck.\n\n#### Round 1 Design Limitations\n- No BLIS (Go) integration or E2E validation was performed.\n- Only `StepTime()` was modeled; the other 4 LatencyModel methods were ignored.\n- No queueing delay, scheduling overhead, or KV dynamics were considered.\n- Baseline was per-experiment (artificially easy); production requires per-model calibration.\n\n#### Data Characteristics Discovered (Round 1)\n- **Phase distribution:** 80.6% pure-decode, 19.4% mixed, 0.005% pure-prefill.\n- **Reasoning workloads** have bimodal distributions and extreme variance (CV > 1.0).\n- **\"General\" workloads** are consistently the hardest (50-121% MAPE).\n- Llama-7B has 47K steps (heavily overrepresented); data is unbalanced.\n\n---\n\n### Round 2 (2026-02-27): BLIS Integration, KV Features, E2E Validation\n\n**Two ideas tested; reasoning workloads excluded (10 experiments: 4 models x 3 workloads).**\n\n#### Idea 1: Bayesian Calibration (2-Regime Piecewise Linear)\n\n- **h1 (Piecewise-linear StepTime):** 87.4% MAPE (target was <30%). Barely improved over blackbox (89.7%).\n- **h2 (Joint Bayesian optimization):** Not run -- blocked because h1 was too inaccurate to justify 66-133 hours of BO compute.\n- **h4 (LOMO):** 148.8% (target <80%), but still 17.2x better than Round 1's 2,559.7%.\n- **h5 (LOWO):** 155.4% (target <40%) -- a regression from Round 1 (109.7%).\n\n**Verdict:** All hypotheses refuted. The 2-regime split (decode-only vs. mixed) is too coarse.\n\n#### Idea 2: Regime-Switching Ensemble (3-Regime Ridge)\n\n- **h1 (Regime Ridge per-step MAPE):** 64.4% with KV features; 43.9% without KV features (target was <15%).\n- **h2 (BLIS E2E validation):** **427.8% mean E2E error** (target <10%). 1/10 experiments under 10% (34b-roleplay, likely coincidental). ITL: **33.6% mean, 5/10 under 10%**. TTFT: **31,906% mean** (catastrophic).\n- **h3 (Secondary method calibration):** **0.0 percentage points** improvement. 200-400us scheduling constants are invisible against 100%+ E2E errors.\n- **h4 (LOMO):** 108.6% (23.6x better than Round 1, but still above 80% target).\n- **h5 (LOWO):** 117.4% (slightly worse than Round 1's 109.7%).\n\n#### Round 2 Key Quantitative Results\n\n| Metric | Idea 1 (2-regime) | Idea 2 (3-regime) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Per-step MAPE (with KV) | 87.4% | 64.4% |\n| Per-step MAPE (no KV) | 83.8% | 43.9% |\n| BLIS E2E mean error | Not tested | 427.8% |\n| ITL mean error | Not tested | 33.6% (5/10 < 10%) |\n| TTFT mean error | Not tested | 31,906% |\n| LOMO avg MAPE | 148.8% | 108.6% |\n| LOWO avg MAPE | 155.4% | 117.4% |\n\n**Per-experiment ITL results (best 5):**\n\n| Experiment | ITL Error |\n|---|---|\n| mixtral-roleplay | **0.7%** |\n| mixtral-codegen | **2.1%** |\n| 7b-roleplay | **4.0%** |\n| mixtral-general | **8.7%** |\n| 70b-hf-codegen | **10.7%** |\n\n#### Round 2: What Worked\n\n1. **Overhead floor mechanism** (`max(overhead, compute)`) -- the single most impactful technique discovered. Per-model overhead constants (7B: 3,897us, 34B: 6,673us, 70B: 8,029-8,203us, Mixtral: 9,125us) handle decode-dominated steps by clamping predictions to real cycle time. This alone solves ITL for 5/10 experiments.\n\n2. **ITL prediction** is good (33.6% mean, 5/10 under 10%). The 7B and Mixtral models are essentially solved for ITL.\n\n3. **LOMO improved 23.6x** (108.6% vs. 2,559.7% in Round 1) due to regime structure + KV features.\n\n4. **Mixtral generalizes exceptionally** -- 0.7-8.7% ITL, 19.1% LOWO. MoE architectures have more regular compute scaling.\n\n5. **Per-model overhead constants are stable** across independent derivations, confirming they are properties of model+GPU+TP configuration.\n\n6. **BLIS E2E validation pipeline** was built (Go integration via `sim/latency/stepml.go`).\n\n#### Round 2: What Failed and Why\n\n1. **KV features are counter-productive in raw linear space.** The central thesis of Round 2 was refuted. Adding ProgressIndex-derived KV features (kv_sum, kv_max, kv_mean) to Ridge regression *degraded* accuracy by 3.6-20.5 percentage points. Root cause: kv_sum values reach 64,000+ causing Ridge coefficient instability. Small alpha amplifies noise; large alpha suppresses all KV signal. **The features themselves are informative but the regression formulation cannot handle their dynamic range.**\n\n2. **TTFT errors are catastrophic** (31,906% mean). This is NOT a step-time modeling problem -- it's a simulation-fidelity mismatch between BLIS's request lifecycle and the real vLLM system. TTFT is the dominant contributor to E2E error.\n\n3. **Mixed-heavy regime is empty** -- only 74/77,816 steps (0.1%) have prefill >= 256 tokens. The 3-regime design collapses to 2 effective regimes.\n\n4. **Secondary method calibration contributes zero** -- 200-400us scheduling/queueing corrections are invisible when E2E errors are 100%+.\n\n5. **CodeLlama-34B is anomalously bad** across all metrics (99.2% per-step MAPE, 2,901% E2E for general workload).\n\n6. **Cross-workload transfer did not improve** (LOWO slightly regressed from Round 1).\n\n#### Overhead Integration Approaches Tested (Round 2)\n\n| Approach | Result |\n|---|---|\n| Additive (compute + overhead) | Phase transition -- system jumps from under-capacity to overload |\n| Log-space cycle time | Exponential amplification -- coefficients get multiplied instead of added |\n| **Max floor (best)** | `max(overhead, compute)` -- handles memory-bound to compute-bound crossover |\n| Floor + cap | `max(overhead, min(compute, 3*overhead))` prevents expm1 blowup |\n\n#### Log-space (expm1) Pitfalls\n- kv_sum coefficient 0.0001 x 64,000 = 6.4 in log-space produces a 601x multiplier.\n- Prefill coefficient 0.06 x 500 tokens = 30 in log-space produces exp(30) = absurd.\n- Safe ONLY for decode-only batches with small coefficients.\n\n---\n\n### Cumulative Scorecard\n\n| Round | Best E2E Error | Best ITL Error | Key Achievement | Primary Blocker |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| R1 | Not tested (Python-only) | Not tested | 34% per-step MAPE with XGBoost (2x over blackbox) | No BLIS integration, no E2E validation |\n| R2 | 427.8% mean (1/10 <10%) | 33.6% mean (5/10 <10%) | Overhead floor + BLIS pipeline + per-request KV features | TTFT mismatch (31,906%) dominates E2E; KV features counter-productive in linear space |\n\n---\n\n### Eliminated Approaches (Do Not Repeat)\n\n| Approach | Why It Failed | Round |\n|---|---|---|\n| Global models (all experiments) | 3+ OOM step-time scale variation | R1 |\n| Analytical FLOPs decomposition without per-request KV | decode_attention = 0, structurally incomplete | R1 |\n| Correction factors on incomplete backbone | Pathological compensation (factor=39.5 on zero signal) | R1 |\n| Pure-phase analysis | Only 6 pure-prefill steps under chunked prefill | R1 |\n| Raw KV features in linear regression | kv_sum up to 64K causes Ridge coefficient instability | R2 |\n| 2-regime piecewise linear | Too coarse -- mixed-batch heterogeneity too high | R2 |\n| Joint Bayesian optimization | Cannot compensate for structural model errors | R2 |\n| Secondary method calibration alone | 200-400us corrections invisible against 100%+ E2E | R2 |\n| Log-space target with large features | expm1 causes exponential blowup | R2 |\n\n---\n\n### Binding Constraints for Round 3 (Ordered by Priority)\n\n1. **TTFT/Workload Spec Mismatch (PRIMARY, blocking E2E target):** The 31,906% mean TTFT error is the single biggest obstacle. It is a simulation-fidelity problem (request injection timing, prefill scheduling, workload spec generation), not a step-time modeling problem. Until TTFT is addressed, no step-time improvement can achieve <10% E2E.\n\n2. **KV Feature Scaling (SECONDARY, blocking per-step improvement):** Per-request KV features are informative but must be properly scaled (StandardScaler, log-transform of features, or tree models). Raw linear regression cannot handle their 0-64,000+ dynamic range.\n\n3. **CodeLlama-34B Anomaly (SECONDARY):** 34B is the worst model by a wide margin. Needs investigation of batch dynamics, step-time distribution, and KV patterns.\n\n4. **Mixed-Heavy Regime Sparsity (TERTIARY):** Only 0.1% of steps are mixed-heavy. Need more data (reasoning workloads) or a lower threshold (64 or 128 tokens).\n\n---\n\n### Successful Techniques to Preserve\n\n1. **Overhead floor (`max(overhead, compute)`)** -- the single most impactful accuracy mechanism.\n2. **Per-model training** -- mandatory due to 3+ OOM step-time variation.\n3. **Regime separation** (decode-only vs. mixed) -- provides distinct modeling contexts.\n4. **Temporal train/test split** -- prevents autocorrelation leakage.\n5. **BLIS E2E validation pipeline** (Go integration via `sim/latency/stepml.go`).\n6. **Per-model overhead derivation** from ground-truth ITL (stable across independent derivations).\n7. **Physics-informed interaction terms** (`prefill_x_decode`, `batch_size_x_kv_pressure`).\n\n---\n\n### Hard Constraints for Any Future Approach\n\n- Per-model training is mandatory (LOMO still >80%).\n- Features must be computable from `[]*Request` with `ProgressIndex` in Go.\n- Prediction latency must be <1ms per step.\n- Pure-Go implementation (no Python/ONNX runtime).\n- `step.duration_us` captures GPU forward pass only; real cycle time includes 4-9ms CPU overhead per model.\n- Step data is ~10% sampled (not every step is logged)."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a596523 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 4198\ntool_uses: 7\nduration_ms: 103536</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"b92e6970-f7d4-49cc-8b1b-668182f9be9c","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Read and summarize the key findings from all prior round artifacts for the StepML research. I need you to read these files and provide a comprehensive summary of what was tried, what worked, what failed, and the current state:\n\n1. hypotheses/h-stepml/round1/FINDINGS_ROUND1.md\n2. hypotheses/h-stepml/round2/FINDINGS_ROUND2.md\n3. Any FINDINGS_SUMMARY.md files under round1/ and round2/\n\nFor each, summarize:\n- What ideas were tested\n- Key quantitative results (E2E errors, MAPE, ITL)\n- What techniques succeeded\n- What techniques failed and why\n- Binding constraints identified\n- Any data characteristics discovered\n\nReturn a detailed but focused summary.","agentId":"a596523","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have all the key documents. Here is the comprehensive summary.\n\n---\n\n## StepML Research: Comprehensive Summary of Rounds 1 and 2\n\n### Goal\n\nReplace BLIS's 3-coefficient blackbox latency model (`step_time = beta0 + beta1*prefill_tokens + beta2*decode_tokens`) with a data-driven predictor achieving **<10% workload-level E2E mean error** across experiments (4 models x 4 workloads on H100 GPUs). The model must integrate into BLIS as a pure-Go `LatencyModel` implementation.\n\n**Training data:** 122,752 step-level observations (Round 1, 16 experiments) / 77,816 steps (Round 2, 10 experiments) from instrumented vLLM v0.15.1 with OpenTelemetry tracing at ~10% sample rate.\n\n---\n\n### Round 1 (2026-02-26): Python-Only Per-Step Modeling\n\n**Three ideas tested; two executed, one deferred.**\n\n#### Idea 1: Physics-Informed Tree Ensemble\n\n- **h1 (30 features + Ridge):** 92.1% avg per-step MAPE per-experiment; 301.7% global. Weakly supported for per-experiment only.\n- **h2 (XGBoost per-experiment):** **Best Round 1 result: 34.0% avg MAPE** -- 2x improvement over blackbox (70.4%). 5/16 experiments under 15% MAPE, zero regressions vs. blackbox.\n- **h3 (Cross-config generalization):** Catastrophic failure. LOMO (leave-one-model-out) = 2,559.7%, LOWO (leave-one-workload-out) = 109.7%.\n\n#### Idea 2: Analytical Decomposition + Learned Corrections\n\n- **h1 (4-component FLOPs decomposition):** 0/4 components exceeded 0.8 Pearson r with step duration. Structurally incomplete because `decode_attention_flops = 0` for all steps (per-request KV lengths unavailable).\n- **h2 (Multiplicative correction factors):** 78.7% MAPE -- *worse* than the 3-parameter blackbox (70.4%). Optimizer set `decode_attn_factor = 39.5` trying to amplify a zero signal.\n\n#### Idea 3: Evolutionary Synthesis (OpenEvolve)\n\nDeferred -- dependent on Idea 2's analytical components and required infrastructure not available.\n\n#### Round 1 Key Quantitative Results\n\n| Approach | Avg Per-Step MAPE | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Blackbox baseline | 70.4% | Per-experiment fit |\n| Ridge 30 features (per-exp) | 92.1% | Worse than blackbox |\n| XGBoost 30 features (per-exp) | **34.0%** | Best result (2x improvement) |\n| Analytical decomposition | 78.7% | Worse than blackbox |\n| Global Ridge | 301.7% | Catastrophic |\n| LOMO XGBoost | 2,559.7% | Catastrophic |\n\n#### Round 1: What Worked\n1. **Per-experiment XGBoost** with 30 physics-informed features provided a genuine 2x improvement.\n2. **Feature engineering insights:** Top features were KV cache state proxies (`kv_blocks_used`, `running_depth`, `kv_blocks_free`), indicating the model is bottlenecked by KV information quality.\n3. **Temporal train/test split** (60/20/20) prevents autocorrelation leakage.\n4. **Physics-informed interaction terms** (`prefill_x_decode`, `batch_size_x_kv_pressure`) added unique signal.\n\n#### Round 1: What Failed\n1. **Global models** -- step times span 3+ orders of magnitude across model configs (7B: 12-500us, 70B: 500-250,000us).\n2. **Cross-model generalization** -- features encode absolute values, not scale-normalized.\n3. **Analytical decomposition** -- structurally incomplete without per-request KV lengths; decode attention (the dominant cost for 80.6% of steps) is literally uncomputable.\n4. **Pure-phase analysis** -- only 6 pure-prefill steps exist under vLLM's chunked prefill.\n\n#### Round 1 Binding Constraints\n1. **PRIMARY: Missing per-request KV cache lengths** in training data. BLIS has `ProgressIndex` at prediction time but training data only has aggregate batch features.\n2. **SECONDARY: Step time scale variation** (3+ OOM) forces per-model training.\n3. **TERTIARY: Hyperparameter underfitting** -- XGBoost selected shallow trees (max_depth=4), suggesting the feature set, not model capacity, is the bottleneck.\n\n#### Round 1 Design Limitations\n- No BLIS (Go) integration or E2E validation was performed.\n- Only `StepTime()` was modeled; the other 4 LatencyModel methods were ignored.\n- No queueing delay, scheduling overhead, or KV dynamics were considered.\n- Baseline was per-experiment (artificially easy); production requires per-model calibration.\n\n#### Data Characteristics Discovered (Round 1)\n- **Phase distribution:** 80.6% pure-decode, 19.4% mixed, 0.005% pure-prefill.\n- **Reasoning workloads** have bimodal distributions and extreme variance (CV > 1.0).\n- **\"General\" workloads** are consistently the hardest (50-121% MAPE).\n- Llama-7B has 47K steps (heavily overrepresented); data is unbalanced.\n\n---\n\n### Round 2 (2026-02-27): BLIS Integration, KV Features, E2E Validation\n\n**Two ideas tested; reasoning workloads excluded (10 experiments: 4 models x 3 workloads).**\n\n#### Idea 1: Bayesian Calibration (2-Regime Piecewise Linear)\n\n- **h1 (Piecewise-linear StepTime):** 87.4% MAPE (target was <30%). Barely improved over blackbox (89.7%).\n- **h2 (Joint Bayesian optimization):** Not run -- blocked because h1 was too inaccurate to justify 66-133 hours of BO compute.\n- **h4 (LOMO):** 148.8% (target <80%), but still 17.2x better than Round 1's 2,559.7%.\n- **h5 (LOWO):** 155.4% (target <40%) -- a regression from Round 1 (109.7%).\n\n**Verdict:** All hypotheses refuted. The 2-regime split (decode-only vs. mixed) is too coarse.\n\n#### Idea 2: Regime-Switching Ensemble (3-Regime Ridge)\n\n- **h1 (Regime Ridge per-step MAPE):** 64.4% with KV features; 43.9% without KV features (target was <15%).\n- **h2 (BLIS E2E validation):** **427.8% mean E2E error** (target <10%). 1/10 experiments under 10% (34b-roleplay, likely coincidental). ITL: **33.6% mean, 5/10 under 10%**. TTFT: **31,906% mean** (catastrophic).\n- **h3 (Secondary method calibration):** **0.0 percentage points** improvement. 200-400us scheduling constants are invisible against 100%+ E2E errors.\n- **h4 (LOMO):** 108.6% (23.6x better than Round 1, but still above 80% target).\n- **h5 (LOWO):** 117.4% (slightly worse than Round 1's 109.7%).\n\n#### Round 2 Key Quantitative Results\n\n| Metric | Idea 1 (2-regime) | Idea 2 (3-regime) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Per-step MAPE (with KV) | 87.4% | 64.4% |\n| Per-step MAPE (no KV) | 83.8% | 43.9% |\n| BLIS E2E mean error | Not tested | 427.8% |\n| ITL mean error | Not tested | 33.6% (5/10 < 10%) |\n| TTFT mean error | Not tested | 31,906% |\n| LOMO avg MAPE | 148.8% | 108.6% |\n| LOWO avg MAPE | 155.4% | 117.4% |\n\n**Per-experiment ITL results (best 5):**\n\n| Experiment | ITL Error |\n|---|---|\n| mixtral-roleplay | **0.7%** |\n| mixtral-codegen | **2.1%** |\n| 7b-roleplay | **4.0%** |\n| mixtral-general | **8.7%** |\n| 70b-hf-codegen | **10.7%** |\n\n#### Round 2: What Worked\n\n1. **Overhead floor mechanism** (`max(overhead, compute)`) -- the single most impactful technique discovered. Per-model overhead constants (7B: 3,897us, 34B: 6,673us, 70B: 8,029-8,203us, Mixtral: 9,125us) handle decode-dominated steps by clamping predictions to real cycle time. This alone solves ITL for 5/10 experiments.\n\n2. **ITL prediction** is good (33.6% mean, 5/10 under 10%). The 7B and Mixtral models are essentially solved for ITL.\n\n3. **LOMO improved 23.6x** (108.6% vs. 2,559.7% in Round 1) due to regime structure + KV features.\n\n4. **Mixtral generalizes exceptionally** -- 0.7-8.7% ITL, 19.1% LOWO. MoE architectures have more regular compute scaling.\n\n5. **Per-model overhead constants are stable** across independent derivations, confirming they are properties of model+GPU+TP configuration.\n\n6. **BLIS E2E validation pipeline** was built (Go integration via `sim/latency/stepml.go`).\n\n#### Round 2: What Failed and Why\n\n1. **KV features are counter-productive in raw linear space.** The central thesis of Round 2 was refuted. Adding ProgressIndex-derived KV features (kv_sum, kv_max, kv_mean) to Ridge regression *degraded* accuracy by 3.6-20.5 percentage points. Root cause: kv_sum values reach 64,000+ causing Ridge coefficient instability. Small alpha amplifies noise; large alpha suppresses all KV signal. **The features themselves are informative but the regression formulation cannot handle their dynamic range.**\n\n2. **TTFT errors are catastrophic** (31,906% mean). This is NOT a step-time modeling problem -- it's a simulation-fidelity mismatch between BLIS's request lifecycle and the real vLLM system. TTFT is the dominant contributor to E2E error.\n\n3. **Mixed-heavy regime is empty** -- only 74/77,816 steps (0.1%) have prefill >= 256 tokens. The 3-regime design collapses to 2 effective regimes.\n\n4. **Secondary method calibration contributes zero** -- 200-400us scheduling/queueing corrections are invisible when E2E errors are 100%+.\n\n5. **CodeLlama-34B is anomalously bad** across all metrics (99.2% per-step MAPE, 2,901% E2E for general workload).\n\n6. **Cross-workload transfer did not improve** (LOWO slightly regressed from Round 1).\n\n#### Overhead Integration Approaches Tested (Round 2)\n\n| Approach | Result |\n|---|---|\n| Additive (compute + overhead) | Phase transition -- system jumps from under-capacity to overload |\n| Log-space cycle time | Exponential amplification -- coefficients get multiplied instead of added |\n| **Max floor (best)** | `max(overhead, compute)` -- handles memory-bound to compute-bound crossover |\n| Floor + cap | `max(overhead, min(compute, 3*overhead))` prevents expm1 blowup |\n\n#### Log-space (expm1) Pitfalls\n- kv_sum coefficient 0.0001 x 64,000 = 6.4 in log-space produces a 601x multiplier.\n- Prefill coefficient 0.06 x 500 tokens = 30 in log-space produces exp(30) = absurd.\n- Safe ONLY for decode-only batches with small coefficients.\n\n---\n\n### Cumulative Scorecard\n\n| Round | Best E2E Error | Best ITL Error | Key Achievement | Primary Blocker |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| R1 | Not tested (Python-only) | Not tested | 34% per-step MAPE with XGBoost (2x over blackbox) | No BLIS integration, no E2E validation |\n| R2 | 427.8% mean (1/10 <10%) | 33.6% mean (5/10 <10%) | Overhead floor + BLIS pipeline + per-request KV features | TTFT mismatch (31,906%) dominates E2E; KV features counter-productive in linear space |\n\n---\n\n### Eliminated Approaches (Do Not Repeat)\n\n| Approach | Why It Failed | Round |\n|---|---|---|\n| Global models (all experiments) | 3+ OOM step-time scale variation | R1 |\n| Analytical FLOPs decomposition without per-request KV | decode_attention = 0, structurally incomplete | R1 |\n| Correction factors on incomplete backbone | Pathological compensation (factor=39.5 on zero signal) | R1 |\n| Pure-phase analysis | Only 6 pure-prefill steps under chunked prefill | R1 |\n| Raw KV features in linear regression | kv_sum up to 64K causes Ridge coefficient instability | R2 |\n| 2-regime piecewise linear | Too coarse -- mixed-batch heterogeneity too high | R2 |\n| Joint Bayesian optimization | Cannot compensate for structural model errors | R2 |\n| Secondary method calibration alone | 200-400us corrections invisible against 100%+ E2E | R2 |\n| Log-space target with large features | expm1 causes exponential blowup | R2 |\n\n---\n\n### Binding Constraints for Round 3 (Ordered by Priority)\n\n1. **TTFT/Workload Spec Mismatch (PRIMARY, blocking E2E target):** The 31,906% mean TTFT error is the single biggest obstacle. It is a simulation-fidelity problem (request injection timing, prefill scheduling, workload spec generation), not a step-time modeling problem. Until TTFT is addressed, no step-time improvement can achieve <10% E2E.\n\n2. **KV Feature Scaling (SECONDARY, blocking per-step improvement):** Per-request KV features are informative but must be properly scaled (StandardScaler, log-transform of features, or tree models). Raw linear regression cannot handle their 0-64,000+ dynamic range.\n\n3. **CodeLlama-34B Anomaly (SECONDARY):** 34B is the worst model by a wide margin. Needs investigation of batch dynamics, step-time distribution, and KV patterns.\n\n4. **Mixed-Heavy Regime Sparsity (TERTIARY):** Only 0.1% of steps are mixed-heavy. Need more data (reasoning workloads) or a lower threshold (64 or 128 tokens).\n\n---\n\n### Successful Techniques to Preserve\n\n1. **Overhead floor (`max(overhead, compute)`)** -- the single most impactful accuracy mechanism.\n2. **Per-model training** -- mandatory due to 3+ OOM step-time variation.\n3. **Regime separation** (decode-only vs. mixed) -- provides distinct modeling contexts.\n4. **Temporal train/test split** -- prevents autocorrelation leakage.\n5. **BLIS E2E validation pipeline** (Go integration via `sim/latency/stepml.go`).\n6. **Per-model overhead derivation** from ground-truth ITL (stable across independent derivations).\n7. **Physics-informed interaction terms** (`prefill_x_decode`, `batch_size_x_kv_pressure`).\n\n---\n\n### Hard Constraints for Any Future Approach\n\n- Per-model training is mandatory (LOMO still >80%).\n- Features must be computable from `[]*Request` with `ProgressIndex` in Go.\n- Prediction latency must be <1ms per step.\n- Pure-Go implementation (no Python/ONNX runtime).\n- `step.duration_us` captures GPU forward pass only; real cycle time includes 4-9ms CPU overhead per model.\n- Step data is ~10% sampled (not every step is logged)."}],"totalDurationMs":103536,"totalTokens":4198,"totalToolUseCount":7,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":4197,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01XSWXeYuD6tp3TnH5t8UevE","type":"tool_result","content":"# MIST: Multi-Stage LLM Inference Modeling Approach\n\n## Core Modeling Architecture\n\nMIST employs a three-layer simulation framework: the AI Workload Layer (request traces), System/Software Layer (coordinator, clients, schedulers), and Hardware Layer (physical nodes). The system models \"end-to-end execution of state-of-the-art LLM inference pipelines\" across these interconnected layers through discrete-event simulation.\n\n## Step/Iteration Time Modeling\n\nMIST represents computation at granular \"step\" levels—for prefill/decode, a step equals one forward pass. The framework supports four hardware modeling approaches:\n\n1. **Real Execution Runtime**: Direct measurement with local databases\n2. **Empirical Runtime**: ML-trained predictors from profiled hardware\n3. **Analytical Modeling**: Mathematical formulations for simpler components\n4. **External Simulators**: Integration with GenZ or LLMCompass\n\nFor LLM clusters specifically, MIST uses ensemble regressors trained on 200k+ datapoints across input sizes, batch sizes, and tensor parallelism configurations, achieving \"average error of 2.5% with median error of less than 1%.\"\n\n## Multi-Stage Pipeline Modeling\n\nThe framework supports six pipeline stages: Preprocess, RAG, Prefill, Decode, KV Cache Retrieval, and Postprocess. Requests flow through arbitrary stage combinations via a global coordinator that performs routing, load balancing, and inter-stage communication management using Astra-Sim for network effects.\n\n## Prefill vs. Decode Latency Handling\n\nMIST distinguishes compute characteristics: prefill is \"compute-intensive,\" while decode is \"memory-bound.\" The scheduler enforces stage-specific batching strategies (static, continuous, chunked, mixed, disaggregated) that differentially impact each phase's throughput and latency profiles.\n\n## Calibration Methodology\n\nCalibration involves three validation approaches:\n\n- **Aggregated-Offline**: Comparing against vLLM on H100x8 (< 2% error)\n- **Aggregated-Online**: Poisson-distributed 5 QPS workloads (5.3% error)\n- **Disaggregated-Online**: Azure traces with Splitwise validation (< 6% error)\n\n## Accuracy Metrics\n\nMIST achieves end-to-end fidelity within \"6% average disparity with deployed inference systems.\" For individual components: LLM cluster predictions show better accuracy than prior tools like Vidur; KV retrieval modeling closely tracks measured latency across memory tiers.\n\n## Key Latency Insights\n\nThe paper reveals that \"end-to-end performance emerges from interactions across stages, across clients, and across layers\"—not isolated operations. Critical findings include:\n\n- RAG significantly impacts P99 tail latency in context-augmented tasks\n- KV transfers become bottlenecks in disaggregated serving under simultaneous prefill/decode transfers\n- Platform-level shared caches optimize private KV scenarios; rack-level caches suit shared global caches\n- For short KV caches (~4K tokens), \"recomputation overhead becomes competitive\" versus retrieval overhead"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"792ccbf8-460c-48d2-99b9-76f736662c3c"}
