{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01G9D4AX6txJT8XM4avPQmbK","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a comprehensive picture. Here is the detailed summary:\n\n---\n\n## Shared Infrastructure Summary for StepML Research\n\n### 1. Complete File Inventory\n\n**Core modules** (in `/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/BLIS-research/hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/`):\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `data_loader.py` | Loads OpenTelemetry traces (step-level BATCH_SUMMARY) and per-request lifecycle metrics from `eval/ground_truth/` |\n| `evaluation.py` | Pure math: `compute_mape`, `compute_mspe`, `compute_pearson_r`, `compute_p99_error`, `bootstrap_ci`, `compute_e2e_mean_error` |\n| `splits.py` | `temporal_split` (60/20/20 within each experiment by step.id), `leave_one_model_out` (4-fold), `leave_one_workload_out` (4-fold) |\n| `baselines.py` | `BlackboxBaseline` (3-coeff NNLS linear), `NaiveMeanBaseline`, `compute_baseline_report`, `check_r4_gate` |\n| `validation.py` | `temporal_vs_random_split_comparison`, `validate_progress_index` (R1 gate) |\n| `validate_blis.py` | Full BLIS E2E validation harness: loads exp-config.yaml, profile.yaml, vllm.log, builds workload spec, runs the `simulation_worker` binary, parses BLIS stdout, computes errors. This is the primary tool for E2E accuracy evaluation. |\n| `establish_baseline.py` | Orchestrates both baselines (roofline + per-model linear regression) through BLIS E2E validation with parallel execution. |\n| `lifecycle_kv_extractor.py` | Joins step timestamps with per-request lifecycle data to compute per-step KV statistics: `kv_mean`, `kv_max`, `kv_sum`, `kv_std`, `kv_count` |\n| `e2e_decomposition.py` | Component-level error attribution: breaks E2E into StepTime, QueueingTime, OutputProcessing, Scheduling, Preemption fractions |\n| `sampling_analysis.py` | Characterizes 10% sampling bias (step.id gaps, periodicity, coverage uniformity) |\n| `convert_lifecycle_to_traces.py` | Converts per-request lifecycle JSON to BLIS trace CSV format for replay |\n| `mfu_benchmarks.py` | `MFUBenchmarkIndex` class for querying InferSim's bench_data/ (GEMM, MHA decode/prefill, grouped GEMM MFU) |\n| `requirements.txt` | pandas, pyarrow, scikit-learn, scipy, pytest, numpy, xgboost |\n\n**Test files**: `test_data_loader.py`, `test_evaluation.py`, `test_splits.py`, `test_baselines.py`, `test_validation.py`, `test_sampling.py`, `test_lifecycle_kv_extractor.py`, `test_e2e_decomposition.py`, `test_mfu_benchmarks.py`\n\n**Baseline results** (in `shared/baseline_results/`): `per_model_linear_baseline.csv`, `per_model_linear_baseline_summary.json`, `roofline_baseline.csv`, `roofline_baseline_summary.json`, `component_attribution.csv`, `r1_gate.json`, `r2_gate.json`, `plot_baselines.py`\n\n### 2. BLIS Validation Pipeline\n\nThe validation pipeline has two entry points:\n\n**`validate_blis.py`** -- The core harness. For each experiment directory under `eval/ground_truth/`:\n1. Parses directory name for model/tp/workload metadata\n2. Loads ground-truth metrics from `results/summary_lifecycle_metrics.json`\n3. Loads vLLM serving args from `exp-config.yaml`\n4. Extracts GPU KV blocks from `vllm.log` (pattern: `GPU KV cache size: N tokens`) and converts to blocks (tokens / 16)\n5. Extracts CPU KV blocks from `vllm.log` (from `cpu_bytes_to_use` and KV cache shape)\n6. Loads `profile.yaml` (JSON despite .yaml extension) for inference-perf stages\n7. Builds a BLIS WorkloadSpec v2 YAML with stages, shared_prefix config, and horizon\n8. Invokes the `simulation_worker` binary with `--model`, `--tp`, `--max-model-len`, `--max-num-running-reqs`, `--max-num-scheduled-tokens`, `--total-kv-blocks`, `--block-size-in-tokens`, plus either `--alpha-coeffs`/`--beta-coeffs` or `--stepml-model` or `--roofline --hardware`\n9. Parses BLIS stdout for the JSON block after `=== Simulation Metrics ===`\n10. Computes relative errors for E2E, TTFT, ITL\n\nKey CLI flags for `validate_blis.py`:\n- `--alpha-coeffs` / `--beta-coeffs`: Traditional blackbox coefficients\n- `--stepml-model`: Path to a StepML artifact JSON (passed as `--stepml-model` to the Go binary)\n- `--roofline --hardware H100`: Use analytical roofline model\n\n**`validate_e2e.py`** (in `round2/idea-2-regime-ensemble/h2-blis-e2e-validation/`): A simplified wrapper that selects the per-model artifact (regime or single) from an artifact directory and runs BLIS for each experiment. Uses `--stepml-model` to pass the artifact to BLIS.\n\n**`establish_baseline.py`**: Orchestrates both baselines with parallel BLIS runs via `ThreadPoolExecutor`. Trains per-model linear coefficients, runs roofline, and produces summary CSVs + JSONs.\n\n### 3. Data Loading Utilities\n\n**`data_loader.py`** provides:\n- `load_all_experiments(data_root)` -- Loads all step-level data into one DataFrame. Parses `traces.json` (OTLP JSONL format), extracts `step.BATCH_SUMMARY` events, flattens attributes. Adds metadata columns (model, tp, workload, timestamp) from directory names.\n- `load_experiment_steps(experiment_dir)` -- Single-experiment step data.\n- `load_lifecycle_data(experiment_dir)` -- Per-request lifecycle from `results/per_request_lifecycle_metrics.json`. Returns DataFrame with `start_time`, `end_time`, `input_tokens`, `output_tokens`, `output_token_times` (list of per-token timestamps).\n- `parse_experiment_metadata(dirname)` -- Extracts model/tp/workload from directory name pattern `YYYYMMDD-HHMMSS-<model>-tp<N>-<workload>`.\n\nDefault data root: `eval/ground_truth/` relative to the shared directory (3 directories up).\n\n**`lifecycle_kv_extractor.py`** provides:\n- `extract_kv_features(steps_df, lifecycle_df)` -- For each step, identifies active requests (overlapping time windows), estimates each request's KV length as `input_tokens + output_tokens_generated_before_step_start`, computes `kv_mean`, `kv_max`, `kv_sum`, `kv_std`, `kv_count`.\n- `extract_all_experiments_kv_features(data_root)` -- Convenience wrapper that loads both data sources for all experiments and enriches steps with KV features.\n\n### 4. Training Data Schema\n\nStep-level features (from BATCH_SUMMARY OTLP events):\n\n| Column | Type | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| `step.id` | Int64 | Step sequence number |\n| `step.ts_start_ns` | Int64 | Nanosecond timestamp |\n| `step.ts_end_ns` | Int64 | Nanosecond timestamp |\n| `step.duration_us` | Int64 | **TARGET** -- GPU forward pass wall-clock time |\n| `batch.prefill_tokens` | Int64 | Prefill tokens this step |\n| `batch.decode_tokens` | Int64 | Decode tokens this step |\n| `batch.num_prefill_reqs` | Int64 | Prefill request count |\n| `batch.num_decode_reqs` | Int64 | Decode request count |\n| `batch.scheduled_tokens` | Int64 | Total scheduled tokens |\n| `batch.num_finished` | Int64 | Finished requests |\n| `batch.num_preempted` | Int64 | Preempted requests |\n| `queue.running_depth` | Int64 | Running queue state |\n| `queue.waiting_depth` | Int64 | Waiting queue state |\n| `kv.blocks_free_gpu` | Int64 | Free GPU KV blocks |\n| `kv.blocks_total_gpu` | Int64 | Total GPU KV blocks |\n| `kv.usage_gpu_ratio` | Float64 | GPU KV utilization |\n\nAfter KV enrichment (via `lifecycle_kv_extractor.py`), additional columns: `kv_mean`, `kv_max`, `kv_sum`, `kv_std`, `kv_count`.\n\nAfter interaction feature engineering (in `train_regime_ridge.py`): `prefill_x_decode`, `decode_x_kv_mean`, `prefill_sq`.\n\nThe data is ~10% sampled (OpenTelemetry tracing at ~10% rate). Total: 122,752 step observations from 12 experiments (4 models x 3 workloads), all on H100 80GB GPUs. Step durations span ~12us to ~250,000us.\n\n### 5. Overhead Floor Mechanism\n\nThe overhead floor is the most impactful technique discovered in Round 2. It exists in two places:\n\n**Go side** (`/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/BLIS-research/sim/latency/stepml.go`, lines 232-268):\n```go\nfunc (s *StepMLLatencyModel) StepTime(batch []*sim.Request) int64 {\n    // ... predict from features ...\n    \n    // Floor: max(overhead, compute)\n    if s.artifact.StepOverheadUs > 0 {\n        if prediction < s.artifact.StepOverheadUs {\n            prediction = s.artifact.StepOverheadUs\n        }\n        // Cap at 3x overhead to prevent exponential blowup\n        maxStep := s.artifact.StepOverheadUs * 3\n        if prediction > maxStep {\n            prediction = maxStep\n        }\n    }\n    \n    // Per-request overhead (additive)\n    if s.artifact.StepOverheadPerReqUs > 0 {\n        batchSize := features[\"num_prefill_reqs\"] + features[\"num_decode_reqs\"]\n        prediction += s.artifact.StepOverheadPerReqUs * batchSize\n    }\n    \n    // Minimum 1us (INV-M-1)\n    if prediction < 1 { prediction = 1 }\n}\n```\n\n**Python training side** (`/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/BLIS-research/hypotheses/h-stepml/round2/idea-2-regime-ensemble/h1-kv-regime-models/train_regime_ridge.py`, `compute_step_overhead` function, lines 293-344):\n- Computes per-model overhead as: `GT_ITL_mean_us - mean_compute_time_per_step`\n- Ground-truth ITL = full step cycle time in continuous batching\n- `step.duration_us` = GPU compute only\n- Skips reasoning workloads (negative overhead due to large-batch compute dominating)\n- The overhead is stored in the artifact JSON as `step_overhead_us`\n\nPer-model overhead constants (from Round 2):\n- Llama-2-7B TP1: 3,897 us\n- CodeLlama-34B TP2: 6,673 us\n- Llama-2-70B TP4: 8,029-8,203 us\n- Mixtral-8x7B TP2: 9,125 us\n\nThe mechanism works because 77.9% of steps are decode-only with small compute (~12-320us), far below the overhead floor (~4,000-9,000us). For these steps, the floor correctly sets the step time to the real cycle time. The 3x cap prevents exponential blowup from outlier feature values in the expm1 transform.\n\n### 6. Coefficient Export for BLIS Consumption\n\nThe artifact JSON format has two versions:\n\n**Version 1** (single model):\n```json\n{\n  \"version\": 1,\n  \"step_time\": {\n    \"model_type\": \"linear\",\n    \"intercept\": 100.0,\n    \"feature_coefficients\": {\"prefill_tokens\": 50.0, \"decode_tokens\": 5.0},\n    \"output_transform\": \"expm1\"  // optional, for log-space models\n  },\n  \"step_overhead_us\": 3897.0,\n  \"step_overhead_per_req_us\": 0.0,\n  \"output_token_processing_time_us\": 0.0,\n  \"scheduling_processing_time_us\": 0.0,\n  \"preemption_processing_time_us\": 0.0\n}\n```\n\n**Version 2** (regime-based):\n```json\n{\n  \"version\": 2,\n  \"step_time_regimes\": [\n    {\n      \"name\": \"decode_only\",\n      \"condition\": {\"feature\": \"prefill_tokens\", \"op\": \"==\", \"value\": 0},\n      \"model\": {\"model_type\": \"linear\", \"intercept\": -37.37, \"feature_coefficients\": {\"decode_tokens\": 7.95, \"num_decode_reqs\": 7.95}}\n    },\n    {\n      \"name\": \"mixed_light\",\n      \"condition\": {\"feature\": \"prefill_tokens\", \"op\": \"<\", \"value\": 256},\n      \"model\": {\"model_type\": \"linear\", \"intercept\": -77.98, \"feature_coefficients\": {...}}\n    },\n    {\n      \"name\": \"mixed_heavy\",\n      \"condition\": null,  // fallback\n      \"model\": {...}\n    }\n  ],\n  \"step_overhead_us\": 3896.76,\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nThe Python-to-Go feature name mapping (in `train_regime_ridge.py`, `_FEATURE_NAME_MAP`):\n- `batch.prefill_tokens` -> `prefill_tokens`\n- `batch.decode_tokens` -> `decode_tokens`\n- `batch.num_prefill_reqs` -> `num_prefill_reqs`\n- `batch.num_decode_reqs` -> `num_decode_reqs`\n- `kv_sum`, `kv_max`, `kv_mean`, `kv_std` -> same names\n- `prefill_x_decode`, `decode_x_kv_mean`, `prefill_sq` -> same names\n\nExport functions in `train_regime_ridge.py`:\n- `export_regime_artifact()` -- Writes version 2 with regime conditions\n- `export_single_artifact()` -- Writes version 1 for comparison\n- `_ridge_to_linear_model()` -- Converts sklearn Ridge to Go LinearModel format, optionally adding `\"output_transform\": \"expm1\"` for log-space models\n\n### 7. Round 2 Training Scripts (for reference)\n\nKey training scripts in `/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/BLIS-research/hypotheses/h-stepml/round2/`:\n\n- `idea-2-regime-ensemble/h1-kv-regime-models/train_regime_ridge.py` -- The most evolved training script. 3-regime Ridge per model, KV features, overhead computation, raw linear (not log-space), artifact export. This is the template for Round 3 experiments.\n- `idea-2-regime-ensemble/h2-blis-e2e-validation/validate_e2e.py` -- E2E validation wrapper\n- `idea-2-regime-ensemble/h3-secondary-method-calibration/calibrate_secondary.py` -- Secondary method constant extraction\n- `idea-2-regime-ensemble/h4-model-generalization/lomo_cv.py` -- Leave-one-model-out CV\n- `idea-2-regime-ensemble/h5-workload-generalization/lowo_cv.py` -- Leave-one-workload-out CV\n- `idea-1-bayesian-calibration/h1-piecewise-steptime/train_piecewise.py` -- 2-regime piecewise linear\n- `idea-1-bayesian-calibration/h2-joint-bo-calibration/bo_calibrate.py` -- Bayesian optimization\n\n### 8. Round 3 State\n\nThe `round3/` directory currently only contains `phase1_wp1_wp2.log` -- indicating that a Round 3 attempt was started but may not have completed. The `problem.md` has been updated with all Round 2 knowledge and identifies the primary blocker as TTFT/simulation fidelity mismatch (31,906% mean TTFT error).\n\n### 9. Available Python Dependencies\n\nFrom `requirements.txt`: pandas 2.2.3, pyarrow 18.1.0, scikit-learn 1.6.1, scipy 1.15.2, pytest 8.3.4, numpy 2.2.3, xgboost 2.1.4.\n\n### 10. Key Infrastructure Patterns for Round 3\n\nAny Round 3 experiment should follow this workflow:\n\n1. **Load data**: `extract_all_experiments_kv_features()` from `lifecycle_kv_extractor.py` (gets steps + KV features)\n2. **Add interactions**: `add_interaction_features()` from `train_regime_ridge.py`\n3. **Compute overhead**: `compute_step_overhead()` from `train_regime_ridge.py`\n4. **Split data**: `temporal_split()` per model from `splits.py`\n5. **Classify regimes**: `classify_regimes()` from `train_regime_ridge.py`\n6. **Train models**: scikit-learn Ridge/XGBoost per regime per model\n7. **Evaluate per-step**: `compute_mape`, `compute_pearson_r` etc. from `evaluation.py`\n8. **Export artifact**: `export_regime_artifact()` or `export_single_artifact()` to JSON\n9. **Validate E2E**: Either `validate_e2e.py` (per-model artifact selection) or `validate_blis.py` (explicit coefficients)\n10. **Generalization**: `leave_one_model_out()` and `leave_one_workload_out()` from `splits.py`"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: aeb1233 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 5048\ntool_uses: 30\nduration_ms: 136777</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"74edf1b6-33bc-4f9c-935b-c9473c564eba","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Explore the shared infrastructure in hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/ directory. I need to understand:\n\n1. What scripts exist (list all .py and .sh files)\n2. How the BLIS validation pipeline works (validate_blis.py, validate_e2e.py)\n3. What data loading utilities are available\n4. What the training data looks like (read a sample or the data loader)\n5. How the overhead floor mechanism is implemented in the training pipeline\n6. How coefficients are exported for BLIS consumption\n\nFocus on understanding the infrastructure that Round 3 experiments would use. Also check:\n- hypotheses/h-stepml/round2/ for any training scripts that show how models were trained\n- The exp-config.yaml or similar configuration files\n\nProvide a detailed summary of available infrastructure.","agentId":"aeb1233","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a comprehensive picture. Here is the detailed summary:\n\n---\n\n## Shared Infrastructure Summary for StepML Research\n\n### 1. Complete File Inventory\n\n**Core modules** (in `/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/BLIS-research/hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/`):\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `data_loader.py` | Loads OpenTelemetry traces (step-level BATCH_SUMMARY) and per-request lifecycle metrics from `eval/ground_truth/` |\n| `evaluation.py` | Pure math: `compute_mape`, `compute_mspe`, `compute_pearson_r`, `compute_p99_error`, `bootstrap_ci`, `compute_e2e_mean_error` |\n| `splits.py` | `temporal_split` (60/20/20 within each experiment by step.id), `leave_one_model_out` (4-fold), `leave_one_workload_out` (4-fold) |\n| `baselines.py` | `BlackboxBaseline` (3-coeff NNLS linear), `NaiveMeanBaseline`, `compute_baseline_report`, `check_r4_gate` |\n| `validation.py` | `temporal_vs_random_split_comparison`, `validate_progress_index` (R1 gate) |\n| `validate_blis.py` | Full BLIS E2E validation harness: loads exp-config.yaml, profile.yaml, vllm.log, builds workload spec, runs the `simulation_worker` binary, parses BLIS stdout, computes errors. This is the primary tool for E2E accuracy evaluation. |\n| `establish_baseline.py` | Orchestrates both baselines (roofline + per-model linear regression) through BLIS E2E validation with parallel execution. |\n| `lifecycle_kv_extractor.py` | Joins step timestamps with per-request lifecycle data to compute per-step KV statistics: `kv_mean`, `kv_max`, `kv_sum`, `kv_std`, `kv_count` |\n| `e2e_decomposition.py` | Component-level error attribution: breaks E2E into StepTime, QueueingTime, OutputProcessing, Scheduling, Preemption fractions |\n| `sampling_analysis.py` | Characterizes 10% sampling bias (step.id gaps, periodicity, coverage uniformity) |\n| `convert_lifecycle_to_traces.py` | Converts per-request lifecycle JSON to BLIS trace CSV format for replay |\n| `mfu_benchmarks.py` | `MFUBenchmarkIndex` class for querying InferSim's bench_data/ (GEMM, MHA decode/prefill, grouped GEMM MFU) |\n| `requirements.txt` | pandas, pyarrow, scikit-learn, scipy, pytest, numpy, xgboost |\n\n**Test files**: `test_data_loader.py`, `test_evaluation.py`, `test_splits.py`, `test_baselines.py`, `test_validation.py`, `test_sampling.py`, `test_lifecycle_kv_extractor.py`, `test_e2e_decomposition.py`, `test_mfu_benchmarks.py`\n\n**Baseline results** (in `shared/baseline_results/`): `per_model_linear_baseline.csv`, `per_model_linear_baseline_summary.json`, `roofline_baseline.csv`, `roofline_baseline_summary.json`, `component_attribution.csv`, `r1_gate.json`, `r2_gate.json`, `plot_baselines.py`\n\n### 2. BLIS Validation Pipeline\n\nThe validation pipeline has two entry points:\n\n**`validate_blis.py`** -- The core harness. For each experiment directory under `eval/ground_truth/`:\n1. Parses directory name for model/tp/workload metadata\n2. Loads ground-truth metrics from `results/summary_lifecycle_metrics.json`\n3. Loads vLLM serving args from `exp-config.yaml`\n4. Extracts GPU KV blocks from `vllm.log` (pattern: `GPU KV cache size: N tokens`) and converts to blocks (tokens / 16)\n5. Extracts CPU KV blocks from `vllm.log` (from `cpu_bytes_to_use` and KV cache shape)\n6. Loads `profile.yaml` (JSON despite .yaml extension) for inference-perf stages\n7. Builds a BLIS WorkloadSpec v2 YAML with stages, shared_prefix config, and horizon\n8. Invokes the `simulation_worker` binary with `--model`, `--tp`, `--max-model-len`, `--max-num-running-reqs`, `--max-num-scheduled-tokens`, `--total-kv-blocks`, `--block-size-in-tokens`, plus either `--alpha-coeffs`/`--beta-coeffs` or `--stepml-model` or `--roofline --hardware`\n9. Parses BLIS stdout for the JSON block after `=== Simulation Metrics ===`\n10. Computes relative errors for E2E, TTFT, ITL\n\nKey CLI flags for `validate_blis.py`:\n- `--alpha-coeffs` / `--beta-coeffs`: Traditional blackbox coefficients\n- `--stepml-model`: Path to a StepML artifact JSON (passed as `--stepml-model` to the Go binary)\n- `--roofline --hardware H100`: Use analytical roofline model\n\n**`validate_e2e.py`** (in `round2/idea-2-regime-ensemble/h2-blis-e2e-validation/`): A simplified wrapper that selects the per-model artifact (regime or single) from an artifact directory and runs BLIS for each experiment. Uses `--stepml-model` to pass the artifact to BLIS.\n\n**`establish_baseline.py`**: Orchestrates both baselines with parallel BLIS runs via `ThreadPoolExecutor`. Trains per-model linear coefficients, runs roofline, and produces summary CSVs + JSONs.\n\n### 3. Data Loading Utilities\n\n**`data_loader.py`** provides:\n- `load_all_experiments(data_root)` -- Loads all step-level data into one DataFrame. Parses `traces.json` (OTLP JSONL format), extracts `step.BATCH_SUMMARY` events, flattens attributes. Adds metadata columns (model, tp, workload, timestamp) from directory names.\n- `load_experiment_steps(experiment_dir)` -- Single-experiment step data.\n- `load_lifecycle_data(experiment_dir)` -- Per-request lifecycle from `results/per_request_lifecycle_metrics.json`. Returns DataFrame with `start_time`, `end_time`, `input_tokens`, `output_tokens`, `output_token_times` (list of per-token timestamps).\n- `parse_experiment_metadata(dirname)` -- Extracts model/tp/workload from directory name pattern `YYYYMMDD-HHMMSS-<model>-tp<N>-<workload>`.\n\nDefault data root: `eval/ground_truth/` relative to the shared directory (3 directories up).\n\n**`lifecycle_kv_extractor.py`** provides:\n- `extract_kv_features(steps_df, lifecycle_df)` -- For each step, identifies active requests (overlapping time windows), estimates each request's KV length as `input_tokens + output_tokens_generated_before_step_start`, computes `kv_mean`, `kv_max`, `kv_sum`, `kv_std`, `kv_count`.\n- `extract_all_experiments_kv_features(data_root)` -- Convenience wrapper that loads both data sources for all experiments and enriches steps with KV features.\n\n### 4. Training Data Schema\n\nStep-level features (from BATCH_SUMMARY OTLP events):\n\n| Column | Type | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| `step.id` | Int64 | Step sequence number |\n| `step.ts_start_ns` | Int64 | Nanosecond timestamp |\n| `step.ts_end_ns` | Int64 | Nanosecond timestamp |\n| `step.duration_us` | Int64 | **TARGET** -- GPU forward pass wall-clock time |\n| `batch.prefill_tokens` | Int64 | Prefill tokens this step |\n| `batch.decode_tokens` | Int64 | Decode tokens this step |\n| `batch.num_prefill_reqs` | Int64 | Prefill request count |\n| `batch.num_decode_reqs` | Int64 | Decode request count |\n| `batch.scheduled_tokens` | Int64 | Total scheduled tokens |\n| `batch.num_finished` | Int64 | Finished requests |\n| `batch.num_preempted` | Int64 | Preempted requests |\n| `queue.running_depth` | Int64 | Running queue state |\n| `queue.waiting_depth` | Int64 | Waiting queue state |\n| `kv.blocks_free_gpu` | Int64 | Free GPU KV blocks |\n| `kv.blocks_total_gpu` | Int64 | Total GPU KV blocks |\n| `kv.usage_gpu_ratio` | Float64 | GPU KV utilization |\n\nAfter KV enrichment (via `lifecycle_kv_extractor.py`), additional columns: `kv_mean`, `kv_max`, `kv_sum`, `kv_std`, `kv_count`.\n\nAfter interaction feature engineering (in `train_regime_ridge.py`): `prefill_x_decode`, `decode_x_kv_mean`, `prefill_sq`.\n\nThe data is ~10% sampled (OpenTelemetry tracing at ~10% rate). Total: 122,752 step observations from 12 experiments (4 models x 3 workloads), all on H100 80GB GPUs. Step durations span ~12us to ~250,000us.\n\n### 5. Overhead Floor Mechanism\n\nThe overhead floor is the most impactful technique discovered in Round 2. It exists in two places:\n\n**Go side** (`/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/BLIS-research/sim/latency/stepml.go`, lines 232-268):\n```go\nfunc (s *StepMLLatencyModel) StepTime(batch []*sim.Request) int64 {\n    // ... predict from features ...\n    \n    // Floor: max(overhead, compute)\n    if s.artifact.StepOverheadUs > 0 {\n        if prediction < s.artifact.StepOverheadUs {\n            prediction = s.artifact.StepOverheadUs\n        }\n        // Cap at 3x overhead to prevent exponential blowup\n        maxStep := s.artifact.StepOverheadUs * 3\n        if prediction > maxStep {\n            prediction = maxStep\n        }\n    }\n    \n    // Per-request overhead (additive)\n    if s.artifact.StepOverheadPerReqUs > 0 {\n        batchSize := features[\"num_prefill_reqs\"] + features[\"num_decode_reqs\"]\n        prediction += s.artifact.StepOverheadPerReqUs * batchSize\n    }\n    \n    // Minimum 1us (INV-M-1)\n    if prediction < 1 { prediction = 1 }\n}\n```\n\n**Python training side** (`/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/BLIS-research/hypotheses/h-stepml/round2/idea-2-regime-ensemble/h1-kv-regime-models/train_regime_ridge.py`, `compute_step_overhead` function, lines 293-344):\n- Computes per-model overhead as: `GT_ITL_mean_us - mean_compute_time_per_step`\n- Ground-truth ITL = full step cycle time in continuous batching\n- `step.duration_us` = GPU compute only\n- Skips reasoning workloads (negative overhead due to large-batch compute dominating)\n- The overhead is stored in the artifact JSON as `step_overhead_us`\n\nPer-model overhead constants (from Round 2):\n- Llama-2-7B TP1: 3,897 us\n- CodeLlama-34B TP2: 6,673 us\n- Llama-2-70B TP4: 8,029-8,203 us\n- Mixtral-8x7B TP2: 9,125 us\n\nThe mechanism works because 77.9% of steps are decode-only with small compute (~12-320us), far below the overhead floor (~4,000-9,000us). For these steps, the floor correctly sets the step time to the real cycle time. The 3x cap prevents exponential blowup from outlier feature values in the expm1 transform.\n\n### 6. Coefficient Export for BLIS Consumption\n\nThe artifact JSON format has two versions:\n\n**Version 1** (single model):\n```json\n{\n  \"version\": 1,\n  \"step_time\": {\n    \"model_type\": \"linear\",\n    \"intercept\": 100.0,\n    \"feature_coefficients\": {\"prefill_tokens\": 50.0, \"decode_tokens\": 5.0},\n    \"output_transform\": \"expm1\"  // optional, for log-space models\n  },\n  \"step_overhead_us\": 3897.0,\n  \"step_overhead_per_req_us\": 0.0,\n  \"output_token_processing_time_us\": 0.0,\n  \"scheduling_processing_time_us\": 0.0,\n  \"preemption_processing_time_us\": 0.0\n}\n```\n\n**Version 2** (regime-based):\n```json\n{\n  \"version\": 2,\n  \"step_time_regimes\": [\n    {\n      \"name\": \"decode_only\",\n      \"condition\": {\"feature\": \"prefill_tokens\", \"op\": \"==\", \"value\": 0},\n      \"model\": {\"model_type\": \"linear\", \"intercept\": -37.37, \"feature_coefficients\": {\"decode_tokens\": 7.95, \"num_decode_reqs\": 7.95}}\n    },\n    {\n      \"name\": \"mixed_light\",\n      \"condition\": {\"feature\": \"prefill_tokens\", \"op\": \"<\", \"value\": 256},\n      \"model\": {\"model_type\": \"linear\", \"intercept\": -77.98, \"feature_coefficients\": {...}}\n    },\n    {\n      \"name\": \"mixed_heavy\",\n      \"condition\": null,  // fallback\n      \"model\": {...}\n    }\n  ],\n  \"step_overhead_us\": 3896.76,\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nThe Python-to-Go feature name mapping (in `train_regime_ridge.py`, `_FEATURE_NAME_MAP`):\n- `batch.prefill_tokens` -> `prefill_tokens`\n- `batch.decode_tokens` -> `decode_tokens`\n- `batch.num_prefill_reqs` -> `num_prefill_reqs`\n- `batch.num_decode_reqs` -> `num_decode_reqs`\n- `kv_sum`, `kv_max`, `kv_mean`, `kv_std` -> same names\n- `prefill_x_decode`, `decode_x_kv_mean`, `prefill_sq` -> same names\n\nExport functions in `train_regime_ridge.py`:\n- `export_regime_artifact()` -- Writes version 2 with regime conditions\n- `export_single_artifact()` -- Writes version 1 for comparison\n- `_ridge_to_linear_model()` -- Converts sklearn Ridge to Go LinearModel format, optionally adding `\"output_transform\": \"expm1\"` for log-space models\n\n### 7. Round 2 Training Scripts (for reference)\n\nKey training scripts in `/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/BLIS-research/hypotheses/h-stepml/round2/`:\n\n- `idea-2-regime-ensemble/h1-kv-regime-models/train_regime_ridge.py` -- The most evolved training script. 3-regime Ridge per model, KV features, overhead computation, raw linear (not log-space), artifact export. This is the template for Round 3 experiments.\n- `idea-2-regime-ensemble/h2-blis-e2e-validation/validate_e2e.py` -- E2E validation wrapper\n- `idea-2-regime-ensemble/h3-secondary-method-calibration/calibrate_secondary.py` -- Secondary method constant extraction\n- `idea-2-regime-ensemble/h4-model-generalization/lomo_cv.py` -- Leave-one-model-out CV\n- `idea-2-regime-ensemble/h5-workload-generalization/lowo_cv.py` -- Leave-one-workload-out CV\n- `idea-1-bayesian-calibration/h1-piecewise-steptime/train_piecewise.py` -- 2-regime piecewise linear\n- `idea-1-bayesian-calibration/h2-joint-bo-calibration/bo_calibrate.py` -- Bayesian optimization\n\n### 8. Round 3 State\n\nThe `round3/` directory currently only contains `phase1_wp1_wp2.log` -- indicating that a Round 3 attempt was started but may not have completed. The `problem.md` has been updated with all Round 2 knowledge and identifies the primary blocker as TTFT/simulation fidelity mismatch (31,906% mean TTFT error).\n\n### 9. Available Python Dependencies\n\nFrom `requirements.txt`: pandas 2.2.3, pyarrow 18.1.0, scikit-learn 1.6.1, scipy 1.15.2, pytest 8.3.4, numpy 2.2.3, xgboost 2.1.4.\n\n### 10. Key Infrastructure Patterns for Round 3\n\nAny Round 3 experiment should follow this workflow:\n\n1. **Load data**: `extract_all_experiments_kv_features()` from `lifecycle_kv_extractor.py` (gets steps + KV features)\n2. **Add interactions**: `add_interaction_features()` from `train_regime_ridge.py`\n3. **Compute overhead**: `compute_step_overhead()` from `train_regime_ridge.py`\n4. **Split data**: `temporal_split()` per model from `splits.py`\n5. **Classify regimes**: `classify_regimes()` from `train_regime_ridge.py`\n6. **Train models**: scikit-learn Ridge/XGBoost per regime per model\n7. **Evaluate per-step**: `compute_mape`, `compute_pearson_r` etc. from `evaluation.py`\n8. **Export artifact**: `export_regime_artifact()` or `export_single_artifact()` to JSON\n9. **Validate E2E**: Either `validate_e2e.py` (per-model artifact selection) or `validate_blis.py` (explicit coefficients)\n10. **Generalization**: `leave_one_model_out()` and `leave_one_workload_out()` from `splits.py`"}],"totalDurationMs":136777,"totalTokens":5048,"totalToolUseCount":30,"usage":{"input_tokens":295,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":4753,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_018xuh4CeTtoPL5mUUjqzRat","type":"tool_result","content":"# DistServe Latency Model (Appendix A)\n\nI cannot extract the specific formulas and model details you've requested from the provided PDF content. While the document structure is visible in the PDF metadata, the actual mathematical content of Appendix A is not readable in the compressed stream data provided.\n\nTo access DistServe's latency modeling approach, I'd recommend:\n\n1. **Consulting the original paper directly** via the GitHub repository linked in the document (https://github.com/LLMServe/DistServe)\n\n2. **Key sections to examine** based on document structure:\n   - The document contains 19 pages with multiple appendices\n   - Algorithm sections (Algorithm 1 and 2 are referenced throughout)\n   - Section 3 discusses scheduling methodology\n   - Section 4 addresses evaluation methodology\n\n3. **Expected content areas** from the visible references:\n   - Prefill/decode phase modeling\n   - M/D/1 queue analysis for TTFT prediction\n   - Hardware profiling methodology\n   - Accuracy metrics and calibration procedures\n\nThe PDF's internal structure shows extensive mathematical content, but the actual equations and calibration specifics are in compressed stream objects that require the paper itself to properly interpret."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"cbaf768b-8988-469d-a20b-34c8109313f4"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01KnhU2ZzeLs5dWb37q6NDwR","type":"tool_result","content":"# Vidur's Execution Time Prediction Methodology\n\n## 1. Operator Profiling and Classification\n\nVidur classifies operators into three categories based on input dependencies:\n\n- **Token-level Operators**: Runtime depends on \"total number of tokens being processed (prefill plus decode) in the batch\" for operations like linear transformations and activations\n\n- **Sequence-level Operators**: Attention operations depend on \"number of tokens in the current batch but also the context length of each request\"\n\n- **Communication Operators**: Runtime depends \"only on the amount of data to be transferred\"\n\n## 2. Runtime Estimation Approach\n\nRather than profiling every input combination, Vidur uses machine learning models for interpolation. The system \"trains small machine-learning models to generate predictions over a large range of parameters.\" Specifically, it employs \"random forest (RF) regression models\" which \"achieve the right balance between data frugality and fidelity,\" avoiding both the data requirements of MLPs and the limitations of polynomial regression for CUDA kernels.\n\n## 3. Prefill vs. Decode Handling\n\n**Prefill Attention**: The cost is approximated as \"proportional to Σ(p_i²)\" where p_i represents individual prefill lengths. For a batch, Vidur predicts runtime as \"equivalent batch of a single prefill\" with equivalent length.\n\n**Decode Attention**: Since this phase is \"largely memory-bound,\" runtime depends on \"total data volume that needs to be fetched from the KV-Cache\" rather than individual context length distributions.\n\n## 4. Mixed Batch Composition\n\nThe document does not provide explicit details on handling mixed prefill-decode batches beyond noting that \"composition of a batch can accommodate requests from both prefill and/or decode phases.\"\n\n## 5. Accuracy Metrics\n\n- **Static workloads**: Predicts \"P95 latency with up to 3.33% error\" across models and datasets\n- **Dynamic workloads (85% capacity)**: Achieves \"<5% error in almost all scenarios\"\n- **Tail latencies**: \"Median normalized execution latency\" and \"P95 normalized execution latency\" both demonstrate high fidelity\n\nThe paper measures \"normalized end-to-end latency\" (request latency divided by output length) for dynamic workloads.\n\n## 6. CDF-Based Approach\n\nThe document does not describe a CDF-based methodology for execution time prediction.\n\n## 7. Batch Composition and Step Time Relationship\n\nVidur models this through operator-specific runtime estimators trained on profiled data, but the document does not provide explicit mathematical formulations for batch composition effects beyond the prefill attention case.\n\n## 8. Profiling Data Requirements\n\nMinimal profiling data is collected: Vidur profiles \"different tensor parallel sharding configurations\" for token-level operators and separately profiles \"attention kernels for prefill and decode phases.\" Communication operations are profiled independently in \"model-agnostic manner for different topologies.\"\n\n## 9. Execution Time Decomposition\n\nThe system decomposes models into \"small set of token-level, sequence-level and communication operators.\" Metrics tracked include \"each operator's input size and execution time\" to identify optimization targets. However, specific component-wise decomposition formulas are not detailed."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"403b7d9b-5883-42b4-abfc-c33184ab8141"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_bdrk_01SRmCiPkbMRRWpXDrq1y1L9","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"claude-opus-4-6","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_bdrk_01HNUK7VVBw4QzEMfgjdrDvg","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://dspace.mit.edu/bitstream/handle/1721.1/162997/wang-sarahyw-meng-eecs-2025-thesis.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y","prompt":"Extract the complete methodology for simulating LLM runtime latency. How does this thesis:\n1. Model step/iteration times?\n2. Handle the gap between per-step prediction and end-to-end latency accuracy?\n3. Calibrate against real traces?\n4. Predict TTFT and ITL?\n5. What accuracy do they achieve?\n6. What are the key findings about error accumulation?\n7. How do they handle CPU overhead vs GPU compute time?\n8. What regression/ML model do they use for step time prediction?"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7156,"output_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"55c2f337-d351-4054-8049-c28bcfed1dd6"}
