{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01H2BNBYiALxjVbroquokx62","type":"tool_result","content":"# Splitwise's Latency Modeling Approach\n\n## 1. Prefill Latency (Prompt Phase)\nSplitwise models prompt computation latency as computationally intensive and scaling linearly with input size. The characterization shows that \"TTFT for both models grows almost linearly as the prompt size increases\" due to the phase being \"compute-bound.\"\n\n## 2. Decode Latency (Token Generation Phase)\nToken generation latency is modeled as memory-constrained. The research demonstrates that \"the throughput in the token phase keeps increasing with batching until 64 batch-size,\" indicating memory bandwidth limitations rather than compute constraints.\n\n## 3. Step Time as Function of Batch Size and Sequence Length\nSplitwise uses \"a piece-wise linear performance model using performance profiles at various batch sizes, input sizes, output sizes\" to capture performance across different configurations.\n\n## 4. Profiling and Calibration\nThe system profiles the LLM \"on the target hardware with various input/output sizes\" and builds performance models from these measurements rather than using analytical formulas.\n\n## 5. Accuracy Achieved\nThe performance model demonstrates high fidelity: \"mean absolute percentage error (MAPE) of less than 3% when evaluated with a 80:20 train:test dataset split.\"\n\n## 6. Mixed Batch Handling\nFor mixed batches containing both phases, Splitwise employs \"mixed continuous batching\" where scheduling decisions occur at each forward pass, allowing \"prompt and token phases can run together.\""}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"d791890d-f37c-4649-808d-bfd99718f050"}
