{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_bdrk_01U866yPgyaXrTVj2Vt5CSqU","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"claude-opus-4-6","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_bdrk_019N8v3kHgqARqj2WysupQdy","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2403.02310v2","prompt":"Extract Sarathi-Serve's approach to iteration time modeling. Specifically:\n1. How does it model iteration time as a function of batch composition?\n2. What is the \"uniform batches\" concept?\n3. How does chunked prefill affect iteration time prediction?\n4. What is the relationship between chunk size, batch size, and step time?\n5. What is the stall-free scheduling guarantee?\n6. How does it handle prefill-decode interference?\n7. What is the key insight about keeping iteration times uniform?"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3188,"output_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"658a7e66-fc3d-4eb7-a453-af79369fe980"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01DoMGPkbepKRN9R9PteaXe2","type":"tool_result","content":"I appreciate your detailed request, but I must be transparent: the content you've provided appears to be a PDF file containing embedded binary data and compression streams (visible in the raw PDF structure with FlateDecode filters, object streams, and font definitions). This isn't readable text content that I can parse to extract methodology details about ReaLLM.\n\nTo help you effectively, I would need:\n\n1. **Plain text or properly extracted content** from the ReaLLM paper rather than raw PDF binary data\n2. **A direct link** to the research paper or publication\n3. **The paper title and authors** so I can discuss it from my training knowledge (up to April 2024)\n\n**What I can tell you generally about LLM inference simulation:**\n\nTrace-driven simulation typically involves: capturing real execution data, identifying latency components (prefill vs. decode phases), building regression models from observed patterns, and validating predictions against held-out traces. TTFT (time-to-first-token) and ITL (inter-token latency) are the standard metrics for predicting LLM generation performance.\n\nHowever, without access to the actual ReaLLM methodology text, I cannot responsibly cite the specific techniques, calibration approaches, or accuracy claims you're asking about. Would you be able to provide the paper content in an extractable format?"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"ed36dabe-dbc5-4247-9976-2df534c77213"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_019N8v3kHgqARqj2WysupQdy","type":"tool_result","content":"# Sarathi-Serve's Iteration Time Modeling Approach\n\n## 1. Iteration Time as a Function of Batch Composition\n\nSarathi-Serve models iteration time based on the mix of prefill and decode tokens. The system recognizes that \"each micro-batch (or iteration) in LLM inference can require a different amount of compute\" depending on whether it contains primarily prefill tokens (compute-bound) or decode tokens (memory-bound).\n\n## 2. Uniform Batches Concept\n\nThe core innovation is creating batches with consistent computational requirements. The paper states that \"uniform batches in Sarathi-Serve ameliorate the imbalance between iterations, resulting in minimal pipeline bubbles.\" This uniformity prevents GPU idle time, especially critical for pipeline-parallel deployments where one stage must wait for another to complete.\n\n## 3. Chunked Prefill Impact on Iteration Time\n\nBy splitting large prefills into smaller chunks, Sarathi-Serve bounds iteration latency predictably. Rather than unpredictable prefill durations (which can span seconds for long prompts), chunking ensures \"iterations with fewer prefill tokens have lower latency,\" making time predictions reliable.\n\n## 4. Chunk Size, Batch Size, and Step Time Relationships\n\nThe system uses a configurable \"token budget\" (τ) to control iteration time. This budget constrains total tokens per batch, ensuring iterations remain memory-bound rather than becoming compute-bound by mixing too many prefill tokens with decodes.\n\n## 5. Stall-Free Scheduling Guarantee\n\nStall-free batching prevents \"decodes never experience a generation stall due to a co-running prefill chunk\" by restricting prefill computation to available arithmetic-intensity slack within decode iterations.\n\n## 6. Prefill-Decode Interference Handling\n\nThe scheduler prioritizes ongoing decodes first, then adds prefill chunks within the token budget. This prevents the interference problem where \"eagerly scheduling prefills of requests...delays the decodes of already running requests.\"\n\n## 7. Key Insight: Uniform Iteration Times\n\nThe fundamental principle is that consistent iteration times eliminate pipeline bubbles by avoiding scenarios where \"single prompt of 4k tokens takes ≈1150 ms to execute compared to...batch size 32 which would take about ≈200 ms,\" preventing GPU idleness in multi-stage deployments."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"8dea0f5b-e0e7-48d2-96ea-58b4acb15258"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_bdrk_01LXZkBEkKmePqFYSVKc6sKF","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"claude-opus-4-6","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_bdrk_01PvsL4HrkubPLGFzKjotfbw","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://www.usenix.org/system/files/osdi22-yu.pdf","prompt":"Extract Orca's approach to:\n1. Iteration-level scheduling - how does it model and schedule individual iterations?\n2. How does it predict or measure iteration time?\n3. What is selective batching and how does it affect step time?\n4. How does continuous batching change the relationship between batch size and iteration time?\n5. What is the key insight about keeping iteration times predictable?"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3551,"output_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"ffb88496-15e9-4958-b097-c60de99c8f39"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_bdrk_01LXZkBEkKmePqFYSVKc6sKF","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"claude-opus-4-6","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_bdrk_012LSmyghz7FGhN4LHGjvrdy","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2405.05465v2","prompt":"Extract the COMPLETE methodology from the Vidur paper published at MLSys 2024. I need:\n1. How does Vidur profile and predict execution times for each iteration?\n2. What is the random forest approach for operator-level prediction?\n3. What specific accuracy numbers (TTFT, TPOT, end-to-end) does it achieve?\n4. How does it handle mixed batches (prefill + decode)?\n5. How does it model the relationship between batch composition and step time?\n6. What are the key findings about simulation fidelity?\n7. How does it handle the CDF of latency distributions?"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3551,"output_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"9a22f031-86bb-458f-8d69-d00443647c2b"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01PvsL4HrkubPLGFzKjotfbw","type":"tool_result","content":"I appreciate your detailed request, but I need to be honest: the provided content appears to be a PDF file encoded in binary/compressed format rather than readable text. The \"%PDF-1.5\" header and subsequent streams contain FlateDecode-compressed data that I cannot extract or interpret directly.\n\nTo properly address your questions about Orca's approach to iteration-level scheduling, iteration time prediction, selective batching, continuous batching effects, and iteration time consistency, I would need:\n\n1. **Plain text or readable format** of the actual paper content\n2. **Specific sections** discussing these technical concepts\n3. **Readable figures or tables** showing scheduling mechanisms\n\n**What I can suggest:**\n- If you have access to the PDF, copy-paste the relevant sections as plain text\n- Share specific page numbers or section headings\n- Provide extracted text from the original research paper\n\nWithout accessible content, I cannot provide the specific citations and technical details you're requesting while maintaining the 125-character quote limit and attribution standards you've outlined.\n\nWould you like to re-submit with readable text content?"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"7d42ef3a-2ce8-4c1d-9ba4-295c9674dd5a"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_012LSmyghz7FGhN4LHGjvrdy","type":"tool_result","content":"# Vidur Methodology: Complete Extraction\n\n## 1. Profiling and Execution Time Prediction\n\nVidur employs a two-phase approach:\n\n**Profiling Phase**: The system identifies operators from model specifications and collects runtime data using CUPTI for different tensor parallel configurations on a single GPU, avoiding expensive multi-GPU profiling.\n\n**Prediction Phase**: \"Small machine-learning models\" interpolate runtimes across input ranges not explicitly profiled, generating operation-wise lookup tables for simulation.\n\n## 2. Random Forest Approach for Operator Prediction\n\nRather than MLPs (which require extensive data) or polynomial regression (which misses nonlinear CUDA kernel behaviors), the system uses \"random forest (RF) regression models\" because they \"achieve the right balance between data frugality and fidelity.\"\n\n## 3. Accuracy Metrics Achieved\n\n- **Static workloads**: Predicts P95 latency with \"up to 3.33% error\" across four models and three datasets\n- **Dynamic workloads**: Achieves \"<5% error\" at 85% system capacity\n- **Overall**: \"Less than 9% error rate\" for request-level inference performance\n\n## 4. Mixed Batch Handling (Prefill + Decode)\n\nThe framework classifies operators into three categories:\n\n- **Token-level**: Runtime depends only on total tokens in batch\n- **Sequence-level**: Runtime depends on context length (attention operations)\n- **Communication**: Runtime depends only on data volume transferred\n\n## 5. Batch Composition and Step Time Modeling\n\n**Prefill attention**: Models as proportional to Σ(prefill_length²), approximating runtime using equivalent single-prefill batch at √(Σp²)\n\n**Decode attention**: Treated as memory-bound; runtime determined by \"total data volume that needs to be fetched from the KV-Cache\"\n\n## 6. Key Simulation Fidelity Findings\n\n- Optimal configurations vary significantly by model-trace pair, not just model\n- Misconfiguration can cause \"up to 2× cost difference\" on different workloads\n- Configuration search costs only $125 in simulation versus $1.14 million in actual hardware execution\n\n## 7. CDF of Latency Distributions\n\nThe paper does not explicitly detail CDF modeling. Instead, it reports percentile-based metrics (P90 TTFT, P95/P99 latency) and normalized end-to-end latency distributions across request populations, measuring prediction error at these percentile points rather than reconstructing full distributions."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"5a14d623-32ec-44f7-b6df-2d01a3c64e33"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_bdrk_01JjJ5Vfdc3KqxRpm8wQAywm","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"claude-opus-4-6","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_bdrk_013HFBtpyaeD3rtckmQ7tdGU","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2508.03611v2","prompt":"Extract Block's approach to LLM serving simulation and load balancing. Specifically:\n1. How does it use simulation for scheduling decisions?\n2. What latency prediction approach does it use?\n3. What error rates does it achieve?\n4. How does it handle the gap between per-step prediction and end-to-end latency?\n5. What calibration approach does it use?\n6. How does it predict request completion time?"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2916,"output_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"dbec7811-b3d4-4975-b3bb-30b892ed101c"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_bdrk_01JjJ5Vfdc3KqxRpm8wQAywm","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"claude-opus-4-6","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_bdrk_0142dZiRUzhPKcqZ8Yqrh3X3","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://www2.eecs.berkeley.edu/Pubs/TechRpts/2025/EECS-2025-192.pdf","prompt":"Extract the vLLM thesis/tech report's approach to performance modeling. Specifically:\n1. How does vLLM model or predict step/iteration times?\n2. What factors affect batch processing latency?\n3. How does batch size affect step time?\n4. What is the relationship between sequence length, KV cache, and iteration time?\n5. How does continuous batching affect predictability of step times?\n6. What are the key observations about latency variability?"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2916,"output_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"678f800b-73c0-4b83-b784-2e3665ba755f"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_013HFBtpyaeD3rtckmQ7tdGU","type":"tool_result","content":"# Block's Simulation and Load Balancing Approach\n\n## 1. Simulation-Based Scheduling\n\nBlock uses a two-stage simulation process adapted from Vidur. First, a \"local scheduler simulator models the batching strategy\" for the inference backend. Second, \"a linear model predicts the execution times for the batches generated in the first stage.\" These predictions inform routing decisions by selecting instances with the lowest projected latency.\n\n## 2. Latency Prediction Approach\n\nThe system employs a lightweight RoBERTa-base regression model (125M parameters) to estimate response lengths based on input prompts. This length estimate feeds into the simulator to predict end-to-end metrics. The researchers note this is more efficient than larger models while achieving comparable accuracy.\n\n## 3. Error Rates\n\nThe length prediction model achieves \"average 24.4% errors\" compared to actual outputs. For simulation-based metric prediction, the system maintains \"prediction error rate...consistently...between 10% to 15%\" across varying load conditions.\n\n## 4. Gap Between Per-Step and End-to-End Latency\n\nBlock addresses this through its deterministic simulation framework. The researchers observe that \"the 10-15% prediction error is not expected entirely skew instance selection, as it includes a constant overhead that uniformly impacts all instances.\"\n\n## 5. Calibration Approach\n\nWhen actual decoded lengths exceed predictions, the system \"dynamically adjusts the estimated length for prediction by using the monitored decode length plus another 10 steps,\" enabling online refinement.\n\n## 6. Request Completion Time Prediction\n\nBlock predicts completion time by simulating batching behavior under current instance state, then applying profiled linear models to interpolate batch execution times based on batch size and token counts, using cached results for previously seen configurations."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"c51ecb38-2bf7-49f5-b2c5-711388d20857"}
