{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01HrpRxAP53fckDNTrbiqVB3","type":"tool_result","content":"# TTFT Prediction in LLM Serving: Analysis of DIRAS Paper\n\nI've reviewed the provided content, which is the DIRAS paper on document relevance annotation for RAG systems. **This paper does not address TTFT (Time To First Token) prediction in LLM serving.**\n\n## Key Finding\n\nDIRAS focuses exclusively on information retrieval annotation methodology. The paper's scope covers:\n- Fine-tuning smaller LLMs to annotate document relevance\n- Creating domain-specific training data for IR systems\n- Evaluating retrieval quality through calibrated confidence scores\n\n## Why TTFT is Not Addressed\n\nThe paper makes no mention of:\n- Token generation latency metrics\n- Request queuing dynamics\n- Batch processing performance characteristics\n- Prefill computation timing\n- Time-to-first-token decomposition\n\nDIRAS is a retrieval system tool, not an LLM serving infrastructure paper. It addresses the upstream problem of identifying which documents are relevant to queries, rather than downstream inference performance metrics.\n\n---\n\n**Recommendation**: To find TTFT prediction research, you would need papers specifically focused on LLM inference optimization, serving systems (like vLLM, TensorRT-LLM), or batching strategies in production deployments."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"4bed8e83-b8d6-4c16-a08e-f40dccc2f1c5"}
