{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_015vLiZbSHE7YqpjggEFX5Nq","type":"tool_result","content":"# MIT Thesis: Simulating LLM Runtime Latency\n\n## Overview\nSarah Wang's 2025 Master's thesis introduces **vLLMSim**, a simulator designed to estimate Large Language Model latency across different hardware configurations and workloads.\n\n## Key Details from Available Content\n\n**Main Purpose:**\nThe thesis addresses the challenge that \"LLM latency is highly task–specific and depends on factors such as offered query load, hardware configurations, request properties, and model characteristics.\"\n\n**Primary Applications:**\n1. Informing users' model and hardware selection decisions\n2. Enabling researchers to rapidly evaluate latency-reduction strategies without time-consuming implementations\n\n**Notable Implementation:**\nThe work is already integrated into two active research projects focused on reducing LLM inference costs and latency.\n\n## Limitations of This Source\n\nThe webpage excerpt provided contains only the abstract and metadata. Specific technical details you requested—including:\n- Exact accuracy metrics\n- Step time modeling methodology\n- TTFT (Time To First Token) prediction mechanisms\n- Calibration procedures against actual vLLM performance\n\n—are not available in this excerpt. These implementation specifics would be contained within the full thesis PDF, which would need to be reviewed directly for comprehensive technical analysis.\n\n**Advisor:** Samuel Madden, MIT EECS"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"b8969943-fcd5-44cf-8f29-3b14f919d1c9"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_0177F9uprGTd6iKCjcj6twSo","type":"tool_result","content":"# AIConfigurator: Latency Prediction and Simulation Methodology\n\n## 1. Iteration/Step Time Modeling\n\nAIConfigurator decomposes inference into fundamental operations rather than treating it as a black box. Each inference step is modeled as \"running a fixed sequence of operators for a number of times, typically depending on the number of layers.\" The key operators include GEMM computations, attention mechanisms (prefill or decode variants), communication primitives (AllReduce, AllGather), and MoE dispatch/combine patterns. Step latency is calculated by aggregating performance profiles of these constituent operators queried from a calibrated database.\n\n## 2. TTFT and TPOT Prediction\n\nThe system derives Time-To-First-Token and Time-Per-Output-Token from steady-state request analysis rather than direct estimation:\n\n- **TTFT** approximates prefill phase latency plus a correction factor accounting for scheduling overhead\n- **TPOT** averages subsequent decode step latencies, calculated as: \"Generation Speed = 1000/TPOT\"\n\nFor aggregated serving, \"TTFT is estimated based on the latency of the Mixed Phase, incorporating an empirical correction factor modeled as a piecewise linear function.\"\n\n## 3. Continuous Batching Simulation\n\nThe aggregated mode algorithm divides execution into two phases:\n\n- **Mixed Phase**: Prefill and decode requests run concurrently; scheduler allocates context capacity to prefills, remaining slots to decoding. When prefill dominates, the system \"throttles the number of concurrent decode streams using a rate-matching heuristic\" to prevent starvation.\n- **Generation-Only Phase**: Pure decoding when the prefill queue drains.\n\nTPOT uses weighted averaging of both phases' latencies, with a \"small offset (3 steps) to the mixed phase duration...filtering out scheduling jitter.\"\n\n## 4. Achieved Accuracy\n\n- **TPOT prediction**: 6-12% Mean Absolute Percentage Error across dense and MoE models; individual results include 8.2% for Qwen3-32B-TensorRT-LLM, 6.8% for Qwen3-235B MoE\n- **TTFT prediction**: 16-22% MAPE; within the interactive speed region (25-50 tokens/s/user), accuracy improves to 3.35% for generation speed\n- **Disaggregated serving**: 13.19% throughput and 3.35% generation speed MAPE in practical operating regions\n\n## 5. Calibration Against Real Systems\n\nAIConfigurator employs a data-driven foundation through:\n\n- **Exhaustive profiling**: Framework-native tools sweep parameters (batch size, sequence length, hidden dimension) accumulating approximately 30 GPU-hours per platform-framework pair\n- **Interpolation**: Intermediate configurations estimated from profiled data points\n- **Speed-of-Light estimation**: Analytical roofline bounds for unprofiled operators\n- **Power-law correction for MoE**: Synthetic token assignment emulates production load imbalance (e.g., \"~70% of compute handled by only 20% of active experts\" in Qwen3-235B)\n\nThe system operates on NVIDIA platforms (Ampere, Ada, Hopper, Blackwell) and supports TensorRT-LLM, vLLM, and SGLang.\n\n## 6. Key Configuration Optimization Insight\n\nThe critical finding is that \"traditional heuristics like 'TP within node, PP across nodes' fail to capture non-linear interactions between compute and network bandwidth.\" AIConfigurator identifies that optimal configurations depend on workload mix, hardware topology, and interconnect bandwidth—demonstrating that disaggregated serving isn't universally superior but context-dependent. In one case study, disaggregated configuration achieved \"101.6% throughput improvement over the aggregated baseline,\" completing searches in seconds rather than days of GPU benchmarking."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"d4322e8e-c204-4e33-a687-98533b7d2207"}
