{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01XPoTmmzirx6MoPoJy25WpB","type":"tool_result","content":"# HERMES Paper Details\n\n**Title:** Understanding and Optimizing Multi-Stage AI Inference Pipelines\n\n**Authors:** Abhimanyu Rajeshkumar Bambhaniya, Hanjiang Wu, Suvinay Subramanian, Sudarshan Srinivasan, Souvik Kundu, Amir Yazdanbakhsh, Midhilesh Elavazhagan, Madhu Kumar, Tushar Krishna\n\n**Abstract Summary:** \nThe paper addresses simulation gaps for modern LLM serving pipelines. It introduces HERMES, a simulator designed to model heterogeneous, multi-stage inference workflows. \"HERMES models diverse request stages; including RAG, KV retrieval, reasoning, prefill, and decode across complex hardware hierarchies.\"\n\n**Key Contribution for LLM Inference Simulation:**\nThe system tackles multi-stage complexity by integrating real hardware traces with analytical modeling. Notably, \"HERMES supports heterogeneous clients executing multiple models concurrently unlike prior frameworks while incorporating advanced batching strategies and multi-level memory hierarchies.\"\n\nThis enables researchers to evaluate critical performance factors such as memory bandwidth contention, communication latency between clusters, and batching efficiency—providing actionable design insights for next-generation AI infrastructure."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"2b3d20dd-2638-4506-8b76-324069374218"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_bdrk_01MWBpZyeBBWD1gXxVhogJQb","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"claude-opus-4-6","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_bdrk_01WdQdwTv2nkoB4FZm7QXKYq","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2504.09775v2","prompt":"Extract the COMPLETE HERMES/MIST framework details. I need:\n1. The exact ML model used for step time prediction (ensemble regressors)\n2. What features/inputs the model takes (batch size, sequence lengths, etc.)\n3. How the 200k+ datapoints were collected\n4. What the 2.5% average error refers to specifically\n5. How end-to-end accuracy of 6% is achieved from per-step 2.5%\n6. How TTFT is modeled\n7. How it validates against vLLM on H100\n8. What is the key insight about error propagation from steps to E2E?"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"output_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"29748725-33a1-4d10-b25d-3b4d6f2297fb"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01WdQdwTv2nkoB4FZm7QXKYq","type":"tool_result","content":"# HERMES ML-Assisted Prediction Framework\n\n## ML Model Architecture\n\nThe paper specifies **polynomial regression models** rather than ensemble regressors:\n\n> \"We use polynomial regression models decode runtime with mean square error(MSE) = 4.09e-07. Prefill runtime is modeled using past token count, prefill token count, batch size, and token2, with MSE = 6.49e-05.\"\n\n## Input Features\n\n**Decode stage inputs:**\n- Batch size\n- Number of past tokens\n- Tensor parallelism configuration (TP2/TP4/TP8)\n\n**Prefill stage inputs:**\n- Past token count\n- Prefill token count\n- Batch size\n- Token² (quadratic term)\n\n## Data Collection\n\nThe framework trained on \"58K datapoints on a DGX-H100 box running vLLM with LLaMA2-70B,\" varying input size, batch size, chunk size (for chunked batching), and tensor parallelism levels. The dataset composition shows \"decode batches constitute ∼96% of the dataset.\"\n\n## Error Metrics\n\nThe **2.5% average error** specifically refers to end-to-end runtime validation against vLLM on H100 hardware with varying parallelization, context lengths, and batch sizes. The **6% maximum error** represents disaggregated serving validation against Splitwise-sim across different models and RPS rates.\n\n## Key Insight on Error Propagation\n\nThe paper does not explicitly detail how per-step errors compound to end-to-end predictions, but indicates integration with \"real hardware traces with analytical modeling\" to mitigate compounding effects rather than discussing explicit error propagation mechanisms."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"7df4ce5b-af45-4abf-93f6-86ee8d59237c"}
