{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01BiDUwSmLQYjFr2vvPU3imT","type":"tool_result","content":"# Latency Prediction Methodology\n\nBased on my review of the provided content, **this survey does not contain a methodology for predicting LLM inference latency**. \n\nThe document is a comprehensive survey on efficient inference for Large Language Models that covers:\n- Data-level optimization (input compression, output organization)\n- Model-level optimization (efficient structures, model compression)\n- System-level optimization (inference engines, serving systems)\n\nWhile the paper discusses latency as an efficiency metric and defines relevant terms like \"first token latency\" and \"per-output token latency,\" it does not present:\n\n1. **Step/iteration time modeling** - No mathematical framework provided\n2. **TTFT prediction methods** - Not addressed\n3. **Regression or analytical models** - Not developed in this survey\n4. **Iteration time decomposition** - Not specified\n5. **Accuracy metrics** - No latency prediction accuracy reported\n6. **Mixed batch handling** - Not discussed\n\nThe survey focuses on *techniques to improve* latency rather than *methods to predict* it. To find latency prediction methodologies, you would need to consult papers specifically addressing performance modeling or benchmarking systems for LLMs, which are not the focus of this particular survey."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"6f503bd2-0c7c-442b-ba39-d1bc8ddf1a71"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_019WWrxHqcF8iNoyS1tLPajn","type":"tool_result","content":"# ServerlessLLM Latency Modeling Analysis\n\nBased on the provided paper content, ServerlessLLM's latency modeling is **limited in scope** and focuses on system components rather than comprehensive LLM inference prediction.\n\n## Key Findings:\n\n### 1. **Step/Iteration Time Prediction**\nServerlessLLM does not explicitly model per-token generation time. Instead, it uses an empirical approach: \"with the inference duration (d) and the average time to produce a token (t), we calculate t_out = d/t\" (Section 6.2).\n\nThis is a **simple linear model** rather than a sophisticated prediction mechanism.\n\n### 2. **TTFT (Time to First Token) Prediction**\nThe system does not directly predict TTFT. Instead, ServerlessLLM focuses on **model startup latency**, which includes loading time but not generation time. Their metric is \"model startup latency, a critical metric for serverless inference scenarios.\"\n\n### 3. **Calibration Methodology**\nServerlessLLM employs **online learning**: \"The scheduler monitors the loading latency returned by the servers. It leverages the monitoring metrics to continuously improve its estimation of the bandwidth through different storage media\" (Section 6.1).\n\nNo formal calibration dataset or methodology is described.\n\n### 4. **Accuracy Achieved**\nMeasured error bounds: \"The GPU time estimation error is bounded at 5ms, while the SSD loading error is bounded at 40ms\" (Section 7.3). However, they note instability: \"average underestimation of 25.78 ms\" with occasional \"maximum underestimation of 623 ms\" in GPU state cleanup operations.\n\n**Conclusion**: ServerlessLLM prioritizes system component prediction over comprehensive LLM inference latency modeling."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"f3701ff9-2feb-4d12-820a-18124466fcbb"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_bdrk_012F454DWfPsFUFNVUQbdipu","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"claude-opus-4-6","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_bdrk_017vLa4yM1Cq7dwDJRoKCcGQ","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2602.23036v1","prompt":"Extract LLMServingSim 2.0's approach to step time prediction and calibration. Specifically:\n1. How does it model iteration/step times?\n2. How does it handle TTFT prediction?\n3. What accuracy does it achieve for TTFT and ITL?\n4. How does it calibrate against real systems?\n5. What are its key insights about the gap between per-step and end-to-end accuracy?\n6. How does it compare to Vidur, HERMES, Revati, and TokenSim?\n7. What profiling-based or analytical approach does it use?\n8. How does it handle continuous batching and chunked prefill?"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3541,"output_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"8fda0948-dbbb-402c-9a7f-3b6e409416b7"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_017vLa4yM1Cq7dwDJRoKCcGQ","type":"tool_result","content":"# LLMServingSim 2.0's Step Time and Latency Prediction Approach\n\nBased on the provided document, here's what LLMServingSim 2.0 employs for timing prediction:\n\n## Step Time Modeling\n\nLLMServingSim 2.0 uses **profile-based operator performance modeling**. The system \"measures operator-level latency and power using only a single decode block per model-device pair\" through an Operator-level Profiler built on PyTorch/HuggingFace, typically completing within 2.1 hours per model-device combination.\n\n## TTFT and ITL Prediction\n\nThe simulator predicts latency through a **runtime-driven execution graph approach**. It constructs execution DAGs encoding \"data dependencies, ordering constraints, parallelism strategies, and the required communication and memory operations,\" then evaluates these through the System Simulator accounting for \"synchronization overhead, network contention, inter-device communication, and memory access latency.\"\n\n## Achieved Accuracy\n\nLLMServingSim 2.0 demonstrates strong validation results:\n- **Aggregate performance metrics**: 0.85% error on RTX A6000, 1.59% on H100\n- **Time-series throughput**: 5.66% error on RTX A6000, 2.98% on H100\n- **Overall average**: 0.97% error across representative workloads\n- **Memory/prefix metrics**: 0.93-0.41% average error\n\n## Real System Calibration\n\nValidation occurs against \"real GPU systems running vLLM\" across three platforms: RTX A6000, H100, and TPU-v6e-1, using workloads sampled from ShareGPT with Poisson-distributed arrivals at 10 requests/second.\n\n## Comparison to Other Simulators\n\nThe document notes LLMServingSim 2.0 \"achieves high accuracy across all metrics, with an average error of 2.35%\" versus prior simulators that \"tend to be accurate only for specific metrics.\" However, the paper doesn't provide detailed head-to-head comparisons with Vidur, HERMES, Revati, or TokenSim on step-time accuracy specifically.\n\n## Key Profiling Approach\n\nThe system combines \"operator-level profiles from external hardware simulators\" with per-device profiling, enabling \"interaction-aware evaluation of future accelerator and PIM-based systems without requiring physical hardware.\"\n\n**Note**: The document doesn't explicitly discuss continuous batching calibration or chunked prefill timing strategies."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"2c86c135-394e-46a2-80bb-083b0de33433"}
