{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_bdrk_01JvWzvEXTZdca3Jsh9Nooxd","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"claude-opus-4-6","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_bdrk_01WnegFyG7wrXEMvRhqPLGR5","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2508.03611v1","prompt":"Extract Block's COMPLETE approach to simulation-based load balancing. I need:\n1. How does the local scheduler simulator model batching strategy?\n2. What is the linear model for batch execution time?\n3. How does it predict per-request TTFT and TPOT?\n4. What is the 10-15% prediction error breakdown?\n5. How does it handle online calibration (dynamic length adjustment)?\n6. What features does the linear model use (batch size, total tokens)?\n7. How does it handle the gap between step prediction and E2E latency?"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2130,"output_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"0540b74a-9ff0-4717-88a3-ebda619c52c1"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01KGBgciMc4dzVsSmuMmRDW2","type":"tool_result","content":"# BiScale's Batch Completion and TTFT Prediction Approach\n\n## 1. Batch Completion Time Modeling\n\nBiScale uses data-driven latency models trained offline for each (LLM model, GPU type) pair. The latency model predicts execution time for a single batch as a function of: \"(1) number of requests in the batch, (2) sum, mean, and standard deviation of input lengths, (3) tensor-parallel (TP) degree, and (4) GPU SM frequency.\" They employ histogram gradient boosting trees due to their nonlinear modeling capacity and low inference overhead.\n\n## 2. TTFT Derivation for Active Requests\n\nDuring MPC-based prefill control, the system performs three steps:\n\n- **Batch projection**: Current waiting and running requests are simulated to determine scheduling into the next N future batches\n- **Frequency evaluation**: Candidate frequency assignments are evaluated using the latency model to \"predict batch completion times and derive projected TTFT for all active requests\"\n- **Feasible energy minimization**: Among SLO-compliant assignments, the lowest-energy option is selected\n\n## 3. Energy-Aware Phase Management\n\nBiScale's two-tier approach separates concerns:\n\n- **Tier 1** (coarse-grained): Determines placement minimizing energy while satisfying SLOs under peak load\n- **Tier 2** (fine-grained): Applies stage-specific DVFS—MPC for prefill's bursty, compute-bound dynamics and lightweight per-batch adaptation for decode's smoother, memory-bound behavior\n\n## 4. Latency Prediction Accuracy\n\nThe latency models achieve strong accuracy: \"MAPE of 2.9% for prefill instances and 2.7% for decode instances,\" with simulator validation showing comparable results (2.3% MAPE for prefill energy, 1.2% for decode).\n\n## 5. Prefill-Decode Interaction Handling\n\nThe ILP provisioning formulation enforces independent capacity constraints: \"prefill and decode independently have sufficient capacity to handle the target goodput.\" This prevents under-provisioning one phase from being compensated by over-provisioning the other, ensuring both phases maintain SLO compliance under their distinct workload characteristics."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"e38bf237-20f6-4a48-bffe-c1e40b9e97aa"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01WnegFyG7wrXEMvRhqPLGR5","type":"tool_result","content":"# Block's Simulation-Based Load Balancing Approach\n\n## 1. Local Scheduler Simulator\n\nBlock adapts the batching strategy modeling from Vidur through a two-stage process. The simulator \"models the batching strategy for a given inference backend,\" then applies execution time predictions. For vLLM specifically, the implementation required minimal effort—\"the new vLLM simulator is only 161 lines of code.\"\n\n## 2. Linear Model for Batch Execution\n\nThe framework uses \"linear models to interpolate execution times for various batches\" based on profiling low-level operators like attention and linear projections on specific GPUs. These models predict batch completion times from configured hardware and batch characteristics.\n\n## 3. Per-Request TTFT and TPOT Prediction\n\nThe paper does not explicitly detail separate mechanisms for Time-To-First-Token versus Time-Per-Output-Token prediction. Instead, the system predicts \"end-to-end latency\" and overall serving metrics through simulation of the complete batching lifecycle.\n\n## 4. Prediction Error Breakdown (10-15%)\n\nThe evaluation reveals that \"overall error rates between 10% to 15% confirm the simulator's high accuracy.\" The authors note this error \"includes a constant overhead that uniformly impacts all instances and therefore does not alter their relative latency rankings\"—meaning relative instance comparison remains reliable.\n\n## 5. Online Calibration with Dynamic Length Adjustment\n\nWhen actual decoded lengths exceed predictions, \"the simulator dynamically adjusts estimated length for prediction by using the monitored decode length plus an additional 10 steps.\"\n\n## 6. Linear Model Features\n\nThe paper specifies two primary inputs: batch size and token count (encoding both context and decoding phases). These configure batch simulation without detailing additional feature engineering.\n\n## 7. Step Prediction to E2E Latency Gap\n\nBlock quantifies scheduling overhead as \"approximately 80 ms within capacity,\" representing the difference between end-to-end client latencies and vLLM-side execution time. This overhead derives primarily from simulation and RPC communication costs."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"7634b47b-dde4-4e05-9b1e-f05ed6273cec"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ET3SZbYVS2gFM9krv6mM9v","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have comprehensive information. Let me compile the findings.\n\n---\n\n# Literature Survey: LLM Inference Latency Prediction and Simulator Calibration\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThis survey covers 12+ systems and papers relevant to BLIS's calibration challenges. The findings point to a clear diagnosis of your 31,906% TTFT error and 427.8% E2E error: **the dominant issue is almost certainly not step-time prediction but rather simulation-level fidelity (request lifecycle, scheduler reimplementation, arrival pattern matching)**. The state of the art has converged on a consistent set of techniques that achieve <5% E2E error. Below is each system's approach, ordered by relevance to your problem.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Revati (Microsoft/Georgia Tech, Jan 2025)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2601.00397\n\n**Key Technique:** \"Time-warp\" simulation — instead of reimplementing the scheduler, Revati intercepts CUDA API calls via LD_PRELOAD and runs the *actual* vLLM/SGLang control plane (scheduler, batch formation, KV cache manager). GPU compute calls become no-ops replaced by predicted durations.\n\n**Step Time Prediction:** Uses an analytical/ML runtime prediction layer accepting batch composition (prefill count, decode count, sequence lengths) and hardware specs. The key insight: \"GPU computation accounts for 90-95% of total execution time, with CPU overhead remaining minimal.\"\n\n**TTFT/ITL Accuracy:** <5% prediction error across TTFT and TPOT for Llama-3.1-8B, Llama-3.1-70B, and Qwen3-30B-A3B on both vLLM and SGLang. 5-17x faster than real GPU execution.\n\n**Calibration:** No explicit calibration needed -- by running the real control plane, scheduler behavior is captured automatically. Memory allocations under 4MB get real backing (for control decisions); compute buffers get virtual pointers.\n\n**Critical Insight for BLIS:** Revati's key finding is that **reimplemented schedulers diverge from real systems**. Vidur required only ~150 lines of code for the original vLLM scheduler but became untenable as vLLM evolved. The simulator maintenance burden causes subtle timing divergences that compound into large E2E errors. **This is the most likely explanation for your 31,906% TTFT error** -- BLIS's reimplemented request lifecycle (arrival, queueing, batch formation, prefill scheduling) diverges from real vLLM behavior.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Vidur (Microsoft Research, MLSys 2024)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2405.05465\n\n**Key Technique:** Operator-level profiling + random forest interpolation. Classifies operations into three categories:\n- **Token-level operators** (linear, activation): runtime depends on total tokens in batch\n- **Sequence-level operators** (attention): runtime depends on per-request context lengths\n- **Communication operators**: runtime depends only on data volume\n\n**Step Time Prediction:** Random forest (RF) regression models trained on profiled data. For prefill attention, cost is proportional to sum(p_i^2) where p_i = individual prefill lengths. For decode attention, runtime determined by total KV cache data volume (memory-bound). RF chosen for \"the right balance between data frugality and fidelity\" vs MLPs (need too much data) and polynomial regression (miss CUDA kernel nonlinearities).\n\n**TTFT/ITL Accuracy:**\n- Static workloads: P95 latency with up to 3.33% error\n- Dynamic workloads (85% capacity): <5% error in almost all scenarios\n- Overall: <9% error rate for request-level inference performance\n\n**Calibration:** Profile operators via CUPTI for different TP configurations on single GPU. ~150 lines of code to reimplement vLLM scheduler. Train small RF models to interpolate across input ranges.\n\n**Relevance:** Vidur achieves good accuracy but **only when the scheduler reimplementation is faithful**. As Revati noted, scheduler divergence is the Achilles heel. The RF approach for step-time prediction is solid and achieves <5% per-step, but step-time is not your binding constraint.\n\n---\n\n## 3. HERMES/MIST (Georgia Tech, Apr 2025)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2504.09775\n\n**Key Technique:** Multi-stage simulation framework with three layers (Workload, System/Software, Hardware). Uses ensemble regressors for step-time prediction.\n\n**Step Time Prediction:** Polynomial regression models:\n- **Decode:** Features = batch_size, past_token_count, TP config. MSE = 4.09e-07\n- **Prefill:** Features = past_token_count, prefill_token_count, batch_size, token^2 (quadratic term). MSE = 6.49e-05\n- Trained on 58K datapoints on DGX-H100 running vLLM with LLaMA2-70B\n\n**Accuracy:**\n- Per-step: 2.5% average error with <1% median\n- End-to-end: <2% error vs vLLM on H100 (aggregated-offline), 5.3% (aggregated-online at 5 QPS), <6% (disaggregated with Azure traces)\n\n**TTFT Model:** Modeled through discrete-event simulation incorporating queuing delays + execution times. Six pipeline stages (Preprocess, RAG, Prefill, Decode, KV Retrieval, Postprocess).\n\n**Key Insight:** \"End-to-end performance emerges from interactions across stages, across clients, and across layers -- not isolated operations.\" This validates that **per-step accuracy alone is insufficient**; the simulation of request flow is equally critical.\n\n---\n\n## 4. FairBatching (2025)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2510.14392\n\n**Key Technique:** Linear execution time model with **three-component decomposition**:\n\n```\nbatch_time = a + b * total_new_tokens + c * total_context\n```\n\nWhere:\n- `a` = fixed per-batch overhead\n- `b` = per-token processing cost (FFN, compute-bound)\n- `c` = per-context-unit KV access cost (attention, memory-bound)\n\n**Calibration:** Linear regression via automated testing framework that profiles runtime for each model-GPU combination. Achieves +/- 1.3% error, down from +/- 5.2% with naive token-only budgeting.\n\n**Critical Insight:** The `c * total_context` term is what captures KV cache effects. This is functionally equivalent to what BLIS's Round 2 tried with `kv_sum` features, but FairBatching uses **total context length across all requests in the batch** (sum of all KV cache lengths), not raw KV block counts. This three-coefficient linear model is much simpler than Ridge regression and achieves better accuracy.\n\n**Relevance to BLIS:** This is the most directly applicable step-time model. Your current model `beta0 + beta1*prefill + beta2*decode` is missing the `c * total_context` term. Adding a total_context_length feature (derivable from ProgressIndex across all batch requests) with proper coefficient fitting could dramatically improve step-time accuracy. **And it fits your Go integration path perfectly -- just add one coefficient.**\n\n---\n\n## 5. AIConfigurator (NVIDIA, Jan 2025)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2601.06288\n\n**Key Technique:** Operator-level decomposition + profiled database. Each inference step modeled as a fixed sequence of operators (GEMM, attention, AllReduce, MoE dispatch). Step latency = sum of constituent operator latencies queried from calibrated database.\n\n**TTFT Prediction:** \"TTFT is estimated based on the latency of the Mixed Phase, incorporating an empirical correction factor modeled as a piecewise linear function.\" For aggregated serving, TTFT = prefill phase latency + scheduling correction. A \"small offset (3 steps) to the mixed phase duration\" filters out scheduling jitter.\n\n**Accuracy:** TPOT 6-12% MAPE across dense and MoE. TTFT 16-22% MAPE overall, improving to 3.35% in practical operating regions.\n\n**Calibration:** ~30 GPU-hours of exhaustive profiling per platform-framework pair. Interpolation for intermediate configurations. Power-law correction for MoE expert load imbalance.\n\n**Relevance:** The \"empirical correction factor\" for TTFT and the \"3-step offset for scheduling jitter\" are simple but effective techniques. Your TTFT error likely needs something similar -- a correction factor that accounts for systematic scheduling delay.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Splitwise (Microsoft, 2023)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2311.18677\n\n**Key Technique:** Piecewise linear performance model built from hardware profiling.\n\n**Step Time Prediction:** \"A piecewise linear performance model using performance profiles at various batch sizes, input sizes, output sizes.\" MAPE <3% on train/test split. Profiled at various configurations on target hardware.\n\n**Key Finding:** \"TTFT for both models grows almost linearly as prompt size increases\" (compute-bound prefill). \"Throughput in the token phase keeps increasing with batching until 64 batch-size\" (memory-bound decode).\n\n**Relevance:** Confirms the piecewise-linear approach works well for step time. The key is profiling at enough configurations.\n\n---\n\n## 7. DistServe (2024)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2401.09670\n\n**Key Technique:** M/D/1 queuing model for TTFT prediction:\n\n```\nAvg_TTFT = D + (R * D^2) / (2 * (1 - R*D))\n```\n\nWhere D = constant execution time per request, R = Poisson arrival rate.\n\n**Key Insight:** TTFT = execution_time + queuing_delay. The queuing delay term `(R*D^2)/(2(1-R*D))` diverges as load approaches capacity (R*D -> 1). This is the classic M/D/1 result.\n\n**Step Time:** FLOPs + memory access analysis. Prefill is compute-bound; decode is memory-bound.\n\n**Accuracy:** <2% error in SLO attainment predictions across all tested configurations.\n\n**Relevance to BLIS:** This queuing formula is directly applicable to understanding your TTFT error. If BLIS's arrival patterns or load level (R*D) differs from reality, the queuing term can explode. A small mismatch in either arrival rate (R) or service time (D) near capacity causes massive TTFT divergence. **This could explain your 31,906% TTFT error** -- if BLIS operates near a different utilization point than reality, queuing delay diverges exponentially.\n\n---\n\n## 8. BiScale (2025)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2602.18755\n\n**Key Technique:** Histogram gradient boosting trees for batch completion time prediction.\n\n**Features:** (1) number of requests in batch, (2) sum/mean/std of input lengths, (3) TP degree, (4) GPU SM frequency.\n\n**Accuracy:** MAPE 2.9% for prefill instances, 2.7% for decode instances.\n\n**TTFT Derivation:** Simulates scheduling of waiting and running requests into N future batches, predicts batch completion times, derives projected TTFT for all active requests.\n\n**Relevance:** The feature set is instructive -- **sum, mean, and std of input lengths** rather than raw token counts. This aligns with FairBatching's `total_context` insight.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Block (Salesforce, 2025)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2508.03611\n\n**Key Technique:** Two-stage simulation (local scheduler simulator + linear execution time model) adapted from Vidur for load balancing decisions.\n\n**Step Time:** Linear models interpolating execution times from profiled operator-level data. Features: batch size, token count.\n\n**Accuracy:** 10-15% prediction error for end-to-end latency. Key finding: \"the 10-15% prediction error includes a constant overhead that uniformly impacts all instances\" -- so relative ranking is preserved even with absolute error.\n\n**Online Calibration:** When actual decoded lengths exceed predictions, dynamically adjusts by \"using the monitored decode length plus an additional 10 steps.\" This is a simple online correction.\n\n**Scheduling Overhead:** \"approximately 80 ms within capacity\" -- representing the difference between end-to-end client latency and vLLM-side execution time.\n\n**Relevance:** The 80ms scheduling overhead measurement is directly relevant -- this is the CPU overhead your `max(overhead, compute)` floor is capturing. The online calibration approach (adjust prediction based on observed vs expected) is simple and effective.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Sarathi-Serve (UIUC/Microsoft, OSDI 2024)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2403.02310\n\n**Key Technique:** Stall-free batching with configurable token budget (tau) to bound iteration time.\n\n**Step Time Model:** Bounded by token budget. Key insight: \"iterations with fewer prefill tokens have lower latency.\" By constraining total tokens per batch via token budget, iteration times become predictable and uniform.\n\n**Key Finding:** A single prefill of 4K tokens takes ~1150ms vs a batch-32 decode taking ~200ms. Chunked prefill bounds the worst case, making step times predictable.\n\n**TTFT Impact:** \"Decodes never experience a generation stall due to a co-running prefill chunk\" -- the scheduler prioritizes ongoing decodes first, then adds prefill chunks within the token budget.\n\n**Relevance:** This explains why your decode-only steps are well-predicted by the overhead floor -- they are bounded by the token budget. The mixed-batch variability comes from varying prefill chunk sizes.\n\n---\n\n## 11. LLMServingSim 2.0 (2025)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2602.23036\n\n**Key Technique:** Operator-level profiling using only a single decode block per model-device pair (~2.1 hours). Constructs execution DAGs encoding data dependencies, ordering constraints, parallelism, and communication.\n\n**Accuracy:** 0.85-1.59% error on aggregate metrics, 2.98-5.66% on time-series throughput. Average 0.97% error. Validated against vLLM on RTX A6000, H100, and TPU-v6e.\n\n**Relevance:** Shows that operator-level decomposition achieves sub-1% accuracy when the execution graph is properly modeled.\n\n---\n\n## 12. TokenSim (2025)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2503.08415\n\n**Key Technique:** Detailed transformer-oriented simulation model connecting batches to external compute simulators (GenZ) for timing.\n\n**Accuracy:** Geometric mean errors of 0.109% for throughput, 0.337-0.6% for P50/P99/max latency. Maintains sub-1% end-to-end error.\n\n**Key Finding About Competitors:** \"Existing simulators yield highly inaccurate performance metrics for dynamic LLM workloads due to their lack of batching support\" -- suggesting that the batching/scheduling simulation, not step-time prediction, is the dominant error source.\n\n---\n\n## Synthesis: Actionable Insights for BLIS\n\n### Root Cause of 31,906% TTFT Error\n\nBased on the literature, your TTFT error is almost certainly caused by **simulation-level fidelity issues**, not step-time prediction. Specific likely causes:\n\n1. **Arrival pattern mismatch:** If BLIS generates requests at a different rate/distribution than the real trace, the DistServe M/D/1 formula shows that queuing delay can diverge exponentially near capacity. Even a 10% arrival rate mismatch near saturation causes massive TTFT divergence.\n\n2. **Scheduler reimplementation divergence:** As Revati demonstrated, reimplemented schedulers inevitably diverge from real vLLM behavior. vLLM's scheduler has complex priority rules, KV allocation logic, and chunked prefill heuristics that are difficult to replicate exactly.\n\n3. **Request lifecycle mismatch:** The vLLM step pipeline (per the vLLM blog) is: schedule -> prepare inputs -> forward pass -> sample -> postprocess. BLIS may not model all these phases with the correct timing.\n\n### Recommended Step-Time Model (Immediate Win)\n\nBased on FairBatching's validated approach, the optimal step-time model for BLIS is:\n\n```\nstep_time = max(overhead, a + b * total_new_tokens + c * total_context)\n```\n\nWhere:\n- `overhead` = per-model constant (your existing values: 7B=3,897us, 34B=6,673us, 70B=8,029us, Mixtral=9,125us)\n- `a` = per-batch fixed cost\n- `b` = per-new-token cost (FFN/compute)\n- `c` = per-context-unit cost (attention/memory bandwidth)\n- `total_context` = sum of ProgressIndex across all requests in batch\n\nThis adds exactly ONE coefficient to your current model while capturing the KV cache effect properly. FairBatching achieved +/- 1.3% error with this formulation.\n\n### Recommended TTFT Fix (Primary Blocker)\n\nThe TTFT error requires investigation at the **simulation level**, not the step-time model level:\n\n1. **Compare arrival patterns:** Extract actual arrival timestamps from ground-truth data and compare to what BLIS generates. Any mismatch here propagates exponentially through queuing.\n\n2. **Compare batch formation:** Log BLIS's batch composition per step and compare to real vLLM logs. Differences in which requests are batched together (and when) directly cause TTFT divergence.\n\n3. **Add queuing delay correction:** Even a simple additive correction (like AIConfigurator's \"3-step offset for scheduling jitter\") could dramatically reduce TTFT error.\n\n4. **Check utilization mismatch:** Per DistServe's M/D/1 model, TTFT = D + RD^2 / (2(1-RD)). If BLIS runs at rho=0.95 while reality is at rho=0.7, the queuing term is 10x larger. Verify that BLIS and reality are at the same utilization level.\n\n### Per-Step Model Hierarchy (Literature Consensus)\n\n| Approach | Per-Step Error | E2E Error | Complexity |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 3-coefficient linear (FairBatching) | +/- 1.3% | N/A (scheduling-dependent) | Trivial |\n| Polynomial regression (HERMES) | 2.5% avg, <1% median | <6% | Low |\n| Piecewise linear profiling (Splitwise) | <3% | <2% SLO error | Low |\n| Random forest (Vidur) | <5% | <9% request-level | Medium |\n| Gradient boosting trees (BiScale) | 2.7-2.9% | N/A | Medium |\n| Operator-level DAG (LLMServingSim 2.0) | ~1% | 0.97% avg | High |\n| Time-warp (Revati) | <5% | <5% | Very High (requires real engine) |\n\n### Key Calibration Techniques from Literature\n\n1. **Online length adjustment (Block):** When actual decode length exceeds prediction, adjust by using monitored length + 10 steps. Simple, effective.\n\n2. **Operator profiling + RF interpolation (Vidur):** Profile operators at grid points, train RF to interpolate. ~150 profiling configurations per model-GPU pair.\n\n3. **Polynomial regression on 58K samples (HERMES):** Quadratic terms for prefill tokens capture the compute-bound scaling.\n\n4. **Histogram gradient boosting with summary statistics (BiScale):** Use sum/mean/std of sequence lengths as features instead of raw counts.\n\n5. **Token budget bounding (Sarathi):** Constraining total tokens per batch makes step times predictable by design.\n\n### What Would Close the Gap for BLIS\n\nThe path to <10% E2E error, informed by the literature:\n\n1. **Fix TTFT (Priority 1):** This requires simulator-level investigation, not ML. Compare BLIS's request arrival/scheduling/batch formation to ground truth. The 31,906% error is a simulation fidelity problem.\n\n2. **Add total_context to step-time model (Priority 2):** `step_time = max(overhead, a + b*new_tokens + c*total_context)` should get per-step to <5%.\n\n3. **Consider feature engineering from BiScale (Priority 3):** Use sum, mean, and std of sequence lengths as features. These capture batch composition effects better than raw token counts.\n\n4. **Avoid complex ML models (Priority 4):** The literature consistently shows that simple linear models (3-4 coefficients) achieve <3% per-step error. The error budget is consumed by simulation fidelity, not step-time model expressiveness. Your Round 2 finding that KV features in Ridge regression were counter-productive (+20.5pp worse) is consistent with this -- the features need proper formulation (total_context vs raw kv_sum), not more complex models."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ae29123 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 5135\ntool_uses: 55\nduration_ms: 886842</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6b183c99-f74b-427d-be1f-597eb641e46a","uuid":"773c4e6c-b21b-4aa7-931b-231a773e9a7c","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Search the web for recent papers and techniques on LLM inference latency prediction and simulator calibration. I need information on:\n\n1. **Vidur simulator** (Microsoft) - how it models step times, any calibration techniques\n2. **MIST** - LLM inference serving trace analysis\n3. **Splitwise / DistServe** - how they model inference latency\n4. **vLLM performance modeling** - any papers on predicting vLLM step times\n5. **Trace-driven simulation calibration** - techniques for calibrating DES simulators against real traces\n6. **TTFT prediction in LLM serving** - how systems predict time-to-first-token\n7. **Queueing theory for LLM inference** - M/G/1-PS models or similar for batch inference\n8. **Online calibration / Bayesian optimization for simulator tuning**\n9. **Sarathi, Orca** - batch scheduling and how they model iteration time\n10. **Any techniques for handling the gap between per-step prediction accuracy and end-to-end latency accuracy in simulators**\n\nFor each, provide:\n- Key technique/approach\n- How they handle step time prediction\n- How they handle TTFT prediction\n- Any calibration methodology\n- Relevance to our specific problem (31,906% TTFT error, 33.6% ITL error)\n\nSearch broadly and provide actionable insights.","agentId":"ae29123","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have comprehensive information. Let me compile the findings.\n\n---\n\n# Literature Survey: LLM Inference Latency Prediction and Simulator Calibration\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThis survey covers 12+ systems and papers relevant to BLIS's calibration challenges. The findings point to a clear diagnosis of your 31,906% TTFT error and 427.8% E2E error: **the dominant issue is almost certainly not step-time prediction but rather simulation-level fidelity (request lifecycle, scheduler reimplementation, arrival pattern matching)**. The state of the art has converged on a consistent set of techniques that achieve <5% E2E error. Below is each system's approach, ordered by relevance to your problem.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Revati (Microsoft/Georgia Tech, Jan 2025)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2601.00397\n\n**Key Technique:** \"Time-warp\" simulation — instead of reimplementing the scheduler, Revati intercepts CUDA API calls via LD_PRELOAD and runs the *actual* vLLM/SGLang control plane (scheduler, batch formation, KV cache manager). GPU compute calls become no-ops replaced by predicted durations.\n\n**Step Time Prediction:** Uses an analytical/ML runtime prediction layer accepting batch composition (prefill count, decode count, sequence lengths) and hardware specs. The key insight: \"GPU computation accounts for 90-95% of total execution time, with CPU overhead remaining minimal.\"\n\n**TTFT/ITL Accuracy:** <5% prediction error across TTFT and TPOT for Llama-3.1-8B, Llama-3.1-70B, and Qwen3-30B-A3B on both vLLM and SGLang. 5-17x faster than real GPU execution.\n\n**Calibration:** No explicit calibration needed -- by running the real control plane, scheduler behavior is captured automatically. Memory allocations under 4MB get real backing (for control decisions); compute buffers get virtual pointers.\n\n**Critical Insight for BLIS:** Revati's key finding is that **reimplemented schedulers diverge from real systems**. Vidur required only ~150 lines of code for the original vLLM scheduler but became untenable as vLLM evolved. The simulator maintenance burden causes subtle timing divergences that compound into large E2E errors. **This is the most likely explanation for your 31,906% TTFT error** -- BLIS's reimplemented request lifecycle (arrival, queueing, batch formation, prefill scheduling) diverges from real vLLM behavior.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Vidur (Microsoft Research, MLSys 2024)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2405.05465\n\n**Key Technique:** Operator-level profiling + random forest interpolation. Classifies operations into three categories:\n- **Token-level operators** (linear, activation): runtime depends on total tokens in batch\n- **Sequence-level operators** (attention): runtime depends on per-request context lengths\n- **Communication operators**: runtime depends only on data volume\n\n**Step Time Prediction:** Random forest (RF) regression models trained on profiled data. For prefill attention, cost is proportional to sum(p_i^2) where p_i = individual prefill lengths. For decode attention, runtime determined by total KV cache data volume (memory-bound). RF chosen for \"the right balance between data frugality and fidelity\" vs MLPs (need too much data) and polynomial regression (miss CUDA kernel nonlinearities).\n\n**TTFT/ITL Accuracy:**\n- Static workloads: P95 latency with up to 3.33% error\n- Dynamic workloads (85% capacity): <5% error in almost all scenarios\n- Overall: <9% error rate for request-level inference performance\n\n**Calibration:** Profile operators via CUPTI for different TP configurations on single GPU. ~150 lines of code to reimplement vLLM scheduler. Train small RF models to interpolate across input ranges.\n\n**Relevance:** Vidur achieves good accuracy but **only when the scheduler reimplementation is faithful**. As Revati noted, scheduler divergence is the Achilles heel. The RF approach for step-time prediction is solid and achieves <5% per-step, but step-time is not your binding constraint.\n\n---\n\n## 3. HERMES/MIST (Georgia Tech, Apr 2025)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2504.09775\n\n**Key Technique:** Multi-stage simulation framework with three layers (Workload, System/Software, Hardware). Uses ensemble regressors for step-time prediction.\n\n**Step Time Prediction:** Polynomial regression models:\n- **Decode:** Features = batch_size, past_token_count, TP config. MSE = 4.09e-07\n- **Prefill:** Features = past_token_count, prefill_token_count, batch_size, token^2 (quadratic term). MSE = 6.49e-05\n- Trained on 58K datapoints on DGX-H100 running vLLM with LLaMA2-70B\n\n**Accuracy:**\n- Per-step: 2.5% average error with <1% median\n- End-to-end: <2% error vs vLLM on H100 (aggregated-offline), 5.3% (aggregated-online at 5 QPS), <6% (disaggregated with Azure traces)\n\n**TTFT Model:** Modeled through discrete-event simulation incorporating queuing delays + execution times. Six pipeline stages (Preprocess, RAG, Prefill, Decode, KV Retrieval, Postprocess).\n\n**Key Insight:** \"End-to-end performance emerges from interactions across stages, across clients, and across layers -- not isolated operations.\" This validates that **per-step accuracy alone is insufficient**; the simulation of request flow is equally critical.\n\n---\n\n## 4. FairBatching (2025)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2510.14392\n\n**Key Technique:** Linear execution time model with **three-component decomposition**:\n\n```\nbatch_time = a + b * total_new_tokens + c * total_context\n```\n\nWhere:\n- `a` = fixed per-batch overhead\n- `b` = per-token processing cost (FFN, compute-bound)\n- `c` = per-context-unit KV access cost (attention, memory-bound)\n\n**Calibration:** Linear regression via automated testing framework that profiles runtime for each model-GPU combination. Achieves +/- 1.3% error, down from +/- 5.2% with naive token-only budgeting.\n\n**Critical Insight:** The `c * total_context` term is what captures KV cache effects. This is functionally equivalent to what BLIS's Round 2 tried with `kv_sum` features, but FairBatching uses **total context length across all requests in the batch** (sum of all KV cache lengths), not raw KV block counts. This three-coefficient linear model is much simpler than Ridge regression and achieves better accuracy.\n\n**Relevance to BLIS:** This is the most directly applicable step-time model. Your current model `beta0 + beta1*prefill + beta2*decode` is missing the `c * total_context` term. Adding a total_context_length feature (derivable from ProgressIndex across all batch requests) with proper coefficient fitting could dramatically improve step-time accuracy. **And it fits your Go integration path perfectly -- just add one coefficient.**\n\n---\n\n## 5. AIConfigurator (NVIDIA, Jan 2025)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2601.06288\n\n**Key Technique:** Operator-level decomposition + profiled database. Each inference step modeled as a fixed sequence of operators (GEMM, attention, AllReduce, MoE dispatch). Step latency = sum of constituent operator latencies queried from calibrated database.\n\n**TTFT Prediction:** \"TTFT is estimated based on the latency of the Mixed Phase, incorporating an empirical correction factor modeled as a piecewise linear function.\" For aggregated serving, TTFT = prefill phase latency + scheduling correction. A \"small offset (3 steps) to the mixed phase duration\" filters out scheduling jitter.\n\n**Accuracy:** TPOT 6-12% MAPE across dense and MoE. TTFT 16-22% MAPE overall, improving to 3.35% in practical operating regions.\n\n**Calibration:** ~30 GPU-hours of exhaustive profiling per platform-framework pair. Interpolation for intermediate configurations. Power-law correction for MoE expert load imbalance.\n\n**Relevance:** The \"empirical correction factor\" for TTFT and the \"3-step offset for scheduling jitter\" are simple but effective techniques. Your TTFT error likely needs something similar -- a correction factor that accounts for systematic scheduling delay.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Splitwise (Microsoft, 2023)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2311.18677\n\n**Key Technique:** Piecewise linear performance model built from hardware profiling.\n\n**Step Time Prediction:** \"A piecewise linear performance model using performance profiles at various batch sizes, input sizes, output sizes.\" MAPE <3% on train/test split. Profiled at various configurations on target hardware.\n\n**Key Finding:** \"TTFT for both models grows almost linearly as prompt size increases\" (compute-bound prefill). \"Throughput in the token phase keeps increasing with batching until 64 batch-size\" (memory-bound decode).\n\n**Relevance:** Confirms the piecewise-linear approach works well for step time. The key is profiling at enough configurations.\n\n---\n\n## 7. DistServe (2024)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2401.09670\n\n**Key Technique:** M/D/1 queuing model for TTFT prediction:\n\n```\nAvg_TTFT = D + (R * D^2) / (2 * (1 - R*D))\n```\n\nWhere D = constant execution time per request, R = Poisson arrival rate.\n\n**Key Insight:** TTFT = execution_time + queuing_delay. The queuing delay term `(R*D^2)/(2(1-R*D))` diverges as load approaches capacity (R*D -> 1). This is the classic M/D/1 result.\n\n**Step Time:** FLOPs + memory access analysis. Prefill is compute-bound; decode is memory-bound.\n\n**Accuracy:** <2% error in SLO attainment predictions across all tested configurations.\n\n**Relevance to BLIS:** This queuing formula is directly applicable to understanding your TTFT error. If BLIS's arrival patterns or load level (R*D) differs from reality, the queuing term can explode. A small mismatch in either arrival rate (R) or service time (D) near capacity causes massive TTFT divergence. **This could explain your 31,906% TTFT error** -- if BLIS operates near a different utilization point than reality, queuing delay diverges exponentially.\n\n---\n\n## 8. BiScale (2025)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2602.18755\n\n**Key Technique:** Histogram gradient boosting trees for batch completion time prediction.\n\n**Features:** (1) number of requests in batch, (2) sum/mean/std of input lengths, (3) TP degree, (4) GPU SM frequency.\n\n**Accuracy:** MAPE 2.9% for prefill instances, 2.7% for decode instances.\n\n**TTFT Derivation:** Simulates scheduling of waiting and running requests into N future batches, predicts batch completion times, derives projected TTFT for all active requests.\n\n**Relevance:** The feature set is instructive -- **sum, mean, and std of input lengths** rather than raw token counts. This aligns with FairBatching's `total_context` insight.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Block (Salesforce, 2025)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2508.03611\n\n**Key Technique:** Two-stage simulation (local scheduler simulator + linear execution time model) adapted from Vidur for load balancing decisions.\n\n**Step Time:** Linear models interpolating execution times from profiled operator-level data. Features: batch size, token count.\n\n**Accuracy:** 10-15% prediction error for end-to-end latency. Key finding: \"the 10-15% prediction error includes a constant overhead that uniformly impacts all instances\" -- so relative ranking is preserved even with absolute error.\n\n**Online Calibration:** When actual decoded lengths exceed predictions, dynamically adjusts by \"using the monitored decode length plus an additional 10 steps.\" This is a simple online correction.\n\n**Scheduling Overhead:** \"approximately 80 ms within capacity\" -- representing the difference between end-to-end client latency and vLLM-side execution time.\n\n**Relevance:** The 80ms scheduling overhead measurement is directly relevant -- this is the CPU overhead your `max(overhead, compute)` floor is capturing. The online calibration approach (adjust prediction based on observed vs expected) is simple and effective.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Sarathi-Serve (UIUC/Microsoft, OSDI 2024)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2403.02310\n\n**Key Technique:** Stall-free batching with configurable token budget (tau) to bound iteration time.\n\n**Step Time Model:** Bounded by token budget. Key insight: \"iterations with fewer prefill tokens have lower latency.\" By constraining total tokens per batch via token budget, iteration times become predictable and uniform.\n\n**Key Finding:** A single prefill of 4K tokens takes ~1150ms vs a batch-32 decode taking ~200ms. Chunked prefill bounds the worst case, making step times predictable.\n\n**TTFT Impact:** \"Decodes never experience a generation stall due to a co-running prefill chunk\" -- the scheduler prioritizes ongoing decodes first, then adds prefill chunks within the token budget.\n\n**Relevance:** This explains why your decode-only steps are well-predicted by the overhead floor -- they are bounded by the token budget. The mixed-batch variability comes from varying prefill chunk sizes.\n\n---\n\n## 11. LLMServingSim 2.0 (2025)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2602.23036\n\n**Key Technique:** Operator-level profiling using only a single decode block per model-device pair (~2.1 hours). Constructs execution DAGs encoding data dependencies, ordering constraints, parallelism, and communication.\n\n**Accuracy:** 0.85-1.59% error on aggregate metrics, 2.98-5.66% on time-series throughput. Average 0.97% error. Validated against vLLM on RTX A6000, H100, and TPU-v6e.\n\n**Relevance:** Shows that operator-level decomposition achieves sub-1% accuracy when the execution graph is properly modeled.\n\n---\n\n## 12. TokenSim (2025)\n\n**Source:** arXiv 2503.08415\n\n**Key Technique:** Detailed transformer-oriented simulation model connecting batches to external compute simulators (GenZ) for timing.\n\n**Accuracy:** Geometric mean errors of 0.109% for throughput, 0.337-0.6% for P50/P99/max latency. Maintains sub-1% end-to-end error.\n\n**Key Finding About Competitors:** \"Existing simulators yield highly inaccurate performance metrics for dynamic LLM workloads due to their lack of batching support\" -- suggesting that the batching/scheduling simulation, not step-time prediction, is the dominant error source.\n\n---\n\n## Synthesis: Actionable Insights for BLIS\n\n### Root Cause of 31,906% TTFT Error\n\nBased on the literature, your TTFT error is almost certainly caused by **simulation-level fidelity issues**, not step-time prediction. Specific likely causes:\n\n1. **Arrival pattern mismatch:** If BLIS generates requests at a different rate/distribution than the real trace, the DistServe M/D/1 formula shows that queuing delay can diverge exponentially near capacity. Even a 10% arrival rate mismatch near saturation causes massive TTFT divergence.\n\n2. **Scheduler reimplementation divergence:** As Revati demonstrated, reimplemented schedulers inevitably diverge from real vLLM behavior. vLLM's scheduler has complex priority rules, KV allocation logic, and chunked prefill heuristics that are difficult to replicate exactly.\n\n3. **Request lifecycle mismatch:** The vLLM step pipeline (per the vLLM blog) is: schedule -> prepare inputs -> forward pass -> sample -> postprocess. BLIS may not model all these phases with the correct timing.\n\n### Recommended Step-Time Model (Immediate Win)\n\nBased on FairBatching's validated approach, the optimal step-time model for BLIS is:\n\n```\nstep_time = max(overhead, a + b * total_new_tokens + c * total_context)\n```\n\nWhere:\n- `overhead` = per-model constant (your existing values: 7B=3,897us, 34B=6,673us, 70B=8,029us, Mixtral=9,125us)\n- `a` = per-batch fixed cost\n- `b` = per-new-token cost (FFN/compute)\n- `c` = per-context-unit cost (attention/memory bandwidth)\n- `total_context` = sum of ProgressIndex across all requests in batch\n\nThis adds exactly ONE coefficient to your current model while capturing the KV cache effect properly. FairBatching achieved +/- 1.3% error with this formulation.\n\n### Recommended TTFT Fix (Primary Blocker)\n\nThe TTFT error requires investigation at the **simulation level**, not the step-time model level:\n\n1. **Compare arrival patterns:** Extract actual arrival timestamps from ground-truth data and compare to what BLIS generates. Any mismatch here propagates exponentially through queuing.\n\n2. **Compare batch formation:** Log BLIS's batch composition per step and compare to real vLLM logs. Differences in which requests are batched together (and when) directly cause TTFT divergence.\n\n3. **Add queuing delay correction:** Even a simple additive correction (like AIConfigurator's \"3-step offset for scheduling jitter\") could dramatically reduce TTFT error.\n\n4. **Check utilization mismatch:** Per DistServe's M/D/1 model, TTFT = D + RD^2 / (2(1-RD)). If BLIS runs at rho=0.95 while reality is at rho=0.7, the queuing term is 10x larger. Verify that BLIS and reality are at the same utilization level.\n\n### Per-Step Model Hierarchy (Literature Consensus)\n\n| Approach | Per-Step Error | E2E Error | Complexity |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 3-coefficient linear (FairBatching) | +/- 1.3% | N/A (scheduling-dependent) | Trivial |\n| Polynomial regression (HERMES) | 2.5% avg, <1% median | <6% | Low |\n| Piecewise linear profiling (Splitwise) | <3% | <2% SLO error | Low |\n| Random forest (Vidur) | <5% | <9% request-level | Medium |\n| Gradient boosting trees (BiScale) | 2.7-2.9% | N/A | Medium |\n| Operator-level DAG (LLMServingSim 2.0) | ~1% | 0.97% avg | High |\n| Time-warp (Revati) | <5% | <5% | Very High (requires real engine) |\n\n### Key Calibration Techniques from Literature\n\n1. **Online length adjustment (Block):** When actual decode length exceeds prediction, adjust by using monitored length + 10 steps. Simple, effective.\n\n2. **Operator profiling + RF interpolation (Vidur):** Profile operators at grid points, train RF to interpolate. ~150 profiling configurations per model-GPU pair.\n\n3. **Polynomial regression on 58K samples (HERMES):** Quadratic terms for prefill tokens capture the compute-bound scaling.\n\n4. **Histogram gradient boosting with summary statistics (BiScale):** Use sum/mean/std of sequence lengths as features instead of raw counts.\n\n5. **Token budget bounding (Sarathi):** Constraining total tokens per batch makes step times predictable by design.\n\n### What Would Close the Gap for BLIS\n\nThe path to <10% E2E error, informed by the literature:\n\n1. **Fix TTFT (Priority 1):** This requires simulator-level investigation, not ML. Compare BLIS's request arrival/scheduling/batch formation to ground truth. The 31,906% error is a simulation fidelity problem.\n\n2. **Add total_context to step-time model (Priority 2):** `step_time = max(overhead, a + b*new_tokens + c*total_context)` should get per-step to <5%.\n\n3. **Consider feature engineering from BiScale (Priority 3):** Use sum, mean, and std of sequence lengths as features. These capture batch composition effects better than raw token counts.\n\n4. **Avoid complex ML models (Priority 4):** The literature consistently shows that simple linear models (3-4 coefficients) achieve <3% per-step error. The error budget is consumed by simulation fidelity, not step-time model expressiveness. Your Round 2 finding that KV features in Ridge regression were counter-productive (+20.5pp worse) is consistent with this -- the features need proper formulation (total_context vs raw kv_sum), not more complex models."}],"totalDurationMs":886842,"totalTokens":5135,"totalToolUseCount":55,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":5134,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
